WEBVTT

00:00:31.520 --> 00:00:39.360
The studio was filled with the rich odour of roses, and when the light summer winds

00:00:39.360 --> 00:00:45.420
stirred amidst the trees of the garden there came through the open door the heavy scent

00:00:45.420 --> 00:00:53.680
of the lilac, or the more delicate perfume of the pink flowering thorn. From the corner

00:00:53.680 --> 00:01:00.360
of the divan of Persian saddlebags on which he was lying, smoking, as usual, innumerable

00:01:00.360 --> 00:01:07.700
cigarettes, Lord Henry Wooten could just catch the gleam of the honey-sweet and honey-coloured

00:01:07.700 --> 00:01:14.380
blossoms of the laburnum, whose tremulous branches seemed hardly able to bear the burden

00:01:14.380 --> 00:01:22.280
of a beauty so flame-like as theirs. And now and then the fantastic shadows of birds in

00:01:22.280 --> 00:01:28.200
the light flitted across the long two-source silk curtains that were stretched in front

00:01:28.200 --> 00:01:36.240
of the huge window, producing a kind of momentary Japanese effect, and making him think of those

00:01:36.240 --> 00:01:43.020
pallid jade-faced painters who, in an art that is necessarily immobile, seek to convey

00:01:43.020 --> 00:01:49.740
the sense of swiftness and motion. The sullen murmur of the bees, shouldering their way

00:01:49.740 --> 00:01:56.000
through the long unmoaned grass, or circling with monotonous insistence round the black

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:02.280
crocketed spires of the early June hollyocks, seemed to make the stillness more oppressive,

00:02:02.660 --> 00:02:10.040
and the dim roar of London was like the burdened note of a distant organ. In the centre of

00:02:10.040 --> 00:02:16.200
the room, clamped to an upright easel, stood the full-length portrait of a young man of

00:02:16.200 --> 00:02:22.820
extraordinary personal beauty, and in front of it, some little distance away, was sitting

00:02:22.820 --> 00:02:28.480
the artist himself, Basil Hallward, whose sudden disappearance some years ago caused

00:02:28.480 --> 00:02:35.340
at the time some public excitement, and gave rise to so many strange conjectures.

00:02:37.400 --> 00:02:43.580
As he looked at the gracious and comely form he had so skilfully mirrored in his art, a

00:02:43.580 --> 00:02:49.700
smile of pleasure passed across his face, and seemed about to linger there, but he suddenly

00:02:49.700 --> 00:02:56.320
started up, and, closing his eyes, placed his fingers upon the lids as though he sought

00:02:56.320 --> 00:03:02.700
to imprison within his brain some curious dream from which he feared he might awake.

00:03:04.020 --> 00:03:11.340
"'It is your best work, Basil, the best thing you have ever done,' said Lord Harry languidly.

00:03:11.340 --> 00:03:17.400
"'You must certainly send it next year to the Grosvenor. The Academy is too large and

00:03:17.400 --> 00:03:22.580
too vulgar. The Grosvenor is the only place.'

00:03:22.580 --> 00:03:28.620
"'I don't think I will send it anywhere,' he answered, tossing his head back in the odd

00:03:28.620 --> 00:03:31.560
way that used to make his friends laugh at him at Oxford.

00:03:32.600 --> 00:03:36.740
"'No, I won't send it anywhere.'"

00:03:36.740 --> 00:03:41.760
Lord Henry elevated his eyebrows, and looked at him in amazement through the thin blue

00:03:41.760 --> 00:03:49.540
wreaths of smoke that curled up in such fanciful whorls from his heavy opium-tainted cigarette.

00:03:50.560 --> 00:03:59.700
"'Not send it anywhere? My dear fellow, why? Have you any reason? What odd chaps you painters

00:03:59.700 --> 00:04:04.660
are! You do anything in the world to gain a reputation. As soon as you have one you

00:04:04.660 --> 00:04:10.560
seem to want to throw it away. It is silly of you. For there is only one thing in the

00:04:10.560 --> 00:04:17.340
world worse than being talked about, and that is not being talked about. A portrait like

00:04:17.340 --> 00:04:22.560
this would set you far above all the young men in England, and make the old men quite

00:04:22.560 --> 00:04:27.380
jealous, if old men are ever capable of any emotion.'

00:04:28.800 --> 00:04:31.740
"'I know you will laugh at me,' he replied.

00:04:32.440 --> 00:04:39.120
"'But I really can't exhibit it. I've put too much of myself into it.'"

00:04:39.120 --> 00:04:44.260
Lord Henry stretched his long legs out on the divan and shook with laughter.

00:04:44.780 --> 00:04:50.100
"'Yes, I knew you would laugh. But it is quite true all the same.'

00:04:50.100 --> 00:04:57.140
"'Too much of yourself in it? Upon my word, Basil, I didn't know you were so vain, and

00:04:57.140 --> 00:05:02.040
I really can't see any resemblance between you, with your rugged strong face and cold

00:05:02.040 --> 00:05:08.080
black hair, and this young Adonis, who looks as if he was made of ivory and rose leaves.

00:05:08.560 --> 00:05:16.560
Why, my dear Basil, he is a Narcissus in you. Well, of course you have an intellectual expression

00:05:16.560 --> 00:05:24.160
and all that, but beauty, real beauty, ends where an intellectual expression begins. Intellect

00:05:24.160 --> 00:05:31.420
is in itself an exaggeration and destroys the harmony of any face. The moment one sits

00:05:31.420 --> 00:05:38.020
down to think, one becomes all nose or all forehead or something horrid. Look at the

00:05:38.020 --> 00:05:43.820
successful men in any of the learned professions. How perfectly hideous they are, except, of

00:05:43.820 --> 00:05:51.400
course, in the church. But then, in the church, they don't think. A bishop keeps on saying

00:05:51.400 --> 00:05:56.600
at the age of eighty what he was told to say when he was a boy of eighteen, and consequently

00:05:56.600 --> 00:06:03.280
he always looks absolutely delightful. Your mysterious friend, whose name you have never

00:06:03.280 --> 00:06:09.400
told me, but whose picture really fascinates me, never thinks. I feel quite sure about

00:06:09.400 --> 00:06:14.920
that. He is a brainless, beautiful thing, who should always be here in winter when we

00:06:14.920 --> 00:06:20.020
have no flowers to look at, and always here in summer when we want something to chill

00:06:20.020 --> 00:06:25.960
our intelligence. Don't flatter yourself, Buzzel. You are not in the least like him.

00:06:26.380 --> 00:06:33.600
You don't understand me, Harry. Of course I am not like him. I know that perfectly well.

00:06:34.500 --> 00:06:40.840
Indeed, I should be sorry to look like him. You shrug your shoulders. I'm telling you

00:06:40.840 --> 00:06:47.640
the truth. There is a fatality about all physical and intellectual distinction. The sort of

00:06:47.640 --> 00:06:53.420
fatality that seems to dog through history the faltering steps of kings. It is better

00:06:53.420 --> 00:06:59.080
not to be different from one's fellows. The ugly and the stupid have the best of it in

00:06:59.080 --> 00:07:04.640
this world. They can sit quietly and gape at the play. If they know nothing of victory,

00:07:04.700 --> 00:07:12.500
they are at least spared the knowledge of defeat. They live as we all should live, undisturbed

00:07:12.500 --> 00:07:19.140
and indifferent and without disquiet. They never bring ruin upon themselves, nor ever

00:07:19.140 --> 00:07:26.600
receive it from alien hands. Your rank and wealth, Harry, my brains, such as they are,

00:07:26.700 --> 00:07:34.180
my fame, whatever it may be worth, Dorian Gray's good looks, we will all suffer for

00:07:34.180 --> 00:07:42.480
what the gods have given us, suffer terribly. Dorian Gray is a great man, a great man,

00:07:42.500 --> 00:07:49.700
a great man. Is that his name? said Lord Henry, walking across the studio towards Basil-Hallwood.

00:07:51.580 --> 00:07:57.920
Yes, that is his name. I didn't intend to tell it to you. But why not? Oh, I can't

00:07:57.920 --> 00:08:04.500
explain. When I like people immensely I never tell their names to anyone. It seems like

00:08:04.500 --> 00:08:10.840
surrendering a part of them. You know how I love secrecy. It is the only thing that

00:08:10.840 --> 00:08:16.800
can make modern life wonderful or mysterious to us. The commonest thing is delightful if

00:08:16.800 --> 00:08:24.440
one only hides it. When I leave town I never tell any people where I am going. If I did

00:08:24.440 --> 00:08:32.740
I would lose all my pleasure. It is a silly habit, I dare say, but somehow it seems to

00:08:32.740 --> 00:08:38.420
bring a great deal of romance into one's life. I suppose you think me awfully foolish about

00:08:38.420 --> 00:08:38.780
it.

00:08:39.500 --> 00:08:46.180
Not at all, answered Lord Henry, laying his hand upon his shoulder. Not at all, my dear

00:08:46.180 --> 00:08:53.440
Basil. You seem to forget that I am married, and the one charm of marriage is that it makes

00:08:53.440 --> 00:08:59.580
a life of deception necessary for both parties. I never know where my wife is, and my wife

00:08:59.580 --> 00:09:05.600
never knows what I am doing. When we meet—we do meet occasionally when we dine together

00:09:05.600 --> 00:09:11.300
or go down to the dukes—we tell each other the most absurd stories with the most serious

00:09:11.300 --> 00:09:17.640
faces. My wife is very good at it—much better, in fact, than I am. She never gets confused

00:09:17.640 --> 00:09:23.120
over her dates, and I always do, but when she does find me out she makes no row at all.

00:09:23.720 --> 00:09:26.880
I sometimes wish she would, but she merely laughs at me.

00:09:28.320 --> 00:09:34.300
I hate the way you talk about your married life, Harry, said Basil Hallward, shaking

00:09:34.300 --> 00:09:40.600
his hand off and strolling towards the door that led into the garden. I believe you are

00:09:40.600 --> 00:09:46.220
really a very good husband, but that you are thoroughly ashamed of your own virtues. You

00:09:46.220 --> 00:09:52.860
are an extraordinary fellow. You never say a moral thing, and you never do a wrong thing.

00:09:53.080 --> 00:09:55.760
Your cynicism is simply a pose.

00:09:57.460 --> 00:10:00.340
Being natural is simply a pose.

00:10:01.040 --> 00:10:06.880
In the most irritating pose I know, cried Lord Henry, laughing, and the two men went

00:10:06.880 --> 00:10:11.860
out into the garden together, and for a time they did not speak.

00:10:13.340 --> 00:10:17.140
After a long pause, Lord Henry pulled out his watch.

00:10:18.140 --> 00:10:24.960
I'm afraid I must be going, Basil, he murmured, and before I go I insist on your answering

00:10:24.960 --> 00:10:27.200
a question I put to you some time ago.

00:10:28.180 --> 00:10:32.500
What is that? asked Basil Hallward, keeping his eyes fixed on the ground.

00:10:33.960 --> 00:10:37.160
You know quite well. I do not, Harry.

00:10:38.640 --> 00:10:47.660
Well, I will tell you what it is. Please don't. I must. I want you to explain to me why you

00:10:47.660 --> 00:10:51.940
won't exhibit Dorian Gray's picture. I want the real reason.

00:10:53.340 --> 00:11:00.940
I told you the real reason. No, you did not. You said it was because there was too much

00:11:00.940 --> 00:11:02.740
of yourself in it.

00:11:03.540 --> 00:11:05.000
Now that is childish.

00:11:06.580 --> 00:11:13.620
Harry, said Basil Hallward, looking at him straight in the face, every portrait that

00:11:13.620 --> 00:11:20.080
is painted with feeling is a portrait of the artist, not of the sitter. The sitter is merely

00:11:20.080 --> 00:11:27.520
the accident, the occasion. It is not he who is revealed by the painter. It is rather

00:11:27.520 --> 00:11:35.180
the painter who, on the coloured canvas, reveals himself that the reason I will not

00:11:35.180 --> 00:11:43.080
exhibit this picture is that I am afraid that I have shown with it the secret of my own

00:11:43.080 --> 00:11:43.500
soul.

00:11:44.720 --> 00:11:46.240
Lord Harry laughed.

00:11:48.640 --> 00:11:52.040
And what is that? he asked.

00:11:53.660 --> 00:11:59.220
I will tell you, said Hallward. An expression of perplexity came over his face.

00:12:00.460 --> 00:12:06.380
I am all expectation, Basil, murmured his companion, looking at him.

00:12:06.380 --> 00:12:13.380
Oh, there is really very little to tell, Harry, answered the young painter, and I am afraid

00:12:13.380 --> 00:12:18.380
you will hardly understand it. Perhaps you will hardly believe it.

00:12:19.420 --> 00:12:25.940
Lord Henry smiled and, leaning down, plucked a pink petal daisy from the grass and examined

00:12:25.940 --> 00:12:26.300
it.

00:12:26.960 --> 00:12:33.880
I am quite sure I shall understand it, he replied, gazing intently at the little golden

00:12:33.880 --> 00:12:39.740
white feathered disc, and I can believe anything, provided that it is incredible.

00:12:41.260 --> 00:12:47.320
The wind shook some blossoms from the trees, and the heavy lilac blooms, with their clustering

00:12:47.640 --> 00:12:54.120
stars, moved to and fro in the languid air. A grasshopper began to chirp in the grass,

00:12:54.560 --> 00:12:59.740
and a long thin dragonfly floated by on its own brown gauze wings.

00:13:00.380 --> 00:13:06.120
Lord Henry felt as if he could hear Basil Hallward's heart beating, and wondered what

00:13:06.120 --> 00:13:06.760
was coming.

00:13:10.340 --> 00:13:17.040
Well, this is incredible, repeated Hallward rather bitterly.

00:13:17.780 --> 00:13:26.100
Incredible to me at times. I don't know what it means. The story is simply this. Two months

00:13:26.100 --> 00:13:31.840
ago I went to a crush at Lady Brandon's. You know we poor painters have to show ourselves

00:13:31.840 --> 00:13:38.560
in society from time to time, just to remind the public that we are not savages. With an

00:13:38.560 --> 00:13:44.320
evening coat and a white tie, as you once told me anybody, even a stockbroker can gain

00:13:44.320 --> 00:13:46.640
a reputation for being civilized.

00:13:48.380 --> 00:13:54.500
Well, after I'd been in the room about ten minutes, talking to huge overdressed dowagers

00:13:54.500 --> 00:14:02.560
and tedious academicians, I suddenly became conscious that someone was looking at me.

00:14:03.120 --> 00:14:11.860
I turned half way round and saw Dorian Gray for the first time. When our eyes met I felt

00:14:11.860 --> 00:14:20.340
that I was growing pale. A curious instinct of terror came over me. I knew that I had

00:14:20.340 --> 00:14:26.360
come face to face with someone whose mere personality was so fascinating that, if I

00:14:26.360 --> 00:14:32.060
allowed it to do so, it would absorb my whole nature, my whole soul, my very art itself.

00:14:33.920 --> 00:14:40.800
I did not want any external influence in my life. You know yourself, Harry, how independent

00:14:40.800 --> 00:14:47.860
I am by nature. My father destined me for the army. I insisted on going to Oxford. Then

00:14:47.860 --> 00:14:53.540
he made me enter my name at the Middle Temple. Before I'd eaten half a dozen dinners I gave

00:14:53.540 --> 00:15:00.020
up the bar and announced my intention of becoming a painter. I've always been my own master.

00:15:01.280 --> 00:15:10.380
Had at least always been so till I met Dorian Gray. And then—but I don't know how to explain

00:15:10.380 --> 00:15:17.840
it to you—something seemed to tell me that I was on the verge of a terrible crisis in

00:15:17.860 --> 00:15:25.180
my life. I had a strange feeling that fate had in store for me exquisite joys and exquisite

00:15:25.180 --> 00:15:33.480
sorrows. I knew that if I had spoke to Dorian I would become absolutely devoted to him.

00:15:34.420 --> 00:15:41.660
And that I ought not to speak to him, I grew afraid, and turned to quit the room. It was

00:15:41.660 --> 00:15:46.900
not conscience that made me do so. It was cowardice. I take no credit to myself for

00:15:46.900 --> 00:15:47.780
trying to escape.

00:15:50.040 --> 00:15:56.160
Conscience and cowardice are really the same things, Basil. Conscience is the trade name

00:15:56.160 --> 00:16:05.060
of the firm, that is all. I don't believe that, Harry. However, whatever my motive—and

00:16:05.060 --> 00:16:10.880
it may have been pride, for I used to be very proud, I certainly struggled to the door—there,

00:16:10.880 --> 00:16:14.800
of course, I stumbled against Lady Brandon.

00:16:15.560 --> 00:16:22.260
"'You are not going to run away so soon, Mr. Hallward,' she screamed out. You know

00:16:22.260 --> 00:16:24.800
her shrill, horrid voice.

00:16:25.660 --> 00:16:32.740
"'Yes, she is a peacock in everything but beauty,' said Lord Henry, pulling the daisy

00:16:32.740 --> 00:16:40.080
to bits with his long, nervous fingers. I could not get rid of her. She brought me up

00:16:40.080 --> 00:16:45.720
to her royalties, and people with stars and garters, and elderly ladies with gigantic

00:16:45.720 --> 00:16:52.720
tiaras and hooked noses. She spoke of me as her dearest friend. I had only met her once

00:16:52.720 --> 00:17:00.060
before, but she took it into her head to lionize me. I believe some picture of mine had made

00:17:00.060 --> 00:17:04.460
a great success at the time, at least had been chatted about in the penny newspapers,

00:17:04.460 --> 00:17:12.720
which is the nineteenth-century standard of immortality. Suddenly I found myself face

00:17:12.720 --> 00:17:18.540
to face with a young man whose personality had so strangely stirred me. We were quite

00:17:18.540 --> 00:17:27.380
close, almost touching. Our eyes met again. It was mad of me, but I asked Lady Brandon

00:17:27.380 --> 00:17:34.440
to introduce me to him. Perhaps it was not so mad, after all. It was simply inevitable.

00:17:35.140 --> 00:17:40.180
We would have spoken to each other without any introduction, I'm sure of that. Dorian

00:17:40.180 --> 00:17:45.900
told me so afterwards. He, too, felt that we were destined to know each other."

00:17:45.900 --> 00:17:53.560
"'And how did Lady Brandon describe this wonderful young man? I know she goes in for giving rapid

00:17:53.560 --> 00:18:00.160
precess of all her guests. I remember her bringing me to a most truculent and red-faced

00:18:00.160 --> 00:18:06.480
gentleman, covered all over with orders and ribbons and hissing into my ear and a tragic

00:18:06.480 --> 00:18:11.600
whisper which must have been perfectly audible to every one in the room, something like,

00:18:12.300 --> 00:18:18.720
"'Sir Humpty Dumpty, you know, Afghan frontier, Russian intrigues, very successful man, wife

00:18:18.720 --> 00:18:23.960
killed by an elephant, quite inconsolable, wants to marry a beautiful American widow,

00:18:23.960 --> 00:18:30.420
who everybody does nowadays, hates Mr. Gladstone, but very much interested in beetles. Ask him

00:18:30.420 --> 00:18:37.340
what he thinks of Shouvalov." I simply fled. I like to find out people for

00:18:37.340 --> 00:18:43.060
myself, but Lady Brandon treats her guests exactly as an auctioneer treats his goods.

00:18:43.600 --> 00:18:48.360
She either explains them entirely away or tells everyone everything about them except

00:18:48.360 --> 00:18:54.020
what one wants to know. But what did she say about Mr. Dorian Gray?

00:18:56.680 --> 00:19:03.560
"'Oh,' she murmured, "'charming boy, poor dear mother and I, quite inseparable, engaged

00:19:03.560 --> 00:19:10.420
to be married to the same man—I mean married on the same day. How very silly of me! I forget

00:19:10.420 --> 00:19:17.260
what he does. Afraid he doesn't do anything. Yes, yes, plays the piano. Or is it the violin,

00:19:17.260 --> 00:19:22.720
dear Mr. Gray? We could neither of us help laughing, and we became friends at once.'

00:19:23.920 --> 00:19:30.140
"'Laughter is not a bad beginning for a friendship, and it is the best ending for one,' said Lord

00:19:30.140 --> 00:19:36.180
Henry, plucking another daisy. Hallward buried his face in his hands.

00:19:36.980 --> 00:19:42.640
"'You don't understand what friendship is, Harry,' he murmured, "'or what enmity is,

00:19:42.640 --> 00:19:48.720
for that matter. You like everyone.' That is to say you are indifferent to everyone.'

00:19:49.520 --> 00:19:55.980
"'How horribly unjust of you!' cried Lord Henry, tilting his hat back and looking at

00:19:55.980 --> 00:20:01.360
the little clouds that were drifting across the hollowed turquoise of the summer sky like

00:20:01.360 --> 00:20:09.100
raveled skeins of glossy white silk. "'Yes, horribly unjust of you. I make a great

00:20:09.100 --> 00:20:14.080
difference between people. I choose my friends for their good looks, my acquaintances for

00:20:14.080 --> 00:20:20.720
their characters, and my enemies for their brains. A man can't be too careful in the

00:20:20.720 --> 00:20:26.780
choice of his enemies. I have not got one who is a fool. They are all men of some intellectual

00:20:26.780 --> 00:20:38.300
power, and consequently they all appreciate me. Is that very vain of me? I think it is

00:20:38.300 --> 00:20:43.420
very. But according to your category I must merely be an acquaintance.'

00:20:44.880 --> 00:20:50.440
"'My dear old Basil, you are much more than an acquaintance.'

00:20:52.380 --> 00:20:59.620
"'And much less a friend, a sort of brother, I suppose. Oh, brothers! I don't care for

00:20:59.620 --> 00:21:03.960
brothers. My elder brother won't die, and my younger brothers seem never to do anything

00:21:03.960 --> 00:21:11.720
else. Harry, my dear fellow, I am not quite serious, but I can't help detesting my relations.

00:21:12.460 --> 00:21:16.820
I suppose it comes from the fact that we can't stand other people having the same faults

00:21:16.820 --> 00:21:23.080
as ourselves. I quite sympathise with the rage of the English democracy against what

00:21:23.080 --> 00:21:29.360
they call the vices of the upper classes. They feel that drunkenness, stupidity, and

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:35.800
immorality should be their own special property, and that if any one of us makes an ass of

00:21:35.800 --> 00:21:43.480
himself he is poaching on their preserves. When poor Southwark got into the divorce court

00:21:43.480 --> 00:21:49.360
their indignation was quite magnificent. Yet I don't suppose that ten per cent of the lower

00:21:49.360 --> 00:21:50.520
orders live correctly.'

00:21:52.460 --> 00:21:58.160
"'I don't agree with a single word that you have said. And what is more, Harry, I don't

00:21:58.160 --> 00:22:05.860
believe you do either.' Lord Henry stroked his pointed brown beard and tapped the toe

00:22:05.860 --> 00:22:09.340
of his patent-leather boot with a tasseled malaca cane.

00:22:10.860 --> 00:22:14.340
"'How English you are, Basil!'

00:22:14.700 --> 00:22:22.380
If one puts forward an idea to a real Englishman—always a rash thing to do—he never dreams of considering

00:22:22.380 --> 00:22:27.740
whether the idea is right or wrong. The only thing he considers of any importance is whether

00:22:27.740 --> 00:22:34.140
he believes it oneself. Now, the value of an idea has nothing whatsoever to do with

00:22:34.140 --> 00:22:40.100
the sincerity of the man who expresses it. Indeed, the probabilities are that the more

00:22:40.100 --> 00:22:47.660
insincere the man is, the more purely intellectual will the idea be, as in that case it will

00:22:47.660 --> 00:22:55.340
not be coloured by either his wants, his desires, or his prejudices. However, I don't propose

00:22:55.340 --> 00:23:02.040
to discuss politics, sociology, or metaphysics with you. I like persons better than principals.

00:23:02.580 --> 00:23:08.860
Tell me more about Dorian Gray. How often do you see him?'

00:23:08.860 --> 00:23:09.940
"'Every day.'

00:23:10.700 --> 00:23:15.460
"'I couldn't be happy if I didn't see him every day. Of course sometimes it's only for

00:23:15.460 --> 00:23:20.720
a few minutes, but a few minutes with somebody one worships means a great deal.'

00:23:21.760 --> 00:23:24.860
"'You don't really worship him?'

00:23:26.680 --> 00:23:27.800
"'I do.'

00:23:27.800 --> 00:23:34.660
"'How extraordinary! I thought you would never care for anything but your painting—your

00:23:34.660 --> 00:23:43.780
art, I should say. Art sounds better, doesn't it? He is all my art to me now. I think sometimes

00:23:43.780 --> 00:23:49.820
Harry that there are only two areas of importance in the history of the world. The first is

00:23:49.820 --> 00:23:56.380
the appearance of a new medium of art, and the second is the appearance of a new personality

00:23:56.380 --> 00:24:03.320
for art also. What the invention of oil painting was to the Venetians, the face of Antinous

00:24:03.320 --> 00:24:09.920
was to late Greek sculpture, and the face of Dorian Gray will some day be to me. It

00:24:09.920 --> 00:24:15.700
is not merely that I paint from him, draw from him, model from him. Of course I've done

00:24:15.700 --> 00:24:22.780
all that. He has stood as Paris in dainty armour, as Adonis with Huntsman cloak and

00:24:22.780 --> 00:24:30.120
polished boar spear. Crowned with heavy lotus-blossoms he has sat on the prow of Adrian's barge

00:24:30.120 --> 00:24:37.440
looking into the green turbid Nile. He has leaned over the still pool of some Greek woodland

00:24:37.440 --> 00:24:43.040
and seen in the water's silent silver the wonder of his own beauty. But he is much more

00:24:43.040 --> 00:24:48.460
important to me than that. I won't tell you that I am dissatisfied with what I have done

00:24:48.460 --> 00:24:53.120
of him, or that his beauty is such that art cannot express it. There is nothing that art

00:24:53.120 --> 00:24:59.480
cannot express. And I know that the work I have done since I met Dorian Gray is good

00:24:59.480 --> 00:25:09.060
work. It is the best work of my life. But in some curious way, I wonder, will you understand

00:25:09.060 --> 00:25:18.660
me? His personality has suggested to me an entirely new manner in art, an entirely new

00:25:18.660 --> 00:25:26.480
mode of style. I see things differently. I think of them differently. I can now recreate

00:25:26.480 --> 00:25:39.040
life in a way that was hidden from me before. A dream of form in days of thought. Who is

00:25:39.040 --> 00:25:45.720
it to me? The merely visible presence of this lad, for he seems to me little more

00:25:45.720 --> 00:25:53.420
than a lad, though he is really over twenty, his merely visible presence. I wonder, can

00:25:53.420 --> 00:26:01.760
you realize all that that means? Unconsciously he defines for me the lines of a fresh school,

00:26:02.280 --> 00:26:08.700
a school that is to have in itself all the passion of the Romantic spirit, all the perfection

00:26:08.700 --> 00:26:15.280
of the spirit that is Greek, the harmony of soul and body. How much that is! We in our

00:26:15.280 --> 00:26:23.360
madness have separated the two and have invented a realism that is bestial, an ideality that

00:26:23.360 --> 00:26:29.900
is void. Harry, if you only knew what Dorian Gray is to me, you remember that landscape

00:26:29.900 --> 00:26:35.560
of mine, for which Agnew offered me such a huge price, but which I would not part with.

00:26:36.180 --> 00:26:40.960
It is one of the best things I've ever done, and why is it so? Because while I was painting

00:26:40.960 --> 00:26:44.340
it Dorian Gray sat beside me.

00:26:44.860 --> 00:26:47.660
Bessel, that is quite wonderful.

00:26:49.120 --> 00:26:51.320
I must see Dorian Gray.

00:26:52.340 --> 00:26:57.720
Collward got up from his seat and walked up and down the garden. After some time he came

00:26:57.720 --> 00:26:58.060
back.

00:26:59.060 --> 00:27:07.300
You don't understand, Harry, he said. Dorian Gray is merely to me a motive in art. He is

00:27:07.300 --> 00:27:12.960
never more present in my work than when no image of him is there. He is simply a suggestion,

00:27:12.960 --> 00:27:19.700
as I have said, of a new manner. I see him in the curves of certain lines, in the loveliness

00:27:19.700 --> 00:27:22.340
and subtleties of certain colours, that is all.

00:27:23.440 --> 00:27:31.120
Then why won't you exhibit his portrait? Because I have put into it all the extraordinary romance

00:27:31.120 --> 00:27:37.380
of which, of course, I have never dared to speak to him. He knows nothing about it. He

00:27:37.380 --> 00:27:43.400
will never know anything about it, but the world might guess it. And I will not bear

00:27:43.400 --> 00:27:50.720
my soul to their shallow prying eyes. My heart shall never be put under their microscope.

00:27:50.720 --> 00:27:55.580
There is too much of myself in that thing, Harry, too much of myself.

00:27:57.800 --> 00:28:03.560
Poets are not so scrupulous as you are. They know how useful passion is for publication.

00:28:04.540 --> 00:28:13.080
Nowadays, broken heart will run to many editions. I hate them for it. An artist should create

00:28:13.080 --> 00:28:18.960
beautiful things, but should put nothing of his own life into them. We live in an age

00:28:19.300 --> 00:28:26.080
where men treat art as if it were meant to be a form of autobiography. We have lost the

00:28:26.080 --> 00:28:33.260
abstract sense of beauty. If I live, I will show the world what it is, and for that reason

00:28:33.260 --> 00:28:36.560
the world shall never see my portrait of Dorian Gray.

00:28:37.740 --> 00:28:43.700
I think you are wrong, Basil, and I won't argue with you. It is only the intellectually

00:28:43.700 --> 00:28:52.320
lost who ever argue. Tell me, is Dorian Gray very fond of you? Hallward considered for

00:28:52.320 --> 00:28:53.180
a few moments.

00:28:55.620 --> 00:29:03.860
He likes me, he answered after a pause. I know he likes me. Of course I flatter him

00:29:03.860 --> 00:29:09.720
dreadfully. I find a pleasure in saying things to him that I know I shall be sorry for having

00:29:09.720 --> 00:29:15.680
said. I give myself away. As a rule he is charming to me, and we walk home together

00:29:15.680 --> 00:29:21.520
from the club arm in arm, or sit in the studio and talk of a thousand things. Now and then,

00:29:21.520 --> 00:29:27.060
however, he is horribly thoughtless. It seems to take a real delight in giving me pain.

00:29:28.100 --> 00:29:33.300
Then I feel, Harry, that I've given away my whole soul to someone who treats it as if

00:29:33.300 --> 00:29:39.680
it were a flower to put in his coat, a bit of decoration to charm his vanity, an ornament

00:29:39.680 --> 00:29:40.920
for a summer's day.

00:29:42.620 --> 00:29:49.820
Days in summer, Basil, are apt to linger. Perhaps you will tire sooner than he will.

00:29:49.860 --> 00:29:55.760
It is a sad thing to think of, but there is no doubt that genius lasts longer than beauty.

00:29:56.700 --> 00:30:02.280
That accounts for the fact that we all take such pains to over-educate ourselves in the

00:30:02.280 --> 00:30:09.080
wild struggle for existence. We want to have something that endures. And so we fill our

00:30:09.080 --> 00:30:12.880
minds with rubbish and facts and the silly hope of keeping our place.

00:30:14.420 --> 00:30:21.060
The thoroughly well-informed man, that is the modern ideal. And the mind of the thoroughly

00:30:21.060 --> 00:30:27.560
well-informed man is a dreadful thing. It's like a bric-a-brac shop, all monsters and

00:30:27.560 --> 00:30:34.840
everything priced above its proper value. I think you will tire first, all the same.

00:30:36.040 --> 00:30:42.280
Some day you will look a-gray, and he will seem to you to be a little out of drawing,

00:30:42.900 --> 00:30:48.840
or you won't like his tone of colour or something. You will bitterly reproach him in your own

00:30:48.840 --> 00:30:53.760
heart, seriously think that he has behaved very badly to you. Next time he calls, you

00:30:53.760 --> 00:30:59.500
will be perfectly cold and indifferent. It will be a great pity, for it will alter you.

00:31:00.120 --> 00:31:05.340
The worst of having a romance is that it leaves one so unromantic.

00:31:06.580 --> 00:31:11.900
Harry, don't talk like that. As long as I live the personality of Dorian Gray will dominate

00:31:11.900 --> 00:31:12.680
me.

00:31:13.800 --> 00:31:19.920
You can't feel what I feel. You change too often. Oh, my dear Basil, that is exactly

00:31:19.920 --> 00:31:27.120
why I can feel it. Those who are faithful know only the pleasures of love. It is the

00:31:27.120 --> 00:31:29.900
faithless who know love's tragedies.

00:31:31.620 --> 00:31:37.740
And Lord Henry struck a light on a dainty silver case, and began to smoke a cigarette

00:31:37.740 --> 00:31:43.480
with a self-conscious and self-satisfied air, as if he had summed up life in a phrase.

00:31:44.040 --> 00:31:50.320
There was a rustle of chirping sparrows in the ivy, and the blue cloud-shadows chased

00:31:50.320 --> 00:31:57.200
themselves across the grass-like swallows. How pleasant it was in the garden, and how

00:31:57.200 --> 00:32:02.100
delightful other people's emotions were. Much more delightful than their ideas, it seemed

00:32:02.100 --> 00:32:04.220
to be fascinating things in life.

00:32:18.400 --> 00:32:25.160
One's own soul and the passions of one's friends, those were the fascinating things in life.

00:32:25.840 --> 00:32:31.760
He thought with pleasure of the tedious luncheon that he had missed by staying so long with

00:32:31.760 --> 00:32:34.200
Basil Hallward. Had he gone to it, he would have been in a state of ecstasy, and he would

00:32:34.880 --> 00:32:40.660
have been sure to meet Lord Goodbody there, and the whole conversation would have been

00:32:40.660 --> 00:32:48.380
about the housing of the poor, and the necessity of model lodging houses. It was charming to

00:32:48.380 --> 00:32:55.060
have escaped all that. As he thought of his aunt, an idea seemed to strike him. He turned

00:32:55.060 --> 00:32:58.820
to Hallward and said, My dear fellow, I've just remembered.

00:32:59.980 --> 00:33:01.160
Remembered what, Harry?

00:33:02.400 --> 00:33:05.260
Where I heard the name of Dorian Gray.

00:33:07.040 --> 00:33:10.500
Where was it? asked Hallward with a slight frown.

00:33:11.000 --> 00:33:17.380
Oh, don't look so angry, Basil. It was at my aunt's, Lady Agatha's. She told me she

00:33:17.380 --> 00:33:22.660
had discovered a wonderful young man who was going to help her in the East End, and that

00:33:22.660 --> 00:33:29.740
his name was Dorian Gray. I'm bound to state that she never told me he was good-looking.

00:33:30.460 --> 00:33:36.460
Women have no appreciation of good looks, at least good women have not. She said that

00:33:36.460 --> 00:33:42.480
he was very earnest and had a beautiful nature. I had once pictured myself a creature with

00:33:42.480 --> 00:33:49.820
spectacles and lank hair, horribly freckled and tramping about on huge feet. I wish I

00:33:49.820 --> 00:33:51.340
had known it was your friend.

00:33:52.080 --> 00:33:54.580
I'm very glad you didn't, Harry. Why?

00:33:55.520 --> 00:33:57.280
I don't want you to meet him.

00:33:57.880 --> 00:34:04.420
Mr. Dorian Gray is in the studio, sir, said the butler, coming into the garden.

00:34:04.960 --> 00:34:10.080
You must introduce me now, cried Lord Henry, laughing.

00:34:11.520 --> 00:34:15.460
Basil Hallward turned to the servant, who stood blinking in the sunlight.

00:34:16.380 --> 00:34:20.320
Ask Mr. Gray to wait, Parker. I'll be in in a few moments.

00:34:20.940 --> 00:34:22.860
The man bowed and went up the walk.

00:34:24.700 --> 00:34:26.380
Then he looked at Lord Henry.

00:34:27.820 --> 00:34:36.300
Dorian Gray is my dearest friend, he said. He has a simple and beautiful nature. Your

00:34:36.300 --> 00:34:42.720
aunt was quite right in what she said of him. Don't spoil him for me. Don't try to influence

00:34:42.720 --> 00:34:48.980
him. Your influence would be bad. The world is wide and has many marvellous people, and

00:34:48.980 --> 00:34:55.760
it don't take away from me the one person that makes life absolutely lovely to me, and

00:34:55.760 --> 00:35:04.000
that gives to my art whatever wonder or charm it possesses. Mind, Harry, I trust you.

00:35:04.560 --> 00:35:10.840
He spoke very slowly, and the words seemed wrung out if I'm almost against his will.

00:35:11.480 --> 00:35:21.100
What nonsense you talk, said Lord Henry, smiling, and, taking Hallward by the arm, he almost

00:35:21.100 --> 00:35:23.100
led him into the house.

00:35:27.220 --> 00:35:30.960
Of the picture of Dorian Gray by Oscar Wilde

00:35:47.507 --> 00:35:50.207
THE PICTURE OF DORIAN GREY

00:35:50.967 --> 00:35:52.027
By Oscar Wilde

00:35:55.507 --> 00:35:58.147
www.jongon.com

00:36:02.047 --> 00:36:09.787
As they entered they saw Dorian Gray. He was seated at the piano with his back to them,

00:36:09.787 --> 00:36:14.287
turning over the pages of a volume of Schumann's Forest Scenes.

00:36:15.727 --> 00:36:20.907
"'You must lend me these, Basil,' he cried. I want to learn them. They are perfectly

00:36:21.807 --> 00:36:22.367
charming."

00:36:22.367 --> 00:36:25.867
"'That entirely depends on how you sit to-day, Dorian.'

00:36:25.867 --> 00:36:27.787
"'Oh, I'm tired of sitting.'

00:36:28.747 --> 00:36:32.947
"'And I don't want a life-size portrait of myself,' answered the lad, swinging around

00:36:32.947 --> 00:36:38.587
on the music-stool in a willful, petulant manner. When he got sight of Lord Henry, a

00:36:38.587 --> 00:36:44.267
faint blush coloured his cheeks for a moment, and he started up. I beg your pardon, Basil,

00:36:44.787 --> 00:36:52.087
but I didn't know you had any one with you. This is Lord Henry Wooten, Dorian, an old Oxford

00:36:52.087 --> 00:36:56.987
friend of mine. I've just been telling him what a capital sitter you were, and now you've

00:36:56.987 --> 00:36:57.707
spoiled everything.'

00:36:59.347 --> 00:37:05.047
"'You have not spoiled my pleasure in meeting you, Mr. Gray,' said Lord Henry, stepping

00:37:05.047 --> 00:37:10.387
forward and shaking him by the hand. My aunt has often spoken to me about you. You are

00:37:10.387 --> 00:37:15.767
one of her favourites, and, I am afraid, one of her victims, too.'

00:37:16.367 --> 00:37:21.847
"'I am in Lady Agatha's black books at present,' answered Dorian, with a funny look of penance.

00:37:23.187 --> 00:37:28.567
"'I promised to go to her club in Whitechapel with her last Tuesday, and I really forgot

00:37:28.567 --> 00:37:34.147
all about it. We were to have played a duet together—three duets, I believe. I don't

00:37:34.147 --> 00:37:39.267
know what she will say to me. I'm far too frightened a call.'

00:37:40.127 --> 00:37:45.547
"'Oh, I will make your peace with my aunt. She is quite devoted to you, and I don't think

00:37:45.547 --> 00:37:50.327
it really matters about your not being there. The audience probably thought it was a duet.

00:37:50.547 --> 00:37:56.687
When Aunt Agatha sits down to the piano, she makes quite enough noise for two people.'

00:37:57.647 --> 00:38:03.987
"'That is very horrid to her, and not very nice to me,' answered Dorian, laughing. Lord

00:38:03.987 --> 00:38:10.127
Henry looked at him. Yes, he was certainly wonderfully handsome, with his finely curved

00:38:10.127 --> 00:38:16.187
scarlet lips, his frank blue eyes, his crisp gold hair. There was something in his face

00:38:16.187 --> 00:38:23.387
that made one trust him at once. All the candour of youth was there, as well as all youth's

00:38:23.387 --> 00:38:30.667
passionate purity. One felt that he had kept himself unspotted from the world. No wonder

00:38:30.667 --> 00:38:35.907
Basil Hallward worshipped him. He was made to be worshipped.'

00:38:37.247 --> 00:38:44.267
"'You're too charming to go into philanthropy, Mr. Grey—far too charming.' And Lord Henry

00:38:44.267 --> 00:38:50.687
flung himself down on the divan and opened his cigarette-case. Hallward had been busy

00:38:50.687 --> 00:38:58.847
mixing his colours and getting his brushes ready. He was looking worried, and when he

00:38:58.847 --> 00:39:01.887
glanced at him hesitated for a moment, and then said,

00:39:03.047 --> 00:39:09.047
"'Hurry, I want to finish this picture to-day. Would you think it awfully rude of me if I

00:39:09.047 --> 00:39:15.747
asked you to go away?' Lord Henry smiled and looked at Dorian Grey.

00:39:16.747 --> 00:39:20.727
"'Am I to go, Mr. Grey?' he asked.

00:39:21.147 --> 00:39:26.607
"'Oh, please don't, Lord Henry. I see that Basil is in one of his sulky moods, and I

00:39:26.607 --> 00:39:33.807
dare him when he sulks. Besides, I want you to tell me why I should not go in for philanthropy.'

00:39:34.467 --> 00:39:40.427
"'I don't know that I shall tell you that, Mr. Grey, but I certainly will not run away,

00:39:40.727 --> 00:39:46.847
now that you have asked me to stop. You don't really mind, do you, Basil? You've often told

00:39:46.847 --> 00:39:53.767
me that you liked your sitters to have someone to chat to.'

00:39:53.767 --> 00:39:54.827
Lord Henry would bit his lip.

00:39:55.807 --> 00:40:02.567
"'If Dorian wishes it, of course you must stay.' Dorian's whims are laws to everybody,

00:40:03.447 --> 00:40:04.447
except himself.

00:40:05.547 --> 00:40:07.867
Lord Henry took up his hat and gloves.

00:40:09.067 --> 00:40:15.527
"'You are very pressing, Basil, but I am afraid I must go. I have promised to meet a man at

00:40:15.527 --> 00:40:22.247
the Orléans. Good-bye, Mr. Grey. Come and see me some afternoon in Curzon Street. I

00:40:22.247 --> 00:40:25.927
am nearly always at home at five o'clock. Write to me when you are coming. I should

00:40:25.927 --> 00:40:28.247
be sorry to miss you.'

00:40:29.187 --> 00:40:35.127
"'Basil,' cried Dorian Grey, "'if Lord Henry goes, I shall go, too. You never open your

00:40:35.127 --> 00:40:38.847
lips when you are painting, and it is horribly dull standing on a platform and trying to

00:40:38.847 --> 00:40:45.767
look pleasant. Ask him to stay. I insist upon it. Stay, Harry, to oblige Dorian.'

00:40:46.287 --> 00:40:52.287
"'And to oblige me,' said Hallward, gazing intently at his picture.

00:40:53.047 --> 00:40:57.847
"'It is quite true. I never talk when I am working, and never listen either, and it must

00:40:57.847 --> 00:41:03.227
be dreadfully tedious for my unfortunate sitters. I beg you to stay.'

00:41:03.227 --> 00:41:07.607
"'But what about my man at the Orléans?' Hallward laughed.

00:41:08.727 --> 00:41:14.847
"'I don't think that there will be any difficulty about that. Sit down again, Harry. And now,

00:41:15.767 --> 00:41:19.687
get up on that platform, and don't move about too much, or pay any attention to what Lord

00:41:19.687 --> 00:41:26.567
Henry says. He is a very bad influence over all his friends, with the exception of myself.'

00:41:27.927 --> 00:41:33.747
Dorian stepped up on the dais with the air of a young Greek martyr, and made a little

00:41:33.747 --> 00:41:40.527
moo-ay of discontent to Lord Henry, to whom he had rather taken a fancy. He was so unlike

00:41:40.527 --> 00:41:46.667
Hallward. They made a delightful contrast, and he had such a beautiful voice. After

00:41:46.667 --> 00:41:48.247
a few moments he said to him,

00:41:49.587 --> 00:41:55.267
"'Have you really a bad influence, Lord Henry, as bad as Basil says?'

00:41:56.027 --> 00:42:03.947
"'There's no such thing as a good influence, Mr. Grey. All influence is immoral. Immoral

00:42:03.947 --> 00:42:07.187
from the scientific point of view.'

00:42:07.187 --> 00:42:14.567
"'Why? Because to influence a person is to give him one's own soul. He does not think

00:42:14.567 --> 00:42:20.847
his natural thoughts, or burn with his natural passions. His virtues are not real to him.

00:42:20.887 --> 00:42:28.027
His sins, if there are such things as sins, are borrowed. He becomes an echo of someone

00:42:28.027 --> 00:42:33.407
else's music, an actor of a part that has not been written for him. The aim of life

00:42:33.407 --> 00:42:39.847
is self-development. To realize one's nature perfectly, that is what each of us is here

00:42:39.847 --> 00:42:48.187
for. People are afraid of themselves nowadays. They have forgotten the highest of all duties,

00:42:48.267 --> 00:42:55.687
the duty that one owes to oneself. Of course they are charitable, they feed the hungry

00:42:55.687 --> 00:43:02.967
and clothe the beggar, but their own souls starve and are naked. Courage has gone out

00:43:02.967 --> 00:43:08.387
of our race. Perhaps we never really had it. The terror of society, which is the basis

00:43:08.387 --> 00:43:13.807
of morals, the terror of God, which is the secret of religion, these are the two things

00:43:13.807 --> 00:43:19.147
that govern us. And yet, just turn your head a little to the right, Dorian, like a good

00:43:19.147 --> 00:43:24.567
boy,' said Hallward, deep in his work, and conscious only that a look had come into the

00:43:24.567 --> 00:43:26.927
lad's face that he had never seen there before.

00:43:28.047 --> 00:43:35.607
"'And yet,' continued Lord Henry, in his low musical voice, and with that graceful wave

00:43:35.607 --> 00:43:41.507
of the hand that was always so characteristic of him and that he had even in his Eden days,

00:43:42.307 --> 00:43:48.407
I believe that if one man were to live his life out fully and completely, were to give

00:43:48.407 --> 00:43:54.387
form to every feeling, expression to every thought, reality to every dream, I believe

00:43:54.387 --> 00:44:00.107
that the world would gain such a fresh impulse of joy that we would forget all the maladies

00:44:00.107 --> 00:44:07.367
of medievalism and return to the Hellenic ideal, to something finer, richer than the

00:44:07.367 --> 00:44:16.467
Hellenic ideal it may be. But the bravest man among us is afraid of himself. The mutilation

00:44:16.467 --> 00:44:23.447
of the savage has its tragic survival in the self-denial that marrs our lives. We are punished

00:44:23.447 --> 00:44:31.187
for our refusals. Every impulse that we strive to strangle broods in the mind and poisons

00:44:31.187 --> 00:44:37.047
us. The body sins once and has done with the sin, for action is a mode of purification.

00:44:37.167 --> 00:44:45.047
Nothing remains then but the recollection of a pleasure or the luxury of a regret. The

00:44:45.047 --> 00:44:52.187
only way to get rid of a temptation is to yield to it, resist it, and your soul grows

00:44:52.187 --> 00:44:59.587
sick with longing for the things it has forbidden to itself, with desire for what its monstrous

00:44:59.587 --> 00:45:07.887
laws have made monstrous and unlawful. It has been said that the great events of the

00:45:07.887 --> 00:45:14.827
world take place in the brain. It is in the brain and the brain only that the great sins

00:45:14.827 --> 00:45:21.187
of the world take place also. You, Mr. Grey, you yourself, with your rose-red youth and

00:45:21.187 --> 00:45:27.527
rose-white boyhood, you have had passions that have made you afraid, thoughts that have

00:45:27.527 --> 00:45:35.767
filled you with terror, day-dreams and sleeping-dreams whose mere memory might stain your cheek with

00:45:35.767 --> 00:45:43.127
shame. Stop, Murmuring Grace, stop, you bewilder me. I don't know what to say. There is some

00:45:43.127 --> 00:45:48.927
answer to you, but I cannot find it. Don't speak. Let me think, or rather let me try

00:45:48.927 --> 00:45:57.487
not to think. For nearly ten minutes he stood there motionless, with parted lips and eyes

00:45:57.487 --> 00:46:04.447
strangely bright. He was dimly conscious that entirely fresh impulses were at work within

00:46:04.447 --> 00:46:12.767
him, and they seemed to him to have come really from himself. The few words that Basil's friend

00:46:12.767 --> 00:46:19.107
had said to him, words spoken by chance, no doubt, and with willful paradox in them, had

00:46:19.107 --> 00:46:25.167
yet touched some secret chord that had never been touched before, but that he felt was

00:46:25.167 --> 00:46:31.807
now vibrating and throbbing to curious pulses. Music had stirred him like that. Music had

00:46:31.807 --> 00:46:37.707
troubled him many times, but music was not articulate, it was not a new world, but rather

00:46:37.707 --> 00:46:44.927
a new chaos that it created in us words, mere words, how terrible they were, how clear

00:46:44.927 --> 00:46:52.767
and vivid and cruel. One could not escape from them, and yet what a subtle magic there

00:46:52.767 --> 00:46:59.567
was in them. They seemed to be able to give a plastic form to formless things and to have

00:46:59.567 --> 00:47:06.687
a music of their own, as sweet as that of the viol or of lute. Mere words?

00:47:07.707 --> 00:47:15.587
Was there anything so real as words? Yes, there had been things in his boyhood that

00:47:15.587 --> 00:47:21.767
he had not understood. He understood them now. I suddenly became fiery-coloured to him.

00:47:22.207 --> 00:47:27.627
It seemed to him that he had been walking in fire. Why had he not known it?

00:47:28.627 --> 00:47:34.267
Lord Henry watched him with his sad smile. He knew the precise psychological moment when

00:47:34.267 --> 00:47:41.547
to say nothing. He felt intensely interested. He was amazed at the sudden impression that

00:47:41.547 --> 00:47:47.167
his words had produced, and, remembering a book that he had read when he was sixteen,

00:47:47.687 --> 00:47:53.627
which had revealed to him much that he had not known before, he wondered whether Dorian

00:47:53.627 --> 00:48:00.027
Grey was passing through the same experience. He had merely shot an arrow into the air.

00:48:00.027 --> 00:48:07.807
Had he hit the mark? How fascinating the lad was! Hallward painted away with that marvellous

00:48:07.807 --> 00:48:15.047
bold touch of his, that had the true refinement and perfect delicacy that come only from strength.

00:48:16.227 --> 00:48:18.627
He was unconscious of the silence.

00:48:20.247 --> 00:48:27.907
"'Bezel, I am tired of standing,' cried Dorian Grey suddenly. I must go out and sit in the

00:48:27.907 --> 00:48:34.347
garden. The air is stifling here. My dear fellow, I am so sorry. When I am painting

00:48:34.347 --> 00:48:39.567
I can't think of anything else. But you never sat better. You were perfectly still, and

00:48:39.567 --> 00:48:44.307
I have caught the effect I wanted—the half-parted lips, the bright look in the eyes. I don't

00:48:44.307 --> 00:48:50.607
know what Harry has been saying to you, but he has certainly made you have the most wonderful

00:48:50.607 --> 00:48:55.587
expression. I suppose he has been paying you compliments. You mustn't believe a word he

00:48:55.587 --> 00:49:01.687
says. He has certainly not been paying me compliments. Perhaps that is the reason I

00:49:01.687 --> 00:49:05.087
don't think I believe anything he has told me.'

00:49:05.087 --> 00:49:11.887
"'You know you believe it all,' said Lord Henry, looking at him in his dreamy, heavy-lidded

00:49:11.887 --> 00:49:18.607
eyes. I will go out to the garden with you. It is horridly hot in the studio. Bezel, let

00:49:18.607 --> 00:49:24.467
us have something iced to drink—something with strawberries in it.' Certainly Harry

00:49:24.467 --> 00:49:29.827
just touched the bell, and when Parker comes I will tell him what you want. I have got

00:49:29.827 --> 00:49:36.727
to work on this background, so I will join you later on. Don't keep Dorian too long.

00:49:36.747 --> 00:49:42.527
I have never been in better form for painting than I am today. This is going to be my masterpiece.

00:49:43.747 --> 00:49:47.787
It is my masterpiece as it stands.'

00:49:47.787 --> 00:49:53.407
Lord Henry went out to the garden and found Dorian Gray burying his face in the great

00:49:53.407 --> 00:50:00.207
cool lilac blossoms, feverishly drinking in their perfume as if it had been wine. He was

00:50:00.207 --> 00:50:03.787
close to them and put his hand on his shoulder.

00:50:04.547 --> 00:50:10.127
"'You're quite right to do that,' he murmured. Nothing can cure the soul but the senses,

00:50:10.867 --> 00:50:14.927
just as nothing can cure the senses but the soul.'

00:50:14.927 --> 00:50:21.107
The lad started and drew back. He was bareheaded, and the leaves had tossed his rebellious curls

00:50:21.107 --> 00:50:27.587
and tangled all their gilded threads. There was a look of fear in his eyes, such as people

00:50:27.587 --> 00:50:34.207
have when they are suddenly awakened. His finely chiselled nostrils quivered, and some

00:50:34.207 --> 00:50:37.587
hidden nerve shook the scarlet of his lips and left them trembling.

00:50:40.107 --> 00:50:49.727
"'Yes,' continued Lord Henry, "'that is one of the great secrets of life—to cure the

00:50:49.727 --> 00:50:58.987
senses by means of the soul. You are a wonderful creature. You know much more than you think

00:50:58.987 --> 00:51:03.887
you know, just as you know less than you want to know.'

00:51:05.167 --> 00:51:11.107
Dorian Gray frowned and turned his head away. He could not help liking the tall, graceful

00:51:11.107 --> 00:51:17.107
young man who was standing by him. His romantic, all-over-covered face and worn expression

00:51:17.107 --> 00:51:24.187
interested him. There was something in his low-language voice that was absolutely fascinating.

00:51:25.047 --> 00:51:32.147
His cool, white, flower-like hands even had a curious charm. They moved, as he spoke,

00:51:32.307 --> 00:51:38.487
like music, and seemed to have a language of their own. But he felt afraid of him and

00:51:38.487 --> 00:51:46.847
ashamed of being afraid. Why had it been left for a stranger to reveal him to himself? He

00:51:46.847 --> 00:51:52.967
had been bored for months, but the friendship between them had never altered him. Suddenly

00:51:53.447 --> 00:51:58.167
there had come someone across his life who seemed to have disclosed to him life's mystery.

00:51:59.007 --> 00:52:07.507
And yet what was there to be afraid of? He was not a schoolboy or a girl. It was absurd

00:52:07.507 --> 00:52:08.367
to be frightened.

00:52:09.447 --> 00:52:16.047
"'Let us go and sit in the shade,' said Lord Henry. Parker has brought out the drinks,

00:52:16.047 --> 00:52:21.307
and if you stay any longer in this glare you will be quite spoiled, and Basil will never

00:52:21.307 --> 00:52:27.387
paint you again. You really must not let yourself become sunburnt. It would be very unbecoming

00:52:27.387 --> 00:52:28.487
to you.'

00:52:29.227 --> 00:52:34.707
"'What does it matter?' cried Dorian, laughing, as he sat down on the seat at the end of the

00:52:34.707 --> 00:52:35.047
garden.

00:52:36.607 --> 00:52:42.287
"'It should matter everything to you, Mr. Grey. Why?'

00:52:42.967 --> 00:52:50.567
"'Because you have now the most marvellous youth, and youth is the one thing worth having.'

00:52:51.327 --> 00:52:59.327
"'Oh, I don't feel that, Lord Henry. No, you don't feel it. Now, some day, when you are

00:52:59.327 --> 00:53:05.987
old and wrinkled and ugly, when thought has seared your forehead with its lines and passion

00:53:05.987 --> 00:53:12.107
branded your lips with its hideous fires, you will feel it. You will feel it terribly.

00:53:12.587 --> 00:53:19.887
Now, wherever you go, you charm the world. Will it always be so? You have a wonderfully

00:53:19.887 --> 00:53:26.687
beautiful face, Mr. Grey. Oh, don't frown, you have. And beauty is a form of genius,

00:53:26.907 --> 00:53:35.547
is higher, indeed, than genius, as it needs no explanation. It is one of the great facts

00:53:35.547 --> 00:53:42.107
of the world, like sunlight, or springtime, or the reflection in dark waters of that silver

00:53:42.107 --> 00:53:49.667
shell we call the moon. It cannot be questioned. It has its divine right of sovereignty. It

00:53:49.667 --> 00:54:00.947
makes princes of those who have it. You smile? When you've lost it, you won't smile. People

00:54:00.947 --> 00:54:07.287
say sometimes that beauty is only superficial. That may be so, but at least it is not so

00:54:07.287 --> 00:54:18.247
superficial as thought. To me, beauty is the wonder of wonders. It is only shallow people

00:54:18.247 --> 00:54:24.727
who do not judge by appearances. The true mystery of the world is the visible, not the

00:54:24.727 --> 00:54:31.647
invisible. Yes, Mr. Grey, the gods have been good to you. But what the gods give, they

00:54:31.647 --> 00:54:37.607
quickly take away. You only have a few years in which really to live. When your youth goes,

00:54:38.227 --> 00:54:44.927
your beauty will go with it. And then you will suddenly discover that there are no triumphs

00:54:44.927 --> 00:54:51.327
left for you, or have to content yourself with those mean triumphs that the memory of

00:54:51.327 --> 00:54:57.127
your past will make more bitter than defeats. Every month, as it wanes, brings you nearer

00:54:57.127 --> 00:55:03.927
to something dreadful. Time is jealous of you. And wars against your lilies and roses,

00:55:04.547 --> 00:55:12.807
you will become sallow and hollow-cheeked and dull-eyed. You will suffer horribly.

00:55:14.207 --> 00:55:20.287
Realize your youth while you have it. Don't squander the gold of your days listening to

00:55:20.287 --> 00:55:26.127
the tedious, trying to improve the hopeless failure, or giving away your life to the ignorant,

00:55:26.487 --> 00:55:34.447
the common and the vulgar, which are the aims, the false ideals of our age. Live. Live the

00:55:34.447 --> 00:55:40.867
wonderful life that is in you. Let nothing be lost upon you. Be always searching for

00:55:40.867 --> 00:55:48.347
new sensations. Be afraid of nothing. A new hedonism. That is what a century wants. You

00:55:48.347 --> 00:55:56.867
might be its visible symbol. With your personality there is nothing you could not do. The world

00:55:56.867 --> 00:56:00.307
belongs to you for a season.

00:56:02.247 --> 00:56:08.987
The moment I met you I saw that you were quite unconscious of what you really are, what you

00:56:08.987 --> 00:56:14.507
really might be. There was so much about you that charmed me that I felt I must tell you

00:56:14.507 --> 00:56:22.207
something about yourself. I thought how tragic it would be if you were wasted. For there

00:56:22.207 --> 00:56:28.627
is such a little time that your youth will last such a little time. The common hill flowers

00:56:28.627 --> 00:56:33.927
wither but they blossom again. The laburnum will be as gold next June as it is now. In

00:56:33.927 --> 00:56:39.047
a month there will be purple stars on the clement, and year after year the green night

00:56:39.287 --> 00:56:47.647
of its leaves will have its purple stars. But never again get we back our youth. The

00:56:47.647 --> 00:56:55.907
pulse of joy that beats in us at twenty becomes sluggish. Our limbs fail, our senses rot.

00:56:56.787 --> 00:57:02.867
We degenerate into hideous puppets, haunted by the memory of the passions of which we

00:57:02.867 --> 00:57:11.127
were much too afraid and the exquisite temptations that we did not dare yield to youth. Youth,

00:57:11.147 --> 00:57:15.067
there is nothing in the world but youth.

00:57:17.187 --> 00:57:24.267
Dorian Gray listened, open-eyed and wondering. The spray of lilac fell from his hand upon

00:57:24.267 --> 00:57:30.867
the gravel. A furry bee came and buzzed round it for a moment, then it began to scramble

00:57:30.867 --> 00:57:37.087
all over the fretted purple of the tiny blossoms. He watched it with that strange interest in

00:57:37.087 --> 00:57:42.267
trivial things that we try to develop when things of high import make us afraid, or when

00:57:42.267 --> 00:57:47.867
we are stirred by some new emotion for which we cannot find expression, or when some thought

00:57:47.867 --> 00:58:00.847
that terrifies us lays sudden siege to the brain and calls on us to yield. He saw it

00:58:00.847 --> 00:58:07.167
quiver, and then swayed gently to and fro. Suddenly Hallward appeared at the door of

00:58:07.167 --> 00:58:11.927
their studio and made frantic signs for them to come in. They turned to each other and

00:58:11.927 --> 00:58:12.307
smiled.

00:58:13.687 --> 00:58:18.527
"'I'm waiting,' cried Hallward. "'Do come in. The light is quite perfect, and you can

00:58:18.527 --> 00:58:24.207
bring your drinks.' They rose up and sauntered down the walk together. Two green and white

00:58:24.207 --> 00:58:29.227
butterflies fluttered past them, and in the pear tree at the end of the garden a thrush

00:58:29.227 --> 00:58:30.227
began to sing.

00:58:31.567 --> 00:58:37.627
"'You are glad to have met me, Mr. Grey,' said Lord Henry, looking at him.

00:58:38.467 --> 00:58:47.867
"'Yes, I am glad now. I wonder, will I always be glad? Always. That is a dreadful word.

00:58:48.627 --> 00:58:54.587
It makes me shudder when I hear it. Women are so fond of using it. They spoil every

00:58:54.587 --> 00:58:59.707
romance by trying to make it last forever. It is a meaningless word, too. The only difference

00:58:59.707 --> 00:59:06.947
between a caprice and a life-long passion is that the caprice lasts a little longer.'

00:59:06.947 --> 00:59:11.187
As they entered the studio Dorian Grey put his hand upon Lord Henry's arm.

00:59:12.507 --> 00:59:21.347
"'In that case, let our friendship be a caprice,' he murmured, flushing at his own

00:59:21.347 --> 00:59:25.367
boldness, then stepped upon the platform and resumed his pose.

00:59:26.507 --> 00:59:32.067
Lord Henry flung himself into a large wicker armchair and watched him. The sweep and dash

00:59:32.067 --> 00:59:37.347
of the brush on the canvas made the only sound that broke the stillness, except when Hollywood

00:59:37.347 --> 00:59:43.287
stepped back now and then to look at his work from a distance. And the slanting beams that

00:59:43.287 --> 00:59:50.007
had streamed through the open doorway, the dust danced and was golden. The heavy scent

00:59:50.007 --> 00:59:56.227
of the roses seemed to brood over everything. After about a quarter of an hour, Hollywood

00:59:56.227 --> 01:00:01.647
stopped painting, looked for a long time at Dorian Grey and then for a long time at the

01:00:01.647 --> 01:00:06.267
picture, biting the end of one of his huge brushes and smiling.

01:00:08.247 --> 01:00:17.107
"'It is quite finished,' he cried at last, and stooping down he wrote his name in thin

01:00:17.107 --> 01:00:22.967
million letters on the left-hand corner of the canvas. Lord Henry came over and examined

01:00:22.967 --> 01:00:28.407
the picture, and certainly a wonderful work of art and a wonderful likeness as well.

01:00:30.547 --> 01:00:36.487
"'My dear fellow, I congratulate you most warmly,' he said.

01:00:36.987 --> 01:00:43.827
"'Mr. Grey, come and look at yourself,' the lad started, as if awakened from some dream.

01:00:43.827 --> 01:00:49.927
"'Is it really finished?' he murmured, stepping down upon the platform.

01:00:51.547 --> 01:00:57.627
"'Quite finished,' said Hallward, and you sat splendidly to-day. I am awfully obliged

01:00:57.627 --> 01:00:59.047
to you.'

01:00:59.047 --> 01:01:05.867
"'That is entirely due to me,' broke Ian Lord Henry. Isn't it, Mr. Grey?'

01:01:06.127 --> 01:01:10.667
Dorian made no answer, but pressed listlessly in front of his picture and turned towards

01:01:10.667 --> 01:01:18.607
it. When he saw it he drew back, and his cheeks flushed for a moment with pleasure. A look

01:01:18.607 --> 01:01:25.787
of joy came into his eyes as if he had recognized himself for the first time. He stood there

01:01:26.527 --> 01:01:32.507
motionless and in wonder, dimly conscious that Hallward was speaking to him but not

01:01:32.507 --> 01:01:39.147
catching the meaning of his words. The sense of his own beauty came on him like a revelation.

01:01:41.107 --> 01:01:50.327
He had never felt it before. Basil Hallward's compliments had seemed to be merely the charming

01:01:50.327 --> 01:01:55.727
exaggerations of friendship. He had listened to them, laughed at them, forgotten them.

01:01:55.927 --> 01:02:04.767
They had not influenced his nature. Then had come Lord Henry, with his strange penigeric

01:02:04.767 --> 01:02:12.167
youth, his terrible warning of its brevity. That had stirred him at the time, and now,

01:02:12.587 --> 01:02:18.647
as he stood gazing at the shadow of his loveliness, the full reality of the description flashed

01:02:18.647 --> 01:02:25.627
across him. Yes, there would be a day when his face would be wrinkled and wisen, his

01:02:25.627 --> 01:02:32.507
eyes dim and colorless, the grace of his figure broken and deformed, the scarlet would pass

01:02:32.507 --> 01:02:39.727
away from his lips, and the gold steal from his hair. The life that was to make his soul

01:02:39.727 --> 01:02:45.467
would mar his body. He would become ignoble, hideous, and uncouth.

01:02:47.767 --> 01:02:55.567
As he thought of it, a sharp pang of pain struck like a knife across him and made each

01:02:55.567 --> 01:03:00.887
delicate fiber of his nature quiver. His eyes deepened into amethyst, and a mist of tears

01:03:00.887 --> 01:03:06.287
came across them. He felt as if a hand of ice had been laid upon his heart.

01:03:08.587 --> 01:03:13.687
"'Don't you like it?' cried Hallward at last, stung a little by the lad's silence and not

01:03:13.687 --> 01:03:14.847
understanding what it meant.

01:03:15.307 --> 01:03:18.647
"'Of course he likes it,' said Lord Henry.

01:03:18.707 --> 01:03:23.127
"'Who wouldn't like it? It is one of the greatest things in modern art. I will give you anything

01:03:23.127 --> 01:03:25.267
you ask for it. I must have it.'

01:03:25.907 --> 01:03:28.427
"'It is not my property, Harry.'

01:03:28.427 --> 01:03:30.227
"'Whose property is it?'

01:03:30.227 --> 01:03:31.827
"'Dorian's, of course.'

01:03:33.807 --> 01:03:36.667
"'He is a very lucky fellow.'

01:03:38.747 --> 01:03:46.227
"'How sad it is,' murmured Dorian Gray, with his eyes still fixed upon his own portrait.

01:03:47.907 --> 01:03:58.407
"'How sad it is! I shall grow old and horrid and dreadful, but this picture will remain

01:03:58.427 --> 01:04:06.727
always young. It will never be older than this particular day of June, if it was only

01:04:06.727 --> 01:04:13.607
the other way, if it was I who were to be always young and the picture that were to

01:04:13.607 --> 01:04:21.447
grow old. For this, oh, for this I would give everything. Yes, there is nothing in the whole

01:04:21.447 --> 01:04:23.847
world I would not give.'

01:04:24.317 --> 01:04:28.747
"'You would hardly care for that arrangement, Basil,' cried Lord Henry, laughing.

01:04:29.487 --> 01:04:36.067
"'It would be rather hard lines on you. I should object very strongly, Harry.'

01:04:36.067 --> 01:04:37.827
Dorian Gray turned and looked at him.

01:04:37.867 --> 01:04:42.987
"'I believe you would, Basil. You like your art better than your friends. I am no more

01:04:42.987 --> 01:04:49.187
to you than a green-bronze figure. Hardly as much, I dare say.'

01:04:49.187 --> 01:04:53.327
Hallward stared in amazement. It was so unlike Dorian to speak like that. What had happened?

01:04:53.627 --> 01:04:57.967
He seemed almost angry. His face was flushed and his cheeks burning.

01:04:58.267 --> 01:05:06.187
"'Yes,' he continued, "'I am less to you than your ivory hermies or your silver fawn. You

01:05:06.187 --> 01:05:10.687
will like them always. How long will you like me? Till I have my first wrinkle, I suppose.

01:05:11.167 --> 01:05:18.287
I know, now, that when one loses one's good looks, whatever they may be, one loses everything.

01:05:18.727 --> 01:05:24.027
Your picture has taught me that. Lord Henry is perfectly right. Youth is the only thing

01:05:24.027 --> 01:05:30.067
worth having. When I find that I am growing old, I will kill myself.'

01:05:30.067 --> 01:05:31.807
Hallward turned pale and caught his hand.

01:05:32.327 --> 01:05:37.667
"'Dorian!' he cried, "'don't talk like that. I have never had such a friend as you, and

01:05:37.667 --> 01:05:42.847
I shall never have another. You are not jealous of material things, are you? I am jealous

01:05:42.847 --> 01:05:47.647
of everything whose beauty does not die. I am jealous of the portrait you have painted

01:05:47.647 --> 01:05:52.327
of me. Why should it keep what I must lose? Every moment that passes takes something from

01:05:52.327 --> 01:05:59.287
me and gives something to it. Oh, if it was only the other way, if the picture could change,

01:05:59.487 --> 01:06:05.227
and I could always be what I am now. Why did you paint it? It will mock me some day, mock

01:06:05.227 --> 01:06:10.027
me horribly.' The hot tears welled into his eyes. He tore his hand away, and flinging

01:06:10.027 --> 01:06:15.047
himself onto the van, he buried his face in the cushions as if he were praying.

01:06:16.627 --> 01:06:21.087
"'This is your doing, Harry,' said Hallward bitterly.

01:06:21.687 --> 01:06:27.047
"'My doing? Yes, yours, and you know it.' Lord Henry shrugged his shoulders.

01:06:27.947 --> 01:06:31.967
"'It is the real Dorian Gray, that is all,' he answered.

01:06:32.087 --> 01:06:37.227
"'It is not. If it is not, what have I to do with it? You should have gone away when

01:06:37.227 --> 01:06:44.807
I asked you. I stayed when you asked me. Harry, I can't quarrel with two of my best friends

01:06:44.807 --> 01:06:50.267
at once. But between you, both you have made me hate the finest piece of work I have ever

01:06:50.267 --> 01:06:55.247
done, and I will destroy it. What is it but canvas and colour? I will not let it come

01:06:55.247 --> 01:06:59.967
across three lives and mar them.'

01:06:59.967 --> 01:07:04.627
Dorian Gray lifted his golden head from the pillow and looked at him with pallid face

01:07:04.627 --> 01:07:11.027
and tear-stained eyes as he walked over to the deal painting table that was set beneath

01:07:11.027 --> 01:07:17.167
the large curtained window. What was he doing there? His fingers were straying among the

01:07:17.167 --> 01:07:23.507
litter of tin tubes and dry brushes seeking for something. Yes, it was a long pallet knife.

01:07:24.007 --> 01:07:28.507
With its thin blade of lithe steel he had found it at last. He was going to rip up the

01:07:28.507 --> 01:07:33.507
canvas. With a stifled sob he leaped from the couch, and rushing over to Hallward, tore

01:07:33.507 --> 01:07:36.027
the knife out of his hand and flung it to the end of the studio.

01:07:36.707 --> 01:07:39.667
"'Don't, Basil, don't,' he cried. It would be murder.'

01:07:40.387 --> 01:07:46.327
"'I'm glad you appreciate my work at last, Dorian,' said Hallward coldly when he had

01:07:46.327 --> 01:07:50.587
recovered from his surprise. I never thought you would.'

01:07:51.307 --> 01:07:52.407
"'Appreciate it?'

01:07:52.407 --> 01:07:59.307
"'I am in love with it, Basil. It is part of myself. I feel that.'

01:08:00.267 --> 01:08:08.347
"'Well, as soon as you are dry, you shall be varnished and framed and sent home. Then

01:08:08.347 --> 01:08:13.547
you can do what you like with yourself.' And he walked across the room and rang the bell

01:08:13.547 --> 01:08:14.067
for tea.

01:08:14.887 --> 01:08:20.187
"'You will have tea, of course, Dorian, and so will you, Harry. Tea is the only simple

01:08:20.187 --> 01:08:22.207
pleasure left to us.'

01:08:22.207 --> 01:08:27.767
"'I don't like simple pleasures,' said Lord Henry. And I don't like scenes, except on

01:08:27.767 --> 01:08:34.307
the stage. What absurd fellows you are, both of you. I wonder who it was defined man as

01:08:34.307 --> 01:08:40.427
the rational animal. It was the most premature definition ever given. Man is many things,

01:08:40.427 --> 01:08:46.447
but he is not rational. I'm glad he is not, after all, though I wish you chaps would not

01:08:46.447 --> 01:08:51.447
squabble over the picture. You had much better let me have it, Basil. The silly boy doesn't

01:08:51.447 --> 01:08:53.707
really want it as I do.'

01:08:54.607 --> 01:08:59.527
"'If you let anyone have it but me, Basil, I will never forgive you,' cried Dorian Gray.

01:08:59.527 --> 01:09:05.827
And I don't allow people to call me a silly boy. You know the picture is yours, Dorian.

01:09:05.867 --> 01:09:07.767
I gave it to you before it existed.'

01:09:10.127 --> 01:09:16.667
"'And you know you have been a little silly, Mr. Gray, and that you shouldn't really mind

01:09:16.667 --> 01:09:17.927
being called a boy.'

01:09:18.487 --> 01:09:22.287
"'I should have minded very much this morning, Lord Henry.'

01:09:22.287 --> 01:09:27.927
"'Oh, this morning! You have lived since then.'

01:09:28.947 --> 01:09:33.567
There came a knock to the door, and the butler entered with the tea-tray and set it down

01:09:33.567 --> 01:09:39.767
upon a small Japanese table. There was a rattle of cups and saucers, and the hissing of a

01:09:39.767 --> 01:09:46.107
fluted Georgian urn. Two globe-shaped china dishes were brought out by a page. Dorian

01:09:46.107 --> 01:09:51.487
Gray went over and poured the tea out. The two men sauntered languidly to the table and

01:09:51.487 --> 01:09:53.067
examined what was under the covers.

01:09:54.327 --> 01:09:57.887
"'Let us go to the theatre tonight,' said Lord Henry.

01:09:58.567 --> 01:10:04.227
"'There is sure to be something on somewhere. I have promised to dine at White's. But it

01:10:04.227 --> 01:10:09.287
is only with an old friend, so I can send my why and say that I am ill or that I am

01:10:09.287 --> 01:10:14.287
prevented from coming in consequence of a subsequent engagement. I think it would be

01:10:14.287 --> 01:10:23.047
rather nice excuse. It would have the surprise of candour. It is such a bore putting on one's

01:10:23.047 --> 01:10:28.567
clothes,' muttered Hallward. And when one has them on, they are so horrid.'

01:10:30.007 --> 01:10:35.707
"'Yes,' answered Lord Henry dreamily, "'the costume of our day is detestable. It is so

01:10:36.047 --> 01:10:43.887
sombre, so depressing. Sin is the only colour element left in modern life. You really must

01:10:43.887 --> 01:10:47.927
not say things like that before Dorian, Harry.'

01:10:47.927 --> 01:10:53.027
"'Before which Dorian? The one who is pouring out the tea for us, or the one in the

01:10:54.067 --> 01:10:54.507
picture?'

01:10:55.947 --> 01:11:00.727
"'Before either. I should like to come to the theatre with you, Lord Henry,' said the

01:11:00.727 --> 01:11:01.007
lad.

01:11:01.347 --> 01:11:05.487
"'Then you shall come. And you will come too, Basil, won't you?'

01:11:05.487 --> 01:11:06.587
"'I can't really.'

01:11:07.787 --> 01:11:10.247
"'I would sooner not. I have a lot of work to do.'

01:11:10.247 --> 01:11:16.787
"'Well, then you and I will go alone, Mr. Grey. I should like that awfully.' Basil

01:11:16.787 --> 01:11:20.127
Hallward bit his lip and walked over, cupping the hand of the picture.

01:11:21.567 --> 01:11:25.407
"'I will stay with the real Dorian,' he said, sadly.

01:11:27.267 --> 01:11:32.327
"'Is it the real Dorian?' cried the original of the portrait, running across to him.

01:11:33.027 --> 01:11:35.127
"'Am I really like that?'

01:11:36.087 --> 01:11:38.247
"'Yes, you are just like that.'

01:11:39.107 --> 01:11:43.367
"'How wonderful, Basil! At least you are like it in appearance.'

01:11:44.967 --> 01:11:47.967
"'But it will never alter,' said Hallward.

01:11:48.727 --> 01:11:50.547
"'That is something.'

01:11:51.267 --> 01:11:55.187
"'What a fuss people make about fidelity!' murmured Lord Henry.

01:11:55.247 --> 01:12:00.407
"'And, after all, it is purely a question of physiology. It has nothing to do with our

01:12:00.407 --> 01:12:06.067
own will. It is either an unfortunate accident or an unpleasant result of temperament. Young

01:12:06.067 --> 01:12:10.767
men want to be faithful, and or not. Old men want to be faithless, and cannot. That is

01:12:10.767 --> 01:12:12.147
all one can say.'

01:12:12.147 --> 01:12:16.967
"'Don't go to the theatre to-night, Dorian. Stop. Dine with me.'

01:12:17.607 --> 01:12:20.187
"'I can't, really.'

01:12:20.187 --> 01:12:21.307
"'Why?'

01:12:21.307 --> 01:12:27.387
"'Because I have promised Lord Henry to go with him. He won't like you any better for

01:12:27.387 --> 01:12:32.967
keeping your promise, as he always breaks his own. I beg you not to go.'

01:12:33.607 --> 01:12:35.947
Dorian Gray laughed and shook his head.

01:12:36.587 --> 01:12:42.347
"'I entreat you,' the lad hesitated, and looked over at Lord Henry, who was watching

01:12:42.347 --> 01:12:44.767
them from the tea-table with an amused smile.

01:12:45.687 --> 01:12:49.287
"'I must go, Basil,' he answered.

01:12:49.807 --> 01:12:54.467
"'Very well,' said Hallward, and he walked over and laid his cup down on the tray.

01:12:54.527 --> 01:13:01.347
"'It is rather late, and as you have to dress, you'd better not lose no time. Good-bye,

01:13:01.587 --> 01:13:05.007
Harry. Good-bye, Dorian. Come see me soon. Come to-morrow.'

01:13:05.687 --> 01:13:05.987
"'Certainly.'

01:13:06.287 --> 01:13:07.407
"'You won't forget?'

01:13:07.407 --> 01:13:09.647
"'No, of course not.'

01:13:09.647 --> 01:13:13.067
"'And, Harry?'

01:13:13.067 --> 01:13:20.067
"'Yes, Basil. Remember what I asked you, when in the garden this morning.'

01:13:20.607 --> 01:13:22.067
"'I have forgotten it.'

01:13:22.907 --> 01:13:24.187
"'I trust you.'

01:13:24.867 --> 01:13:29.467
"'I wish I could trust myself,' said Lord Henry, laughing.

01:13:29.767 --> 01:13:36.027
"'Come, Mr. Gray, my handsome is outside, and I can drop you at your own place. Good-bye,

01:13:36.107 --> 01:13:37.067
Basil.'

01:13:37.067 --> 01:13:42.927
It has been a most interesting afternoon. As the door closed behind them, Hallward flung

01:13:42.927 --> 01:13:48.807
himself down on a sofa, and a look of pain came into his face.

01:14:27.177 --> 01:14:34.537
One afternoon, a month later, Dorian Gray was reclining in a luxurious arm-chair in

01:14:34.537 --> 01:14:40.917
the little library of Lord Henry's house in Curzon Street. It was, in its way, a very

01:14:40.917 --> 01:14:46.737
charming room, with its high-paneled wainscotting of olive-stained oak, its creamed-coloured

01:14:46.737 --> 01:14:53.317
frieze and ceiling of raised plaster-work, and its brick-dust-felt carpet-strewn with

01:14:53.317 --> 01:15:01.157
long-fringed silk-Persian rugs. On a tiny satin-wood table stood a statuette of Clodian,

01:15:01.717 --> 01:15:09.097
and beside it lay a copy of Les Cent Nouveaux, bound for Margaret au Voila by Clovis Eve,

01:15:09.657 --> 01:15:15.917
and powdered with the gilt daisies that the Queen had selected for her device. Some large

01:15:15.917 --> 01:15:22.057
blue china jars, filled with parrot tulips, were ranged on the mantel-shelf, and through

01:15:22.057 --> 01:15:27.237
the small leaded panes of the window streamed the apricot-coloured light of a summer's day

01:15:27.237 --> 01:15:34.677
in London. Lord Henry had not come in yet. He was always late on principle, his principle

01:15:34.677 --> 01:15:37.537
being that punctuality is the thief of time.

01:15:38.657 --> 01:15:44.777
So the lad was looking rather sulky, as with listless fingers he turned over the pages

01:15:44.777 --> 01:15:51.057
of an elaborately illustrated edition of Manon Lescaut that he had found in one of the book

01:15:51.057 --> 01:15:58.037
cases. The formal monotonous ticking of the Louis Quatorze clock annoyed him. Once or

01:15:58.037 --> 01:16:03.777
twice he thought of going away. At last he heard a light step outside, and the door opened.

01:16:04.357 --> 01:16:07.217
"'How late you are, Harry!' he murmured.

01:16:07.837 --> 01:16:13.657
"'I am afraid it is not Harry, Mr. Grey,' said a woman's voice. He glanced quickly

01:16:13.657 --> 01:16:15.217
around and rose to his feet.

01:16:15.797 --> 01:16:22.857
"'I beg your pardon, I thought. You thought it was my husband. It is only his wife. You

01:16:22.857 --> 01:16:28.717
must let me introduce myself. I know you quite well by your photographs. I think my husband

01:16:28.717 --> 01:16:31.037
has got twenty-seven of them.'

01:16:31.037 --> 01:16:34.657
"'Not twenty-seven, Lady Henry?'

01:16:34.657 --> 01:16:36.957
"'Well, twenty-six, then.'

01:16:36.957 --> 01:16:42.877
"'And I saw you with him the other night at the opera. She laughed nervously as she spoke,

01:16:42.877 --> 01:16:48.657
and watched in with her vague forget-me-not eyes. She was a curious woman, whose dresses

01:16:48.657 --> 01:16:54.657
always looked as if they had been designed in a rage and put on in a tempest. She was

01:16:54.657 --> 01:17:00.537
always in love with somebody, and, as her passion was never returned, she had kept all

01:17:00.537 --> 01:17:06.617
her illusions. She tried to look picturesque, but only succeeded in being untidy. Her name

01:17:06.617 --> 01:17:11.377
was Victoria, and she had a perfect mania for going to church.'

01:17:11.377 --> 01:17:15.917
"'That was at Lohengrin, Lady Henry, I think?'

01:17:15.917 --> 01:17:23.457
"'Yes. It was at dear Lohengrin. I like Wagner's music much better than any other music. It

01:17:23.457 --> 01:17:29.277
is so loud that one can talk the whole time, without people hearing what one says. That

01:17:29.277 --> 01:17:33.197
is a great advantage. Don't you think so, Mr. Gray?'

01:17:33.197 --> 01:17:38.637
The same nervous staccato laugh broke from her thin lips, and her fingers began to play

01:17:38.637 --> 01:17:43.357
with a long paper knife. Dorian smiled, and shook his head.

01:17:43.877 --> 01:17:49.277
"'I'm afraid I don't think so, Lady Henry. I never talk during music, at least during

01:17:49.277 --> 01:17:53.917
good music. If one hears bad music, it is one's duty to drown it by conversation.'

01:17:56.217 --> 01:18:00.437
"'Ah, that is one of Harry's views, isn't it, Mr. Gray?'

01:18:01.137 --> 01:18:05.977
"'But you must not think I don't like good music. I adore it. But I am afraid of it.

01:18:05.977 --> 01:18:13.257
It makes me too romantic. I have simply worshipped pianists. Two at a time, sometimes. I don't

01:18:13.257 --> 01:18:17.717
know what it is about them. Perhaps it is that they are foreigners. They all are, aren't

01:18:17.717 --> 01:18:21.797
they? Even those that are born in England become foreigners after a time, don't they?

01:18:22.237 --> 01:18:27.877
It is so clever of them. It is such a compliment to art. Makes it quite cosmopolitan, doesn't

01:18:27.877 --> 01:18:33.237
it? You've never been to any of my parties, have you, Mr. Gray? You must come. I can't

01:18:33.237 --> 01:18:38.417
afford orchids, but I spend no expense in foreigners. They make one's rooms look so

01:18:38.417 --> 01:18:44.657
picturesque. Ah, but here is Harry. Harry, I came in to look for you, to ask you something.

01:18:45.037 --> 01:18:50.837
I forget what it was. And I found Mr. Gray here. But we've had such a pleasant chat about

01:18:50.837 --> 01:18:52.877
music. We have quite the same views.'

01:18:53.957 --> 01:19:00.417
"'No. Oh, I think our views are quite different. But he has been most pleasant. I am so glad

01:19:00.417 --> 01:19:01.857
I've seen him.'

01:19:01.857 --> 01:19:07.877
"'I am charmed, my love, quite charmed,' said Lord Henry, elevating his dark crescent-shaped

01:19:07.877 --> 01:19:11.737
eyebrows, and looking at them both with an amused smile.

01:19:12.257 --> 01:19:18.057
"'So sorry I am late, Dorian. I went to look after a piece of old briquette in Wardour

01:19:18.057 --> 01:19:22.577
Street, and had to bargain for hours for it. Nowadays people know the price of everything

01:19:22.577 --> 01:19:24.457
and the value of nothing.'

01:19:26.857 --> 01:19:32.357
"'I am afraid I must be going,' exclaimed Lady Henry, after an awkward silence, with

01:19:32.357 --> 01:19:39.437
her silly sudden laugh. "'I have promised to drive with the Duchess. Good-bye, Mr. Gray.'

01:19:39.437 --> 01:19:45.657
"'Good-bye, Harry. You are dining out, I suppose. So am I. Perhaps I shall see you at Lady Thornberry's.'

01:19:45.657 --> 01:19:50.997
"'I dare say, my dear,' said Lord Henry, shutting the door behind her as she flitted out of

01:19:50.997 --> 01:19:55.617
the room, looking like a bird of paradise that had been out in the rain, and leaving

01:19:55.617 --> 01:20:01.497
a faint odour of patchouli behind her. Then he shook hands with Dorian Gray, lit a cigarette,

01:20:01.677 --> 01:20:03.737
and flung himself down on the sofa.

01:20:04.537 --> 01:20:10.077
"'Never marry a woman with straw-coloured hair, Dorian,' he said, after a few puffs.

01:20:10.957 --> 01:20:12.077
"'Why, Harry?'

01:20:12.077 --> 01:20:18.717
"'Because they are so sentimental. But I like sentimental people. Never marry at all,

01:20:18.717 --> 01:20:26.277
Dorian. Men marry because they are tired, women because they are curious. Both are disappointed.'

01:20:26.857 --> 01:20:33.457
"'I don't think I am likely to marry, Harry. I am too much in love,' said one of your

01:20:33.457 --> 01:20:34.197
referisms.

01:20:34.657 --> 01:20:38.997
"'I am putting it into practice, as I do everything you say.'

01:20:38.997 --> 01:20:44.017
"'Whom are you in love with?' said Lord Henry, looking at him with a curious smile.

01:20:44.857 --> 01:20:48.437
"'With an actress,' said Dorian Gray, blushing.

01:20:49.637 --> 01:20:56.197
"'Lord Henry shrugged his shoulders. That is a rather commonplace debut,' he murmured.

01:20:56.677 --> 01:21:01.277
"'You would not say so if you saw her, Harry. Who is she?'

01:21:01.277 --> 01:21:09.637
"'Her name is Sybil Vane. Never heard of her. No one has. People will, some day, however.

01:21:09.677 --> 01:21:12.297
She is a genius.'

01:21:12.837 --> 01:21:21.217
"'My dear boy, no woman is a genius. Women are a decorative sex. They never have anything

01:21:21.217 --> 01:21:27.497
to say, but they say it charmingly. They represent the triumph of matter over mind, just as men

01:21:27.497 --> 01:21:33.197
represent the triumph of mind over morals. There are only two kinds of women—the plain

01:21:33.197 --> 01:21:39.017
and the coloured. The plain women are very useful. If you want to gain a reputation for

01:21:39.517 --> 01:21:45.437
respectability, you have merely to take them down to supper. The other women are very charming.

01:21:45.717 --> 01:21:52.437
They commit one mistake, however. They paint in order to try to look young. Our grandmothers

01:21:52.437 --> 01:22:00.157
paint it in order to try to talk brilliantly. Rouge and Esprit used to go together. That

01:22:00.157 --> 01:22:05.197
has all gone out now. As long as a woman can look ten years younger than her own daughter,

01:22:05.737 --> 01:22:11.617
she is perfectly satisfied. As for conversation, there are only five women in London worth

01:22:11.617 --> 01:22:17.717
talking to, and two of these can't be admitted into decent society. However, tell me about

01:22:17.717 --> 01:22:20.697
your genius. How long have you known her?'

01:22:20.697 --> 01:22:22.477
"'About three weeks.'

01:22:22.477 --> 01:22:28.417
"'Not so much. About two weeks and two days. How did you come across her?'

01:22:28.417 --> 01:22:34.857
"'I will tell you, Harry, but you mustn't be unsympathetic about it. After all, it never

01:22:34.857 --> 01:22:39.897
would have happened if I had not met you. You filled me with a wild desire to know everything

01:22:39.897 --> 01:22:46.857
about life. For days after I met you, something seemed to throb in my veins. As I lounged

01:22:46.857 --> 01:22:51.917
in the park or strolled down Piccadilly, I used to look at every one who passed me and

01:22:51.917 --> 01:22:57.037
wonder with a mad curiosity what sort of lives they led. Some of them fascinated me, others

01:22:57.037 --> 01:23:03.937
filled me with terror. There was exquisite poison in the air. I had a passion for sensations.'

01:23:04.857 --> 01:23:12.317
"'One evening, about seven o'clock, I determined to go out in search of some adventure. I felt

01:23:12.317 --> 01:23:18.537
that this grey, monstrous London of ours, with its myriads of people, its splendid sinners,

01:23:18.577 --> 01:23:24.517
and its sordid sins, as you once said, must have something in store for me. I fancied

01:23:24.517 --> 01:23:31.697
a thousand things. The mere danger gave me a sense of delight. I remember what you had

01:23:31.697 --> 01:23:35.457
said to me on that wonderful night when we first dined together about the search for

01:23:35.457 --> 01:23:40.977
beauty being the poisonous secret of life. I don't know what I expected, but I went out

01:23:40.977 --> 01:23:46.737
and wandered eastward, soon losing my way in a labyrinth of grimy streets and black

01:23:46.737 --> 01:23:53.777
grassless squares. About half past eight I passed by a little third-rate theatre with

01:23:53.777 --> 01:24:00.437
a great flaring gas-jets and gaudy playbills, a hideous Jew in the most amazing waistcoat

01:24:00.437 --> 01:24:06.717
I have ever beheld in my life was standing at the entrance, smoking a vile cigar. He

01:24:06.717 --> 01:24:12.097
had greasy ringlets and an enormous diamond blazed in the centre of a soiled shirt.

01:24:13.017 --> 01:24:19.557
"'Have a box, my lord,' he said when he saw me, and he took off his hat with an act of

01:24:19.557 --> 01:24:26.117
gorgeous civility. There was something about him, Harry, that amused me. He was such a

01:24:26.117 --> 01:24:31.637
gentleman. You will laugh at me, I know, but I really went in and paid a whole guinea for

01:24:31.637 --> 01:24:38.997
a stage-box. To the present day I can't make out why I did so, and yet if I hadn't, my

01:24:38.997 --> 01:24:45.097
dear Harry, if I hadn't I would have missed the greatest romance of my life. I see you

01:24:45.097 --> 01:24:51.617
are laughing, it is horrid of you. I am not laughing, Dorian, at least I am not laughing

01:24:51.617 --> 01:24:59.177
at you. But you should not say the greatest romance of your life. You should say the first

01:24:59.177 --> 01:25:05.917
romance of your life. You will always be loved, and you will always be in love with love.

01:25:06.797 --> 01:25:11.057
There are exquisite things in store for you. This is merely the beginning.'

01:25:11.897 --> 01:25:16.617
"'Do you think my nature so shallow?' cried Dorian Gray angrily.

01:25:16.617 --> 01:25:20.357
"'No, I think your nature so deep.'

01:25:21.117 --> 01:25:22.337
"'How do you mean?'

01:25:23.137 --> 01:25:31.237
"'My dear boy, people only love once in their lives are really shallow people. What they call

01:25:31.237 --> 01:25:38.777
their loyalty and their fidelity, I call either the lethargy of custom or the lack of imagination.

01:25:39.797 --> 01:25:46.437
Faithlessness is to the emotional life what consistency is to the intellectual life.

01:25:47.057 --> 01:25:53.117
Simply a confession of failure. But I don't want to interrupt you. Go on with your story.'

01:25:54.757 --> 01:26:01.537
"'Well, I found myself seated in a horrid little private box with a vulgar drop scene staring me

01:26:01.537 --> 01:26:07.477
in the face. I looked out behind the curtain and surveyed the house. It was a tawdry affair, all

01:26:07.477 --> 01:26:14.997
cupids and cornucopias like a third-rate wedding cake. The gallery and pit were fairly full,

01:26:15.577 --> 01:26:21.457
but the two rows of dingy stalls were quite empty, and there was hardly a person in what I

01:26:21.457 --> 01:26:28.157
supposed they called the dress circle. Women went about with oranges and ginger beer,

01:26:28.157 --> 01:26:33.397
and there was a terrible consumption of nuts going on. It must have been just like the palmy

01:26:33.397 --> 01:26:40.617
days of British drama. Just like, I should fancy, and very horrid. I began to wonder what on earth

01:26:40.617 --> 01:26:45.777
I should do when I caught sight of the playbill. What do you think the play was, Harry?'

01:26:45.777 --> 01:26:54.397
"'I should think, oh, the idiot boy, or dumb but innocent. Our fathers used to like that sort of

01:26:54.397 --> 01:27:00.377
piece, I believe. The longer I live, Dorian, the more keenly I feel that whatever was good

01:27:00.377 --> 01:27:08.417
for our fathers is not good enough for us. In art, as in politics, les grands prêts ont toujours trop.'

01:27:10.397 --> 01:27:18.357
"'This play was good enough for us, Harry. It was Romeo and Juliet. I must admit I was rather

01:27:18.357 --> 01:27:23.437
annoyed at the idea of seeing Shakespeare done in such a wretched whole of a place. Still,

01:27:23.437 --> 01:27:29.717
I felt interested in a sort of way. At any rate, I determined to wait for the first act.

01:27:29.877 --> 01:27:34.977
There was a dreadful orchestra, presided over by a young Jew who sat to the cracked piano that

01:27:34.977 --> 01:27:42.117
nearly drove me away. But at last the drop scene was drawn up and the play began. Romeo was a stout

01:27:42.117 --> 01:27:48.537
elderly gentleman with corked eyebrows, a husky tragedy voice, and a figure like a beer-barrel.

01:27:49.537 --> 01:27:55.617
Recuscio was almost as bad. He was played by the low comedian who would introduce gags of his own

01:27:55.617 --> 01:28:01.537
and went on most familiar terms with the pit. They were as grotesque as the scenery, and that

01:28:01.537 --> 01:28:11.017
looked as if it had come out of a pantomime of fifty years ago. But Juliet? Harry, imagine a girl

01:28:11.017 --> 01:28:17.417
hardly seventeen years of age, with a little flower-like face, a small Greek head with plaited

01:28:17.417 --> 01:28:25.237
coils of dark brown hair, eyes that were violet wells of passion, lips that were like the petals

01:28:25.237 --> 01:28:31.817
of a rose. She was the loveliest thing I'd ever seen in my life. You said to me once that

01:28:31.817 --> 01:28:38.437
pathos left you unmoved, but that beauty, mere beauty, could fill your eyes with tears? I tell

01:28:38.437 --> 01:28:44.137
you, Harry, I could hardly see this girl for the mist of tears that came across me. And her voice?

01:28:44.257 --> 01:28:50.877
Oh, I never heard such a voice. It was very low at first, with deep mellow notes that seemed to

01:28:50.877 --> 01:28:57.637
singly fall upon one's ear. Then it became a little louder and sounded like a flute or a

01:28:57.637 --> 01:29:03.637
distant hat-bois. In the garden scene it had all the tremulous ecstasy that one hears just before

01:29:03.637 --> 01:29:09.357
dawn when nightingales are singing. There were moments later on when it had the wild passion

01:29:09.357 --> 01:29:15.357
of violins. You know how a voice can stir one. Your voice and the voice of Sybil Vane are two

01:29:15.357 --> 01:29:20.937
that I shall never forget. When I close my eyes, I hear them, and each one of them is saying

01:29:20.937 --> 01:29:28.157
something different. I don't know which to follow. Why should I not love her? Harry, I do love her.

01:29:28.597 --> 01:29:33.957
She is everything to me in life. Night after night I go to see her play. One evening she is

01:29:33.957 --> 01:29:40.037
Rosalind, the next she is Imogen. I have seen her die in the gloom of an Italian tomb, sucking the

01:29:40.037 --> 01:29:45.357
poison from her lover's lips. I have watched her wandering through the forest of Arden, disguised

01:29:45.357 --> 01:29:51.157
as a pretty boy in hose and doublet and dainty cap. She has been mad, and has come into the presence

01:29:51.157 --> 01:29:57.537
of a guilty king, and has given him rue to wear, with bitter herbs to taste of. She has been

01:29:57.537 --> 01:30:04.117
innocent, and the black hands of jealousy has crushed her reed-like throat. I have seen her in

01:30:04.117 --> 01:30:10.417
every age and in every costume. Ordinary women never appeal to one's imagination. They are limited

01:30:10.417 --> 01:30:18.257
to their century. No glamour ever transfigures them. One knows their minds as easily as one knows

01:30:18.257 --> 01:30:25.937
their bonnets. One can always find them. There is no mystery in one of them. They ride in the park,

01:30:26.117 --> 01:30:31.657
in the morning, and chatter at tea parties in the afternoon. They have the stereotyped smile in their

01:30:31.657 --> 01:30:39.837
fashionable manner. They are quite obvious. But an actress? How different an actress is. Why didn't

01:30:39.837 --> 01:30:45.937
you tell me that the only thing worth loving is an actress? Because I have loved so many of them,

01:30:46.117 --> 01:30:54.877
Dorian. Oh, yes, horrid people with dyed hair and painted faces. Don't run down dyed hair and painted

01:30:54.877 --> 01:31:01.937
faces. There is an extraordinary charm in them sometimes. I wish now I had not told you about

01:31:01.937 --> 01:31:10.077
Sibyl Vane. You could not have helped telling me, Dorian. All through your life you will tell me

01:31:10.077 --> 01:31:18.097
everything you do. Yes, Harry, I believe that is true. I cannot help telling you things.

01:31:18.097 --> 01:31:22.617
You have a curious influence over me. If I ever did a crime,

01:31:23.537 --> 01:31:26.737
I would come and confide it to you. You would understand me.

01:31:28.437 --> 01:31:35.277
People like you, the willful sunbeams of life, don't commit crimes, Dorian. But I am much obliged

01:31:35.277 --> 01:31:40.937
for the compliment all the same. And now, tell me. Reach me the matches, like a good boy.

01:31:40.937 --> 01:31:47.377
Thanks. Tell me. Where are your relations with Sibyl Vane?

01:31:48.257 --> 01:31:53.097
Dorian Gray leaped to his feet with flushed cheeks and burning eyes.

01:31:53.537 --> 01:31:56.517
Harry, Sibyl Vane is sacred.

01:31:57.537 --> 01:32:02.237
It is only the sacred things that are worth touching, Dorian, said Lord Henry,

01:32:02.777 --> 01:32:09.457
with a strange touch of pathos in his voice. But why should you be annoyed? I suppose she will

01:32:09.457 --> 01:32:14.337
be yours some day. When one isn't love, one always begins by deceiving oneself,

01:32:14.457 --> 01:32:20.117
and one always ends by deceiving others. That is what the world calls romance.

01:32:21.057 --> 01:32:27.797
But you know her, at any rate, I suppose? Of course I know her. On the first night I was

01:32:27.797 --> 01:32:32.077
at the theatre, the horrid old Jew came round to the box after the performance was over,

01:32:32.477 --> 01:32:37.117
and offered to bring me behind the scenes and introduce me to her. I was furious with him,

01:32:37.117 --> 01:32:42.357
told him that Juliet had been dead for hundreds of years, and that her body was lying in a marble

01:32:42.357 --> 01:32:49.297
tomb in Verona. I think, from his blank look of amazement, that he thought I had taken too

01:32:49.297 --> 01:32:54.857
much champagne or something. I am not surprised. I was not surprised either.

01:32:55.917 --> 01:33:00.337
Then he asked me if I wrote for any of the newspapers. I told him I never even read them.

01:33:00.797 --> 01:33:05.837
He seemed terribly disappointed in that, and confided to me that all the dramatic critics

01:33:05.837 --> 01:33:11.477
were in conspiracy against him, and that they were all to be bought. I believe he was quite

01:33:11.477 --> 01:33:17.277
right there, but on the other hand most of them are not at all expensive. Well, he seemed to think

01:33:17.277 --> 01:33:21.657
they were beyond his means. By this time the lights were being put out in the theatre,

01:33:21.657 --> 01:33:27.677
and I had to go. He wanted me to try some cigars, which he strongly recommended, I declined.

01:33:28.117 --> 01:33:32.777
The next night, of course, I arrived at the theatre again. When he saw me he made a low bow

01:33:32.777 --> 01:33:38.577
and assured me that I was a patron of art. He was a most offensive brute, though he had an

01:33:38.577 --> 01:33:44.897
extraordinary passion for Shakespeare. He told me once, with an air of pride, that his three

01:33:44.897 --> 01:33:50.897
bankruptcies were due entirely to the poet whom he insisted on calling The Bard. He seemed to

01:33:50.897 --> 01:33:57.517
think it a distinction. It was a distinction, my dear Dorian, a great distinction. But when

01:33:57.517 --> 01:34:04.957
did you first speak to Mrs. Sybilvane? The third night. She had been playing Rosalind.

01:34:05.217 --> 01:34:10.657
I could not help going around. I had thrown her some flowers, and she looked at me. At least

01:34:10.657 --> 01:34:17.177
I fancied she had. The old Jew was persistent. He seemed determined to bring me behind, so I

01:34:17.177 --> 01:34:24.117
consented. It was curious my not wanting to know her, wasn't it? No, I don't think so.

01:34:24.777 --> 01:34:32.117
My dear Harry, why? I'll tell you some other time. Now I want to know about the girl. Sybil? Oh!

01:34:32.457 --> 01:34:40.437
She was so shy and so gentle. There was something of a child about her. Her eyes opened wide in

01:34:40.437 --> 01:34:45.737
exquisite wonder when I told her what I thought of her performance, and she seemed quite unconscious

01:34:45.737 --> 01:34:53.077
of her power. I think we were both rather nervous. The old Jew stood grinning at the doorway of the

01:34:53.077 --> 01:34:58.637
green room, making elaborate speeches about us both, while we stood looking at each other like

01:34:58.637 --> 01:35:05.577
children. He would insist on calling me my lord. So I had assured Sybil that I was not anything

01:35:05.577 --> 01:35:10.657
of the kind. She said quite simply to me, You look more like a prince.

01:35:11.777 --> 01:35:17.677
But my word, Dorian, Miss Sybil knows how to make compliments. You don't understand her, Harry.

01:35:18.317 --> 01:35:23.917
She regarded me merely as a person in a play. She knows nothing of life. She lives with a mother,

01:35:24.177 --> 01:35:30.697
a faded, tired woman who played Lady Capulet in a sort of magenta dressing wrapper on the first

01:35:30.697 --> 01:35:38.177
night, and looks as if she'd seen better days. I know that look. It always depresses me.

01:35:38.837 --> 01:35:42.437
The Jew wanted to tell me her history, but I said it did not interest me.

01:35:42.437 --> 01:35:48.057
You're quite right. There was always something infinitely mean about other people's tragedies.

01:35:48.917 --> 01:35:53.137
Sybil is the only thing I care about. What is it to me where she

01:35:53.137 --> 01:35:58.577
came from? From a little head to a little feet she is absolutely and entirely divine.

01:35:59.737 --> 01:36:04.837
I go to see her act every night of my life, and every night she is more marvellous.

01:36:06.037 --> 01:36:09.497
That is the reason, I suppose, that you will never dine with me now.

01:36:09.497 --> 01:36:16.237
I thought you must have some curious romance on hand. You have, but it's not quite what I expected.

01:36:17.557 --> 01:36:21.657
My dear Harry, we either lunch or sup together every day,

01:36:21.937 --> 01:36:28.097
and I've been to the opera with you several times. You always come dreadfully late. Well,

01:36:28.097 --> 01:36:34.477
I can't help going to see Sybil play, even if it is only for an act. I get hungry for her presence,

01:36:34.517 --> 01:36:39.077
and when I think of the wonderful soul that is hidden away in that little ivory body I am

01:36:39.077 --> 01:36:46.377
filled with awe. You can dine with me tonight, Dorian, can't you? He shook his head. Tonight

01:36:46.917 --> 01:36:55.277
she is Imogen, he answered. Tomorrow night she will be Juliet. When is she Sybil Vane?

01:36:56.417 --> 01:37:04.597
Never. I congratulate you. How horrid you are! She is all the great heroines of the world in one.

01:37:04.597 --> 01:37:12.157
She is more than an individual, you laugh, but I tell you she has genius. I love her,

01:37:13.017 --> 01:37:20.317
and I must make her love me. You, who know all the secrets of life, tell me how to charm

01:37:20.317 --> 01:37:26.437
Sybil Vane to love me. I want to make Romeo jealous. I want the dead lovers of the world

01:37:26.437 --> 01:37:33.177
to hear our laughter and grow sad. I want a breath of our passion to stir their dust into

01:37:33.177 --> 01:37:38.157
consciousness, to wake their ashes into pain. My God, Harry, how I worship her!

01:37:38.577 --> 01:37:44.617
He was walking up and down the room as he spoke, hectic spots of red burned on his cheeks. He was

01:37:44.617 --> 01:37:51.257
terribly excited. Lord Henry watched him with a subtle sense of pleasure. How different he was

01:37:51.257 --> 01:37:58.077
now from the shy frightened boy he had met in Basil Hallward's studio. His nature had developed

01:37:58.077 --> 01:38:04.877
like a flower, had borne blossoms of scarlet flame. Out of its secret hiding-place had crept

01:38:04.877 --> 01:38:08.857
his soul, and desire had come to meet it on the way.

01:38:09.917 --> 01:38:17.317
And what do you propose to do? said Lord Henry at last. I want you and Basil to come with me

01:38:17.317 --> 01:38:22.597
some night and see her act. I've not the slightest fear of the result. You won't be able to refuse

01:38:22.597 --> 01:38:28.057
to recognise her genius. Then we must get her out of the Jews' hands. She's bound to him for

01:38:28.057 --> 01:38:33.937
three years, at least two years and eight months for the present time. I will have to pay him

01:38:33.937 --> 01:38:39.577
something, of course. When all that is settled, I will take a West End theatre and bring her out

01:38:39.577 --> 01:38:47.437
properly. She will make the world as mad as she has made me. Impossible, dear boy. Yes, she will.

01:38:48.577 --> 01:38:54.397
She has not merely art, consummate art instinct in her, but she has personality, too.

01:38:55.037 --> 01:39:01.057
And you have often told me that it is personalities, not principles, that move the age.

01:39:02.117 --> 01:39:09.677
Well, what night shall we go? Let me see. Today's Tuesday. Let us fix tomorrow.

01:39:10.637 --> 01:39:16.557
She plays Juliet tomorrow. All right, the Bristol at eight o'clock, and I will get Basil.

01:39:17.457 --> 01:39:23.037
Not eight. Hurry, please. Half-past six. We must be there before the curtain rises. You must see

01:39:23.037 --> 01:39:30.337
her in the first act, where she meets Romeo. Half-past six? What an hour!

01:39:31.377 --> 01:39:35.457
It will be like having a meat-tea, however, just as you wish.

01:39:36.417 --> 01:39:39.697
Shall you see Basil between this and then, or shall I write to him?

01:39:39.897 --> 01:39:44.897
Dear Basil, I have not laid eyes on him for a week. It is rather horrid of me,

01:39:45.117 --> 01:39:49.737
as he has sent me my portrait in the most wonderful frame designed by himself,

01:39:49.737 --> 01:39:54.397
and though I am a little jealous of it for being a whole month younger than I am,

01:39:54.397 --> 01:40:00.057
I must admit that I delight in it. Perhaps you would better write him. I don't want

01:40:00.057 --> 01:40:03.597
to see him alone. He says things that annoy me.

01:40:05.457 --> 01:40:12.017
He gives you good advice, I suppose. People are always giving away things they need most themselves.

01:40:13.057 --> 01:40:17.477
You don't mean to say that Basil has got any passion or any romance in him?

01:40:18.037 --> 01:40:22.357
I don't know whether he has any passion, but he certainly has romance,

01:40:22.917 --> 01:40:27.957
said Lord Henry, with an amused look in his eyes. Has he never let you know that?

01:40:28.897 --> 01:40:35.057
Never. I must ask him about it. I am rather surprised to hear it. He is the

01:40:35.057 --> 01:40:38.737
best of fellows, but he seems to me to be just a bit of a philistine.

01:40:39.757 --> 01:40:42.677
Since I have known you, Harry, I have discovered that.

01:40:44.277 --> 01:40:50.337
Basil, my dear boy, puts everything that is charming in him into his work.

01:40:51.037 --> 01:40:55.917
The consequence is that he has nothing left for life but his prejudices, his principles,

01:40:55.937 --> 01:41:01.277
and his common sense. The only artists I have ever known who are personally delightful are

01:41:01.277 --> 01:41:06.257
bad artists. Good artists give everything to their art, and consequently are perfectly

01:41:06.257 --> 01:41:11.317
uninteresting in themselves. A great poet, a really great poet,

01:41:12.177 --> 01:41:19.177
is the most unpoetical of all creatures, but inferior poets are absolutely fascinating.

01:41:20.977 --> 01:41:26.517
The worse their rhymes are, the more picturesque they look. The mere fact of having published a

01:41:26.517 --> 01:41:31.917
book of second-rate sonnets makes a man quite irresistible. He lives the poetry that he cannot

01:41:31.917 --> 01:41:36.437
write. The others write the poetry that they dare not realise.

01:41:37.477 --> 01:41:42.897
I wonder, is that really so, Harry? said Dorian Gray, putting some perfume on his

01:41:42.897 --> 01:41:46.817
handkerchief out of a small gold-topped bottle that stood on the table.

01:41:47.517 --> 01:41:53.337
It must be, if you say so. And now I must be off. Imogen is waiting for me.

01:41:53.497 --> 01:41:56.477
And don't forget about tomorrow. Good-bye.

01:41:56.477 --> 01:42:02.657
As he left the room, Lord Henry's heavy eyelids drooped, and he began to think.

01:42:03.657 --> 01:42:10.037
Certainly few people had ever interested him so much as Dorian Gray, and yet the lad's mad

01:42:10.037 --> 01:42:15.237
adoration of someone else caused him not the slightest pang of annoyance or jealousy.

01:42:16.157 --> 01:42:22.557
He was pleased by it. It made him a more interesting study. He had always been enthralled

01:42:22.557 --> 01:42:27.457
by the methods of science, but the ordinary subject matter of science had seemed to him

01:42:27.457 --> 01:42:35.297
trivial and of no import. And so he had begun by vivisecting himself as he had ended by vivisecting

01:42:35.297 --> 01:42:43.677
others. Human life. That appeared to him as the one thing worth investigating.

01:42:44.517 --> 01:42:51.337
There was nothing else of any value compared to it. It was true that as one watched life in its

01:42:51.337 --> 01:42:57.217
curious crucible of pain and pleasure, one could not wear over one's face a mask of glass,

01:42:57.617 --> 01:43:02.937
or keep the sulfurous fumes from troubling the brain and making the imagination turbid with

01:43:03.617 --> 01:43:11.717
monstrous fancies and misshapen dreams. There were poisons so subtle that to know their properties

01:43:11.717 --> 01:43:17.237
one had to sicken of them. There were maladies so strange that one had to pass through them

01:43:17.237 --> 01:43:22.997
if one sought to understand their nature. And yet what a great reward one received!

01:43:23.697 --> 01:43:29.717
How wonderful the whole world became to one! To note the curious hard logic of passion

01:43:29.717 --> 01:43:34.077
and the emotional coloured life of the intellect, to observe where they met

01:43:34.077 --> 01:43:39.977
and where they separated, at one point they became one and at what point they were at discord,

01:43:40.497 --> 01:43:44.577
there was a delight in that. What matter was the cost?

01:43:45.097 --> 01:43:48.537
One could never pay too high a price for any sensation.

01:43:49.837 --> 01:43:56.677
He was conscious, and the thought brought a gleam of pleasure into his brown-ugget eyes,

01:43:57.457 --> 01:44:02.577
that it was through certain words of his, musical words said with musical utterance,

01:44:02.957 --> 01:44:08.497
that Dorian Gray's soul had turned to this white girl and bowed in worship before her.

01:44:08.497 --> 01:44:14.777
To a large extent the lad was his own creation. He had made him premature,

01:44:15.257 --> 01:44:20.097
that was something. Ordinary people waited till life disclosed to them its secret,

01:44:20.197 --> 01:44:26.017
but to the few, to the elect, the mysteries of life were revealed before the veil was

01:44:26.017 --> 01:44:32.077
drawn away. Sometimes this was the effect of art, and chiefly of the art of literature,

01:44:32.077 --> 01:44:37.677
which dealt immediately with the passions and the intellect. But now and then a complex

01:44:37.677 --> 01:44:43.457
personality took the place, and assumed the office of art was indeed, in its way,

01:44:43.937 --> 01:44:50.617
a real work of art, life having its elaborate masterpieces just as poetry has, or sculpture,

01:44:50.917 --> 01:44:58.097
or painting. Yes, the lad was premature. He was gathering his harvest while it was yet spring.

01:44:58.097 --> 01:45:03.917
The pulse and passion of youth were in him, but he was becoming self-conscious.

01:45:04.517 --> 01:45:09.757
It was delightful to watch him. With his beautiful face, and his beautiful soul,

01:45:09.937 --> 01:45:15.957
he was a thing to wonder at. It was no matter how it all ended, or was destined to end,

01:45:15.977 --> 01:45:21.217
he was like one of those gracious figures in a pageant or a play, whose joys seemed too

01:45:21.217 --> 01:45:30.917
from one, but whose sorrows stir one sense of beauty, and whose wounds are like red roses.

01:45:32.017 --> 01:45:39.757
Soul and body, body and soul, how mysterious they were! There was animalism in the soul,

01:45:39.937 --> 01:45:45.647
and the body had its moments of spirituality. The senses could refine, and the intellect could

01:45:45.647 --> 01:45:52.727
grade. Who could say where the fleshly impulse ceased, or the psychical impulse began?

01:45:54.067 --> 01:46:01.027
How shallow were the arbitrary definitions of ordinary psychologists, and yet how difficult

01:46:01.027 --> 01:46:07.107
to decide between the claims of the various schools? Was the soul a shadow seated in the

01:46:07.107 --> 01:46:12.427
house of sin, or was the body really in the soul, as Giordano Bruno thought?

01:46:12.427 --> 01:46:19.527
The separation of spirit from matter was a mystery, and the union of spirit with matter

01:46:19.527 --> 01:46:26.647
was a mystery also. He began to wonder whether we should ever make psychology so absolute a science

01:46:26.647 --> 01:46:33.827
that each little spring of life should be revealed to us. As it was, we always misunderstood ourselves,

01:46:33.967 --> 01:46:41.027
and rarely understood others. Experience was of no ethical value. It was merely the name we gave

01:46:41.027 --> 01:46:51.007
to our mistakes. Men had, as a rule, regarded it as a mode of warning, had claimed for it a certain

01:46:51.007 --> 01:46:57.787
moral efficacy in the formation of character, had praised it as something that taught us what to

01:46:57.787 --> 01:47:05.127
follow, and showed us what to avoid. But there was no motive power in experience. It was as little of

01:47:05.127 --> 01:47:11.467
an active cause as conscience itself. All that it really demonstrated was that our future would be

01:47:11.467 --> 01:47:17.527
the same as our past, and that the sin we had done once, and with loathing, we would do many times

01:47:17.527 --> 01:47:24.427
with joy. It was clear to him that the experimental method was only a method by which one could arrive

01:47:24.427 --> 01:47:30.667
at any scientific analysis of the passions, and certainly Dorian Gray was a subject made to his

01:47:30.667 --> 01:47:37.507
hand, and seemed to promise rich and fruitful results. His sudden mad love for Sybil was a

01:47:37.507 --> 01:47:44.147
psychological phenomenon of no small interest. There was no doubt that curiosity had much to do

01:47:44.147 --> 01:47:51.407
with it—curiosity and the desire for new experiences. Yet it was not a simple but rather

01:47:51.407 --> 01:47:58.987
a very complex passion. What there was in it, of the purely sensuous instinct of boyhood,

01:47:58.987 --> 01:48:04.627
had been transformed by the workings of the imagination, changed into something that seemed

01:48:04.627 --> 01:48:12.767
to the boy himself to be remote from sense, and was for that very reason all the more dangerous.

01:48:13.547 --> 01:48:20.307
It was the passions about whose origin we deceived ourselves that tyrannized most strongly over us.

01:48:21.127 --> 01:48:27.267
Our weakest motives were those of whose nature we were conscious. It often happened that,

01:48:27.267 --> 01:48:31.807
when we thought we were experimenting on others, we were really experimenting on ourselves.

01:48:32.807 --> 01:48:37.227
While Lord Henry saw dreaming of these things, a knock came to the door, and his valet entered,

01:48:37.627 --> 01:48:44.407
and reminded him it was time to dress for dinner. He got up, looked out onto the street. The sunset

01:48:44.407 --> 01:48:50.227
had smitten into scarlet gold the upper windows of the houses opposite. The panes glowed like glass

01:48:50.227 --> 01:48:57.907
of heated metal. The sky above was like a faded rose. He thought of Dorian Gray's

01:48:58.967 --> 01:49:03.447
young fiery-coloured life, and wondered how it was all going to end.

01:49:04.647 --> 01:49:10.067
When he arrived home, about half past twelve o'clock, he saw a telegram lying on the whole

01:49:10.067 --> 01:49:19.287
table. He opened it, and found it was from Dorian. It was to tell him that he was engaged to be

01:49:19.287 --> 01:49:21.467
Sibyl Vane.

01:50:01.592 --> 01:50:08.012
"'I suppose you have heard the news, Basil?' said Lord Henry on the following evening,

01:50:08.432 --> 01:50:13.652
as Hallward was shown into a little private room at the Bristol, where dinner had been

01:50:13.652 --> 01:50:14.692
laid for three.

01:50:16.132 --> 01:50:21.092
"'No, Harry,' answered Hallward, giving his hat and coat to the bowing-waiter.

01:50:21.132 --> 01:50:22.292
"'What is it?

01:50:22.372 --> 01:50:24.132
Nothing about politics, I hope.

01:50:24.392 --> 01:50:26.452
They don't interest me.

01:50:27.212 --> 01:50:32.472
"'There is hardly a single person in the House of Commons worth painting, though many of

01:50:32.472 --> 01:50:35.292
them would be the better for a little whitewashing.'

01:50:36.552 --> 01:50:42.132
"'Dorian Grey is engaged to be married,' said Lord Henry, watching him as he spoke.

01:50:42.912 --> 01:50:48.912
Hallward turned perfectly pale, and a curious look flashed for a moment into his eyes and

01:50:48.912 --> 01:50:51.092
then passed away, leaving them dull.

01:50:52.692 --> 01:50:55.552
"'Dorian engaged to be married?' he cried.

01:50:56.492 --> 01:50:57.092
"'Impossible!

01:50:57.092 --> 01:50:59.012
It is perfectly true.'

01:50:59.012 --> 01:50:59.892
"'To whom?'

01:50:59.892 --> 01:51:02.032
"'To some little actress or other.

01:51:02.172 --> 01:51:03.312
I can't believe it.

01:51:03.532 --> 01:51:04.892
Dorian is far too sensible.

01:51:05.732 --> 01:51:11.172
Dorian is far too wise not to do foolish things now and then, my dear Basil.'

01:51:12.912 --> 01:51:19.292
"'Marriage is hardly a thing that one can do now and then, Harry,' said Hallward, smiling.

01:51:19.672 --> 01:51:20.852
"'Except in America.

01:51:21.512 --> 01:51:23.452
But I didn't say he was married.

01:51:23.452 --> 01:51:26.292
"'I said he was engaged to be married.

01:51:26.512 --> 01:51:28.072
There is a great difference.

01:51:28.732 --> 01:51:34.232
I have a distinct remembrance of being married, but I have no recollection at all of being

01:51:34.232 --> 01:51:34.932
engaged.

01:51:35.412 --> 01:51:39.052
I am inclined to think that I was never engaged.'

01:51:40.112 --> 01:51:43.232
"'But think of Dorian's birth and position and wealth.

01:51:43.232 --> 01:51:46.132
It would be absurd for him to marry so much beneath him.

01:51:46.292 --> 01:51:49.012
If you want him to marry this girl, tell him that, Basil.

01:51:49.112 --> 01:51:50.472
He is sure to do it then.

01:51:51.032 --> 01:51:56.072
Whenever a man does a thoroughly stupid thing, it is always for the noblest motives.'

01:51:57.672 --> 01:51:59.672
"'I hope the girl is good, Harry.

01:51:59.992 --> 01:52:04.832
I don't want to see Dorian tied to some vile creature who might degrade his nature and

01:52:04.832 --> 01:52:05.872
ruin his intellect.

01:52:06.372 --> 01:52:08.532
Oh, she is more than good.

01:52:08.912 --> 01:52:14.732
She is beautiful,' murmured Lord Henry, sipping a glass of vermouth and orange bitters.

01:52:15.572 --> 01:52:21.152
"'Dorian says she is beautiful, and he is not often wrong about things of that kind.

01:52:21.772 --> 01:52:27.012
Your portrait of him has quickened his appreciation of the personal appearance of other people.

01:52:27.672 --> 01:52:31.732
It has had that excellent effect, among others.

01:52:32.252 --> 01:52:36.532
We are to see her tonight, if that boy doesn't forget his appointment.'

01:52:36.532 --> 01:52:41.812
"'But do you approve of it, Harry?' asked Hallward, walking up and down the room and

01:52:41.812 --> 01:52:42.552
biting his lip.

01:52:42.552 --> 01:52:44.472
"'You can't approve of it, really.

01:52:44.712 --> 01:52:47.152
It is some silly infatuation.

01:52:48.212 --> 01:52:52.652
I never approve or disapprove of anything now.

01:52:53.192 --> 01:52:56.012
It is an absurd attitude to take towards life.

01:52:56.352 --> 01:53:00.372
We are not sent into the world to err of our moral prejudices.

01:53:00.812 --> 01:53:06.532
I never take any notice of what common people say, and I never interfere with what charming

01:53:06.532 --> 01:53:07.252
people do.

01:53:07.252 --> 01:53:14.772
If a personality infatuates me, whatever the personality chooses to do is absolutely delightful

01:53:14.772 --> 01:53:15.312
to me.

01:53:15.752 --> 01:53:19.912
Dorian Gray falls in love with a beautiful girl who acts Shakespeare and proposes to

01:53:19.912 --> 01:53:20.552
marry her.

01:53:20.832 --> 01:53:21.552
Why not?

01:53:22.012 --> 01:53:25.892
If he wanted Messalina, he would be none the less interesting.

01:53:26.672 --> 01:53:29.272
You know I am not a champion of marriage.

01:53:30.112 --> 01:53:33.332
The real drawback to marriage is that it makes one unselfish.

01:53:33.332 --> 01:53:37.432
And unselfish people are colourless.

01:53:37.712 --> 01:53:39.332
They lack individuality.

01:53:40.292 --> 01:53:44.812
Still, there are certain temperaments that marriage makes more complex.

01:53:45.192 --> 01:53:48.772
They retain their egotism and add to it many other egos.

01:53:49.212 --> 01:53:51.452
They are forced to have more than one life.

01:53:51.492 --> 01:53:53.652
They become more highly organised.

01:53:54.252 --> 01:54:00.392
Besides, every experience is of value, and whatever one may say against marriage it is

01:54:00.392 --> 01:54:01.912
certainly an experience.

01:54:01.912 --> 01:54:07.672
I hope that Dorian Gray will make this girl his wife, passionately adore her for six months,

01:54:07.972 --> 01:54:10.752
and then suddenly become fascinated by someone else.

01:54:10.872 --> 01:54:13.432
He would be a wonderful study.

01:54:14.352 --> 01:54:16.672
You don't mean all that, Harry.

01:54:16.772 --> 01:54:18.132
You know you don't.

01:54:18.532 --> 01:54:22.272
If Dorian Gray's life were spoiled, no one would be sorrier than yourself.

01:54:22.632 --> 01:54:25.032
You are much better than you pretend to be.

01:54:25.712 --> 01:54:27.192
Lord Henry laughed.

01:54:29.132 --> 01:54:35.352
The reason we all like to think so well of others is that we are all afraid for ourselves.

01:54:36.232 --> 01:54:38.592
The basis of optimism is sheer terror.

01:54:39.172 --> 01:54:46.492
We think that we are generous because we credit our neighbour with those virtues that are likely to benefit ourselves.

01:54:46.852 --> 01:54:49.952
We praise the banker that we may overdraw our account,

01:54:49.952 --> 01:54:54.512
and we find good qualities in the highwayman in the hope that he may spare our pockets.

01:54:55.312 --> 01:54:57.492
I mean everything I have said.

01:54:58.232 --> 01:55:06.972
I have the greatest contempt for optimism, and as for a spoiled life, no life is spoiled but one whose growth is arrested.

01:55:07.612 --> 01:55:11.152
If you want to mar a nature, you merely have to reform it.

01:55:11.272 --> 01:55:12.572
But here is Dorian himself.

01:55:12.992 --> 01:55:15.132
He will tell you more than I can.

01:55:15.132 --> 01:55:26.792
Oh, my dear Harry, my dear Basil, you both must congratulate me," said the boy, throwing off his evening cape with his satin-lined wings and shaking each of his friends by the hand in turn.

01:55:27.452 --> 01:55:29.312
I have never been so happy.

01:55:29.812 --> 01:55:38.272
Of course it is sudden, all really delightful things are, and yet it seems to me to be the one thing I have been looking for all my life.

01:55:38.952 --> 01:55:43.232
He was flushed with excitement and pleasure, and looked extraordinarily handsome.

01:55:44.012 --> 01:55:48.272
I hope you will always be very happy, Dorian," said Hallward.

01:55:48.312 --> 01:55:52.472
But I don't quite forgive you for not letting me know of your engagement.

01:55:52.932 --> 01:55:54.292
You let Harry know.

01:55:55.032 --> 01:56:03.652
And I don't forgive you for being late for dinner, broken Lord Henry, putting his hand on the lad's shoulder and smiling as he spoke.

01:56:04.372 --> 01:56:12.072
Come, let us sit down and try what the new chef here is like, and then you will tell us how it all came about.

01:56:12.812 --> 01:56:18.832
There is really not much to tell," cried Dorian, as they took their seats at the small round table.

01:56:19.452 --> 01:56:21.492
What happened was simply this.

01:56:22.312 --> 01:56:33.252
After I left you yesterday evening, Harry, I had some dinner at that curious Italian restaurant in Rupert Street you introduced me to, and went down afterwards to the theatre.

01:56:33.252 --> 01:56:41.812
Sybil was playing Rosalind. Of course the scenery was dreadful and the Orlando absurd, but Sybil—oh, you should have seen her.

01:56:42.012 --> 01:56:45.552
When she came on in her boy's dress she was perfectly wonderful.

01:56:46.152 --> 01:56:58.572
She wore a moss-coloured velvet jerkin with cinnamon sleeves, a slim brown cross-cutted hose, a dainty little green cap with a hock's feather cottoned jewel, and a hooded cloak lined with dull red.

01:56:58.572 --> 01:57:03.132
She never seemed to me more exquisite.

01:57:03.992 --> 01:57:08.952
She had all the delicate grace of that Tanegra figurine that you have in your study, Basil.

01:57:09.832 --> 01:57:14.272
Her hair clustered round her face like dark leaves round a pale rose.

01:57:14.892 --> 01:57:15.952
As for her acting?

01:57:16.832 --> 01:57:20.712
Well, you will see her tonight. She is simply a born artist.

01:57:21.352 --> 01:57:25.032
I sat in the dingy box, absolutely enthralled.

01:57:25.032 --> 01:57:32.072
I forgot I was in London, and in the nineteenth century I was away with my love in a forest that no man had ever seen.

01:57:32.992 --> 01:57:36.512
After the performance was over I went behind and spoke to her.

01:57:37.252 --> 01:57:42.992
As we were sitting together, suddenly there came a look into her eyes that I had never seen there before.

01:57:43.632 --> 01:57:46.772
My lips moved towards hers, we kissed each other.

01:57:48.992 --> 01:57:52.152
I can't describe to you what I felt at that moment.

01:57:52.152 --> 01:57:58.792
It seemed to me that all my life had been narrowed to one perfect point of rose-coloured joy.

01:57:59.472 --> 01:58:03.112
She trembled all over and shook like a white narcissus.

01:58:03.572 --> 01:58:06.432
Then she flung herself on her knees and kissed my hands.

01:58:06.912 --> 01:58:09.832
I feel that I should not tell you all of this, but I can't help it.

01:58:10.092 --> 01:58:14.092
Of course our engagement is a dead secret. She has not even told her own mother.

01:58:14.592 --> 01:58:16.692
I don't know what my guardians will say.

01:58:17.292 --> 01:58:19.292
Lord Radley is sure to be furious.

01:58:19.852 --> 01:58:24.732
But I don't care. I shall be of age and less than a year, and then I can do what I like.

01:58:25.332 --> 01:58:31.232
I have been right, Basil, haven't I, to take my love out of poetry and define my wife in Shakespeare's plays?

01:58:32.012 --> 01:58:35.812
Lips that Shakespeare taught to speak have whispered their secret in my ear.

01:58:35.832 --> 01:58:41.732
I have had the arms of Rosalind around me, and kissed Juliet on the mouth.

01:58:42.912 --> 01:58:49.192
Yes, Dorian, I suppose you were right, said Hallward, slowly.

01:58:50.412 --> 01:58:54.412
Have you seen her to-day? asked Lord Henry.

01:58:55.272 --> 01:58:56.572
Dorian shook his head.

01:58:57.792 --> 01:59:03.072
I left her in the forest of Arden. I shall find her in an orchard in Verona.

01:59:03.932 --> 01:59:07.652
Lord Henry sipped his champagne in a meditative manner.

01:59:08.592 --> 01:59:16.812
At what particular point did you mention the word marriage, Dorian, and what did she say in answer?

01:59:17.432 --> 01:59:19.832
Perhaps you forgot all about it.

01:59:20.212 --> 01:59:27.792
My dear Harry, I did not treat it as a business transaction, and I did not make a formal proposal.

01:59:28.072 --> 01:59:32.652
I told her that I loved her, and she said she was not worthy to be my wife.

01:59:32.652 --> 01:59:36.932
She was not worthy. Why, the whole world is nothing to me compared to her.

01:59:38.012 --> 01:59:44.272
Women are wonderfully practical, murmured Lord Henry, much more practical than we are.

01:59:44.772 --> 01:59:51.912
In situations of that kind we often forget to say anything about marriage, and they always remind us.

01:59:53.012 --> 01:59:55.132
Hallward laid his hand upon his arm.

01:59:55.712 --> 01:59:58.772
Don't, Harry, you have annoyed Dorian.

01:59:58.772 --> 02:00:05.972
He is not like other men. He would never bring misery upon anyone. His nature is far too fine for that.

02:00:07.152 --> 02:00:09.172
Lord Henry looked across the table.

02:00:09.652 --> 02:00:12.852
Dorian is never annoyed with me, he answered.

02:00:13.092 --> 02:00:18.892
I ask the question for the best reason possible, for the only reason, indeed, that excuses one asking any question.

02:00:19.752 --> 02:00:20.312
Curiosity.

02:00:20.992 --> 02:00:31.172
I have a theory that it always happens that women propose to us, and not we who propose to the women, except, of course, in middle-class life.

02:00:31.472 --> 02:00:35.972
But then the middle classes are not modern.

02:00:36.712 --> 02:00:39.332
Dorian Gray laughed and tossed his head.

02:00:39.892 --> 02:00:43.392
You are quite incorrigible, Harry, but I don't mind.

02:00:43.392 --> 02:00:45.652
It is impossible to be angry with you.

02:00:45.772 --> 02:00:51.452
When you see Sibyl Vane you will feel that the man who could wrong her would be a beast without a heart.

02:00:52.112 --> 02:00:55.912
I cannot understand how anyone can wish to shame what he loves.

02:00:56.552 --> 02:00:58.772
I love Sibyl Vane.

02:00:59.192 --> 02:01:04.732
I wish to place her on a pedestal of gold and to see the world worship the woman who is mine.

02:01:05.852 --> 02:01:06.732
What is marriage?

02:01:06.732 --> 02:01:12.992
An irrevocable vow, and it is an irrevocable vow that I want to take.

02:01:13.952 --> 02:01:17.592
Her trust makes me faithful, her belief makes me good.

02:01:18.072 --> 02:01:21.732
When I am with her I regret all that you have taught me.

02:01:21.812 --> 02:01:25.192
I become different from what you have known me to be.

02:01:25.472 --> 02:01:26.892
I am changed.

02:01:27.272 --> 02:01:36.552
And the mere touch of Sibyl Vane's hands makes me forget you and all your wrong, fascinating, poisonous, delightful theories.

02:01:37.232 --> 02:01:42.372
You will always like me, Dorian, said Lord Henry.

02:01:43.272 --> 02:01:45.352
Will you have some coffee, you fellows?

02:01:45.672 --> 02:01:50.472
Waiter, bring coffee and fine champagne and some cigarettes.

02:01:50.692 --> 02:01:52.792
No, no, don't mind the cigarettes, I have some.

02:01:53.372 --> 02:01:55.652
Basil, I can't allow you to smoke cigars.

02:01:55.832 --> 02:01:57.152
You must have a cigarette.

02:01:57.572 --> 02:02:00.012
A cigarette is the perfect type of a perfect pleasure.

02:02:00.132 --> 02:02:02.872
It is exquisite, and it leaves one unsatisfied.

02:02:03.572 --> 02:02:04.552
What more can one want?

02:02:04.552 --> 02:02:08.852
Yes, Dorian, you will always be fond of me.

02:02:09.312 --> 02:02:14.412
I represent to you all the sins you have never had the courage to commit.

02:02:15.252 --> 02:02:17.732
What nonsense you talk, Harry!

02:02:18.212 --> 02:02:24.792
cried Dorian Gray, lighting a cigarette from a fire-breathing silver dragon that the waiter had placed on the table.

02:02:25.812 --> 02:02:27.472
Let us go down to the theatre.

02:02:27.992 --> 02:02:31.812
When you see Sibyl you will have a new ideal of life.

02:02:31.812 --> 02:02:36.972
She will represent something to you that you have never known.

02:02:38.232 --> 02:02:44.172
I have known everything, said Lord Henry, with a sad look in his eyes.

02:02:44.972 --> 02:02:48.452
But I am always ready for a new emotion.

02:02:49.372 --> 02:02:52.332
I am afraid there is no such thing.

02:02:52.712 --> 02:02:54.292
For me, at any rate.

02:02:54.672 --> 02:02:57.252
Still, your wonderful girl may thrill me.

02:02:57.432 --> 02:02:58.412
I love acting.

02:02:58.872 --> 02:03:00.972
It is so much more real than life.

02:03:00.972 --> 02:03:01.852
Let us go.

02:03:01.992 --> 02:03:04.112
Dorian, you will come with me.

02:03:04.272 --> 02:03:08.712
I am so sorry, Basil, but there is only room for two in the Brome.

02:03:09.432 --> 02:03:11.752
You must follow us in a hensome.

02:03:12.112 --> 02:03:15.632
They got up and put on their coats, sipping their coffee standing.

02:03:16.472 --> 02:03:18.652
Hallward was silent and preoccupied.

02:03:18.792 --> 02:03:20.572
There was a gloom over him.

02:03:21.172 --> 02:03:27.472
He could not bear this marriage, and yet it seemed to him to be better than many other things that might have happened.

02:03:28.152 --> 02:03:31.712
After a few moments they all passed downstairs.

02:03:32.352 --> 02:03:38.492
He drove off by himself, as had been arranged, and watched the flashing lights of the little Brome in front of him.

02:03:39.692 --> 02:03:42.292
A strange sense of loss came over him.

02:03:42.892 --> 02:03:47.892
He felt that Dorian Gray would never again be to him all that he had been in the past.

02:03:48.452 --> 02:03:53.952
His eyes darkened, and the crowded, flaring streets became blurred to him.

02:03:53.952 --> 02:04:01.272
When the cab drew up at the doors of the theatre, it seemed to him that he had grown years older.

02:04:41.077 --> 02:04:47.557
For some reason or other the house was crowded that night, and the fat Jew manager who met

02:04:47.557 --> 02:04:54.017
them at the door was beaming from ear to ear with an oily, tremulous smile. He escorted

02:04:54.017 --> 02:04:59.977
them to their box with a sort of pompous humility, waving his fat jeweled hands and talking at

02:04:59.977 --> 02:05:06.217
the top of his voice. Dorian Gray loathed him more than ever. He felt as if he had come

02:05:06.217 --> 02:05:13.777
Miranda and had been met by Caliban. Lord Henry, upon the other hand, rather liked him. At least

02:05:13.777 --> 02:05:19.297
he declared he did, and insisted on shaking him by the hand, and assured him that he was proud to

02:05:19.297 --> 02:05:26.897
be a man who had discovered a real genius and gone bankrupt over Shakespeare. Hallward amused himself

02:05:26.897 --> 02:05:32.577
with watching the faces in the pit. The heat was terribly oppressive, and the huge sunlight

02:05:32.577 --> 02:05:38.637
flamed like a monstrous dahlia with petals of fire. The youths in the gallery had taken off

02:05:38.637 --> 02:05:43.917
their coats and waistcoats and hung them over the side. They talked to each other across the

02:05:43.917 --> 02:05:49.597
theatre and shared their oranges with the tawdry painted girls who sat by them. Some women were

02:05:49.597 --> 02:05:55.857
laughing in the pit. Their voices were horribly shrill and discordant. The sound of popping corks

02:05:55.857 --> 02:05:57.057
came from the bar.

02:05:58.157 --> 02:06:03.057
What a place to find one's divinity in, said Lord Henry.

02:06:04.957 --> 02:06:11.657
Yes, answered Dorian Gray. It was here I found her, and she is divine beyond all living things.

02:06:12.297 --> 02:06:17.057
When she acts, he will forget everything. These common people here, with their coarse faces and

02:06:17.057 --> 02:06:23.237
brutal gestures, become quite different when she is on the stage. They sit silently and watch her.

02:06:23.237 --> 02:06:28.977
They weep and laugh as she wills them to. She makes them as responsive as a violin.

02:06:29.197 --> 02:06:34.977
She spiritualizes them. And one feels that they are of the same flesh and blood as oneself.

02:06:35.637 --> 02:06:41.577
Oh, I hope not, murmured Lord Henry, who was scanning the occupants of the gallery through

02:06:41.577 --> 02:06:42.417
his opera-glass.

02:06:43.377 --> 02:06:48.617
Don't pay any attention to him, Dorian, said Hallward. I understand what you mean,

02:06:48.617 --> 02:06:54.457
and I believe in this girl. Any one you love must be marvelous, and any girl that has the

02:06:54.457 --> 02:07:01.117
effect you describe must be fine and noble. To spiritualize one's age, that is something

02:07:01.117 --> 02:07:08.517
worth doing. If this girl can give a soul to those who have lived without one, if she can create the

02:07:08.517 --> 02:07:14.237
sense of beauty in people whose lives have been sordid and ugly, if she can strip them of their

02:07:14.237 --> 02:07:20.357
selfishness and lend them tears for sorrows that are not their own, she is worthy of all your

02:07:20.357 --> 02:07:27.177
adoration, worthy of the adoration of the world. This marriage is quite right. I did not think so

02:07:27.177 --> 02:07:33.897
at first, but I admit it now. God made Sibyl Vane for you. Without her, you would have been

02:07:33.897 --> 02:07:34.377
incomplete.

02:07:35.857 --> 02:07:42.637
Thanks, Basil, answered Dorian Gray, pressing his hand. I knew that you would understand me.

02:07:42.637 --> 02:07:49.417
Harry is so cynical, he terrifies me. But here is the orchestra. It is quite dreadful, but

02:07:49.797 --> 02:07:54.957
it only lasts for about five minutes. Then the curtain rises, and you will see the girl to whom

02:07:54.957 --> 02:08:00.457
I am going to give all my life, to whom I have given everything that is good in me.

02:08:01.777 --> 02:08:06.617
Quarter of an hour afterwards, amidst the extraordinary turmoil of applause,

02:08:06.857 --> 02:08:09.137
Sibyl Vane stepped on to the stage.

02:08:10.357 --> 02:08:15.557
Yes, she was certainly lovely to look at, one of the loveliest creatures, Lord Henry thought,

02:08:15.797 --> 02:08:22.577
that he had ever seen. There was something of the fawn in her shy grace and startled eyes.

02:08:23.417 --> 02:08:29.477
A faint blush, like the shadow of a rose in a mirror of silver, came to her cheeks as she

02:08:29.477 --> 02:08:39.117
glanced at the crowded, enthusiastic house. She stepped back a few paces, and her lips seemed to

02:08:39.117 --> 02:08:43.977
applaud. Dorian Gray sat motionless, gazing on her like a man in a dream.

02:08:44.897 --> 02:08:48.157
Lord Henry peered through his opera glass, murmuring,

02:08:50.317 --> 02:08:51.477
Charming, charming!

02:08:52.577 --> 02:08:58.397
The scene was the hall of Capulet's house, and Romeo, in his pilgrim's dress, had entered

02:08:58.397 --> 02:09:04.397
with Mercutio and his friends. The band, such as it was, struck up a few bars of music,

02:09:04.397 --> 02:09:10.477
and the dance began. Through the crowd of ungainly, shabbily dressed actors,

02:09:10.697 --> 02:09:16.077
Sibyl Vane moved like a creature from a finer world. Her body swayed as she danced,

02:09:16.457 --> 02:09:23.197
as a plant sways in the water. The curves of her throat were like the curves of a white lily.

02:09:24.037 --> 02:09:26.697
Her hands seemed to be made of cool ivory.

02:09:27.797 --> 02:09:35.457
Yet she was curiously listless. She showed no sign of joy when her eyes rested on Romeo,

02:09:35.637 --> 02:09:40.397
the few lines she had to speak. Good pilgrim, you do wrong your hand too much,

02:09:40.697 --> 02:09:46.297
which manly devotion shows in this, for saints have hands that pilgrim hands do touch,

02:09:46.617 --> 02:09:52.857
and palm to palm is holy Palmer's kiss. With the brief dialogue that follows,

02:09:52.857 --> 02:09:58.597
were spoken in thoroughly artificial manner. The voice was exquisite, but from the point of

02:09:58.597 --> 02:10:06.457
view of tone it was absolutely false. It was wrong in colour. It took away all the life from

02:10:06.457 --> 02:10:13.557
the verse. It made the passion unreal. Dorian Gray grew pale as he watched her.

02:10:13.957 --> 02:10:19.417
Neither of his friends dared to say anything to him. She seemed to them to be absolutely

02:10:19.417 --> 02:10:27.257
incompetent. They were horribly disappointed. Yet they felt that the true test of any Juliet

02:10:27.257 --> 02:10:32.277
is the balcony scene of the second act. They waited for that. If she failed there,

02:10:32.637 --> 02:10:38.457
there was nothing in her. She looked charming as she came out in the moonlight.

02:10:39.017 --> 02:10:45.777
That could not be denied. But the stageyness of her acting was unbearable, and grew worse

02:10:45.777 --> 02:10:51.437
as she went on. Her gestures became absurdly artificial. She overemphasised everything that

02:10:51.437 --> 02:10:59.137
she had to say. The beautiful passage, Thou knowest the mask of night is on my face,

02:10:59.537 --> 02:11:05.037
else would a maiden blush bepaint my cheek for that which thou hast heard me speak to-night,

02:11:05.697 --> 02:11:11.137
was declaimed with the painful precision of a schoolgirl who had been taught to recite by

02:11:11.137 --> 02:11:17.297
some second-rate professor of elocution. When she leaned over the balcony and came to those

02:11:17.297 --> 02:11:24.957
wonderful lines, although I joy in thee, I have no joy of this contract to-night. It is too rash,

02:11:25.197 --> 02:11:32.157
too unadvised, too sudden, too like the lightning which doth cease to be ere one can say it

02:11:32.157 --> 02:11:39.277
lightens. Sweet, good-night. This bud of love by summer's ripening breath may prove a beauty's

02:11:39.277 --> 02:11:47.177
flower when next we meet. She spoke the words as if they conveyed no meaning to her. It was not

02:11:47.177 --> 02:11:52.897
nervousness. Indeed, so far from being nervous she seemed absolutely self-contained. It was

02:11:53.957 --> 02:12:02.357
simply bad art. She was a complete failure. Even the common uneducated audience of the

02:12:02.357 --> 02:12:07.157
pit and gallery lost their interest in the play. They got restless and began to talk loudly and to

02:12:07.837 --> 02:12:13.297
The Jew manager, who was standing at the back of the dress circle, stamped and swore with rage.

02:12:13.897 --> 02:12:22.057
The only person unmoved was the girl herself. When the second act was over there came a storm

02:12:22.057 --> 02:12:26.377
of hisses and Lord Henry got up from his chair and put on his coat.

02:12:27.177 --> 02:12:31.897
She's quite beautiful, Dorian, he said, but she can't act. Let us go.

02:12:32.757 --> 02:12:37.817
I am going to see the play through, answered the lad in a hard, bitter voice.

02:12:38.277 --> 02:12:44.157
I am awfully sorry that I have made you waste an evening, Harry. I apologize to both of you.

02:12:44.997 --> 02:12:51.797
My dear Dorian, I should think Miss Vane was ill, interrupted Hallward. We will come some

02:12:51.797 --> 02:12:59.377
other night. I wish she was ill, he rejoined, but she seems to me to be simply callous and cold.

02:12:59.377 --> 02:13:03.957
She has entirely altered. Last night she was a great artist.

02:13:04.957 --> 02:13:08.697
Tonight she is merely a commonplace, mediocre actress.

02:13:09.797 --> 02:13:15.937
Don't talk like that about anyone you love, Dorian. Love is a more wonderful thing than art.

02:13:16.637 --> 02:13:21.097
They are both simply forms of imitation, murmured Lord Henry.

02:13:22.117 --> 02:13:28.577
But do let us go. Dorian, you must not stay here any longer. It is not good for one's

02:13:28.577 --> 02:13:34.257
morals to see bad acting. Besides, I don't suppose you will want your wife to act,

02:13:34.417 --> 02:13:38.837
so what does it matter if she plays Juliet like a wooden doll? She is very lovely,

02:13:39.217 --> 02:13:43.797
and if she knows as little about life as she does about acting, she will be a delightful experience.

02:13:44.597 --> 02:13:47.677
There are only two kinds of people who are really fascinating,

02:13:48.197 --> 02:13:53.077
people who know absolutely everything and people who know absolutely nothing.

02:13:53.677 --> 02:13:56.657
Oh, good heavens, my dear boy, don't look so tragic!

02:13:57.457 --> 02:14:01.697
The secret of remaining young is never to have an emotion that is unbecoming.

02:14:03.077 --> 02:14:08.177
Come to the club with Basil and myself. We will smoke cigarettes and drink to the beauty of

02:14:08.177 --> 02:14:11.277
Sybilvane. She is beautiful. What more can you want?

02:14:12.137 --> 02:14:17.157
Please go away, Harry, cried the lad. I really want to be alone.

02:14:18.117 --> 02:14:20.657
Basil, you don't mind my asking you to go.

02:14:21.197 --> 02:14:27.537
Can't you see that my heart is breaking? The hot tears came to his eyes. His lips trembled, and

02:14:27.537 --> 02:14:31.897
rushing to the back of the box, he leaned up against the wall, hiding his face in his hands.

02:14:33.617 --> 02:14:39.917
Let us go, Basil, said Lord Henry, with a strange tenderness in his voice,

02:14:40.657 --> 02:14:42.937
and the two young men passed out together.

02:14:44.217 --> 02:14:49.017
A few moments afterwards the footlights flared up, and the curtain rose on the third act.

02:14:49.897 --> 02:14:54.237
Dorian Gray went back to his seat. He looked pale and proud and indifferent.

02:14:55.037 --> 02:14:59.737
The play dragged on and seemed interminable. Half the audience went out,

02:14:59.877 --> 02:15:04.097
tramping in heavy boots and laughing. The whole thing was a fiasco.

02:15:04.837 --> 02:15:07.597
The last act was played to almost empty benches.

02:15:08.817 --> 02:15:14.437
As soon as it was over, Dorian Gray rushed behind the scenes into the green room.

02:15:14.917 --> 02:15:18.557
The girl was standing alone there, with a look of triumph on her face.

02:15:19.237 --> 02:15:23.657
Her eyes were lit with an exquisite fire. There was a radiance about her.

02:15:23.677 --> 02:15:27.397
Her parted lips were smiling over some secret of their own.

02:15:28.597 --> 02:15:33.897
When he entered, she looked at him, and an expression of infinite joy came over her.

02:15:35.217 --> 02:15:39.177
"'How badly I acted to-night, Dorian!' she cried.

02:15:40.397 --> 02:15:43.217
"'Horribly,' he answered, gazing at her in amazement.

02:15:43.397 --> 02:15:48.697
"'Horribly! It was dreadful. Are you ill? You've no idea what it was. You've no

02:15:48.697 --> 02:15:52.397
idea what I suffered.' The girl smiled.

02:15:53.177 --> 02:15:57.757
"'Dorian,' she answered, lingering on his name with a long-drawn music in her voice,

02:15:57.797 --> 02:16:01.777
as though it were sweeter than honey to the red petals of her lips.

02:16:02.557 --> 02:16:06.457
"'Dorian, you should have understood. But you understand now, don't you?'

02:16:06.457 --> 02:16:09.677
"'Understand what?' he asked angrily.

02:16:10.937 --> 02:16:16.657
"'Why I was so bad to-night. Why I shall always be bad. Why I shall never act well again.'

02:16:18.017 --> 02:16:19.677
He shrugged his shoulders.

02:16:20.197 --> 02:16:24.577
"'You are ill, I suppose. When you are ill, you shouldn't act. You make

02:16:24.577 --> 02:16:27.377
yourself ridiculous. My friends were bored. I was bored.'

02:16:28.457 --> 02:16:34.037
"'She seemed not to listen to him. She was transfigured with joy, and ecstasy of happiness

02:16:34.037 --> 02:16:38.077
dominated her. "'Dorian, Dorian!' she cried.

02:16:38.657 --> 02:16:44.297
"'Before I knew you, acting was the one reality in my life. It was only in the theatre that I

02:16:44.297 --> 02:16:50.837
lived. I thought that it was all true. I was Roslyn one night and Portia the other. The joy

02:16:50.837 --> 02:16:57.497
of Beatrice was my joy, and the sorrows of Cordelia were mine also. I believed in everything.

02:16:58.277 --> 02:17:05.697
The common people who acted with me seemed to me to be godlike. The painted scenes were my world.

02:17:06.197 --> 02:17:09.697
I knew nothing but shadows, and I thought them real.

02:17:10.577 --> 02:17:15.437
"'You came, oh, my beautiful love, and you freed my soul from prison.

02:17:16.157 --> 02:17:23.577
You taught me what reality really is. Tonight, for the first time in my life, I saw through the

02:17:23.577 --> 02:17:28.897
hollowness, the sham, the silliness of the empty pageant in which I had always played. Tonight,

02:17:28.957 --> 02:17:36.417
for the first time, I became conscious that the Romeo was hideous and old and painted,

02:17:37.217 --> 02:17:41.477
that the moonlight in the orchard was false, that the scenery was vulgar, and that the words

02:17:41.477 --> 02:17:46.557
I had to speak were unreal, were not my words, not what I wanted to say.

02:17:47.657 --> 02:17:53.397
You had brought me something higher, something of which all art is but a reflection.

02:17:54.717 --> 02:18:00.457
You have made me understand what love really is. My love, my love, I am sick of shadows.

02:18:01.217 --> 02:18:07.457
You are more to me than all art can ever be. What have I to do with the puppets of a play?

02:18:08.097 --> 02:18:12.237
When I came on tonight, I could not understand how it was that everything had gone from me.

02:18:13.357 --> 02:18:20.297
Suddenly it dawned on my soul what it all meant. The knowledge was exquisite to me. I heard them

02:18:20.297 --> 02:18:27.597
hissing, and I smiled. What should they know of love? Take me away, Dorian. Take me away with you,

02:18:27.597 --> 02:18:33.917
where we can be quite alone. I hate the stage. I might mimic a passion that I do not feel,

02:18:33.917 --> 02:18:41.577
but I cannot mimic one that burns me like fire. Oh, Dorian, Dorian, you understand now what it

02:18:41.577 --> 02:18:47.797
all means? Even if I could do it, it would be profanation for me to play at being in love.

02:18:48.077 --> 02:18:54.177
You have made me see that. He flung himself down on the sofa and turned away his face.

02:18:55.077 --> 02:19:02.257
You have killed my love, he muttered. She looked at him in wonder and laughed.

02:19:02.817 --> 02:19:07.517
He made no answer. She came across to him and stroked his hair with her little fingers.

02:19:09.097 --> 02:19:15.397
She knelt down and pressed his hands to her lips. He drew them away, and a shudder ran through him.

02:19:16.217 --> 02:19:19.097
Then he leapt up and went to the door.

02:19:19.577 --> 02:19:21.097
Yes, he cried.

02:19:22.457 --> 02:19:27.357
You have killed my love. You used to stir my imagination,

02:19:27.357 --> 02:19:32.097
now you don't even stir my curiosity. You simply produce no effect.

02:19:33.137 --> 02:19:36.977
I loved you because you were wonderful, because you were genius and intellect,

02:19:37.357 --> 02:19:42.457
because you realized the dreams of great poets and gave shape and substance to the shadows of art.

02:19:43.797 --> 02:19:52.337
You've thrown it all away. You are shallow and stupid. My God, how mad I was to love you!

02:19:52.817 --> 02:19:55.077
What a fool I have been! You are nothing to me now.

02:19:55.577 --> 02:20:00.457
I will never see you again. I will never think of you. I will never mention your name.

02:20:01.597 --> 02:20:05.537
You don't know what you were to me once. Why, once?

02:20:06.337 --> 02:20:11.217
Oh, I can't bear to think of it. I wish I never laid eyes on you. You have spoiled the

02:20:11.217 --> 02:20:18.277
romance of my life. How little you can know of love if you say it mars your art. What are

02:20:18.277 --> 02:20:24.477
you without your art? Nothing. I would have made you famous, splendid, magnificent.

02:20:24.477 --> 02:20:28.577
The world would have worshipped you, and you would have belonged to me.

02:20:29.137 --> 02:20:33.197
What do you know? A third-rate actress with a pretty face.

02:20:34.597 --> 02:20:39.537
The girl grew white and trembled. She clenched her hands together,

02:20:39.577 --> 02:20:41.637
and her voice seemed to catch in her throat.

02:20:42.457 --> 02:20:47.157
You are not serious, Dorian. She murmured you are acting.

02:20:48.537 --> 02:20:54.457
Acting? I leave that to you. You do it so well.

02:20:55.117 --> 02:20:59.357
He answered bitterly. She rose up from her knees and with a

02:20:59.357 --> 02:21:03.277
piteous expression of pain in her face came across the room to him.

02:21:04.577 --> 02:21:09.477
She put her hand on his arm and looked into his eyes. He thrust her back.

02:21:11.077 --> 02:21:15.977
Don't touch me, he cried. A low moan broke from her,

02:21:16.137 --> 02:21:19.817
and she flung herself at his feet and lay there like a trampled flower.

02:21:20.697 --> 02:21:22.857
Dorian, Dorian, don't leave me, she whispered.

02:21:23.657 --> 02:21:27.457
I am sorry I didn't act well. I was thinking of you all the time, but I will try.

02:21:27.937 --> 02:21:31.577
Indeed, I will try. It came so suddenly across me. My love for you,

02:21:31.577 --> 02:21:35.597
I think I should never have known it if you had not kissed me, if we had not kissed each other.

02:21:36.537 --> 02:21:39.497
Kiss me again, my love. Don't go away from me. I couldn't bear it.

02:21:40.337 --> 02:21:44.577
Can you forgive me for tonight? I will work so hard and try to improve.

02:21:45.057 --> 02:21:48.397
Don't be cruel to me, because I love you better than anything in the world. After all,

02:21:48.397 --> 02:21:53.377
it is only once that I have not pleased you. But you are quite right, Dorian. I should have

02:21:54.597 --> 02:22:00.157
shown myself more of an artist. It was foolish of me, and yet I couldn't help it. Don't leave me,

02:22:00.157 --> 02:22:05.617
don't leave me. A fit of passionate sobbing choked her. She crouched on the floor like a wounded

02:22:05.617 --> 02:22:12.677
thing, and Dorian Gray, with his beautiful eyes, looked down at her, and his chiselled lips curled

02:22:12.677 --> 02:22:19.177
in exquisite disdain. There is always something ridiculous about the passions of people whom

02:22:19.177 --> 02:22:28.757
one has ceased to love. Sibyl Vane seemed to him to be absurdly melodramatic. Her tears and sobs

02:22:28.757 --> 02:22:37.577
annoyed him. I am going, he said at last in his calm, clear voice. I don't wish to be unkind,

02:22:37.577 --> 02:22:45.117
but I can't see you again. You have disappointed me. She wept silently and made no answer but

02:22:45.117 --> 02:22:52.457
crept nearer to him. Her little hands stretched blindly out and appeared to be seeking for him.

02:22:52.877 --> 02:22:58.137
He turned on his heel and left the room. In a few moments he was out of the theatre.

02:22:59.957 --> 02:23:07.257
Where he went to he hardly knew. He remembered wandering through dimly lit streets with gaunt

02:23:07.257 --> 02:23:13.497
black-shattered archways and evil-looking houses. Women with hoarse voices and harsh

02:23:13.497 --> 02:23:19.637
laughter had called after him. Drunkards had reeled by, cursing and chattering to themselves

02:23:19.637 --> 02:23:25.597
like monstrous apes. He had seen grotesque children huddled upon doorsteps, and had heard

02:23:25.597 --> 02:23:32.457
shrieks and oaths from gloomy courts. When the dawn was just breaking he found himself at Covent

02:23:32.457 --> 02:23:38.637
Garden. Huge carts filled with nodding lilies rumbled slowly down the polished empty street.

02:23:39.437 --> 02:23:45.957
The air was heavy with perfume of the flowers, and their beauty seemed to bring him an anodyne

02:23:45.957 --> 02:23:51.717
for his pain. He followed into the market and watched the men unloading their wagons.

02:23:52.737 --> 02:23:58.657
A white-smocked carter offered him some cherries. He thanked him, wondered why he refused to accept

02:23:58.657 --> 02:24:03.497
any money for them, and began to eat them listlessly. They had been plucked in midnight,

02:24:03.877 --> 02:24:09.397
and the coldness of the moon had entered into them. A long line of boys carrying crates of

02:24:09.397 --> 02:24:16.677
stripped tulips, and of yellow and red roses, defiled in front of him, threading their way

02:24:16.677 --> 02:24:23.977
through the huge jade-green piles of vegetables. Under the portico, with its grey sun-bleached

02:24:23.977 --> 02:24:30.417
pillars, loitered a troupe of draggled, bare-headed girls waiting for the auction to be over.

02:24:31.337 --> 02:24:38.557
After some time he hailed a handsome and drove home. He was pure opal now, and the roofs of the

02:24:38.557 --> 02:24:45.197
houses glistened like silver against it. As he was passing through the library towards the door

02:24:45.197 --> 02:24:51.077
of his bedroom, his eye fell upon the portrait Basil Hallward had painted him. He started back

02:24:51.077 --> 02:24:57.497
in surprise, and then went over to it and examined it. In the dim, arrested light that struggled

02:24:57.497 --> 02:25:05.417
through the cream-coloured silk blinds, the face seemed to him to be a little changed. The expression

02:25:05.417 --> 02:25:11.597
looked different. One would have said there was a touch of cruelty in the mouth. He was certainly

02:25:11.597 --> 02:25:19.357
curious. He turned round, and, walking to the window, drew the blinds up. The bright dawn

02:25:19.357 --> 02:25:24.737
flooded the room and swept the fantastic shadows into dusky quarters where they lay shuddering.

02:25:25.537 --> 02:25:30.657
But the strange expression that he had noticed in the face of the portrait seemed to linger there,

02:25:31.077 --> 02:25:37.357
to be more intensified even. The quivering, ardent sunlight showed the lines of cruelty

02:25:37.357 --> 02:25:42.397
around the mouth as clearly as if he had been looking into a mirror after he had done some

02:25:42.397 --> 02:25:50.057
dreadful thing. He winced, and, taking up from the table an oval glass framed in ivory cupids

02:25:50.057 --> 02:25:56.937
that Lord Henry had given him, he glanced hurriedly into it. No line like that warped his red lips,

02:25:57.017 --> 02:26:02.657
but what did it mean? He rubbed his eyes, came close to the picture, and examined it again.

02:26:03.597 --> 02:26:08.157
There were no signs of any change when he looked into the actual painting,

02:26:08.717 --> 02:26:14.317
and yet there was no doubt that the whole expression had altered. It was not a mere

02:26:14.317 --> 02:26:20.417
fancy of his own that the thing was horribly apparent. He threw himself into a chair and

02:26:20.417 --> 02:26:26.317
began to think. Suddenly there flashed across his mind what he had said in Basil Hallward's

02:26:26.317 --> 02:26:38.137
studio the day the picture had been finished. Yes, he remembered it perfectly. He had uttered a

02:26:38.137 --> 02:26:43.917
his own beauty might be untarnished, and the face on the canvas bear the burden of his passions and

02:26:43.917 --> 02:26:50.377
his sins, that the painted image might be seared with the lines of suffering and thought,

02:26:51.277 --> 02:26:57.357
and that he might keep all the delicate bloom and loveliness of his then just conscious boyhood.

02:26:58.097 --> 02:27:04.237
Surely his prayer had not been answered. Such things were impossible. It seemed monstrous to

02:27:04.237 --> 02:27:10.037
think of them, and yet there was the picture before him with a touch of cruelty in the mouth.

02:27:11.897 --> 02:27:19.857
Cruelty? Had he been cruel? It was the girl's fault, not his. He had dreamed of her as a

02:27:19.857 --> 02:27:23.377
great artist, had given his love to her because he had thought her great.

02:27:24.357 --> 02:27:28.297
Then she had disappointed him. She had been shallow and unworthy.

02:27:29.057 --> 02:27:34.937
And yet a feeling of infinite regret came over him as he thought of her lying at his feet sobbing

02:27:34.937 --> 02:27:41.717
like a little child. He remembered with what callousness he had watched her. Why had he been

02:27:41.717 --> 02:27:50.517
made like that? Why had such a soul been given to him? But he suffered also. During the three

02:27:50.517 --> 02:27:57.777
terrible hours as the play lasted he had lived centuries of pain, eon upon eon of torture.

02:27:58.977 --> 02:28:06.517
His life was well worth hers. She admired him for a moment, if he wounded her for an age.

02:28:06.957 --> 02:28:13.477
Besides, women were better suited to bear sorrow than men. They lived on their emotions. They only

02:28:13.477 --> 02:28:19.117
thought of their emotions. When they took lovers it was merely to have someone with whom they could

02:28:19.117 --> 02:28:25.117
have scenes. Lord Henry told him that, and Lord Henry knew what women were. Why should he trouble

02:28:25.117 --> 02:28:34.157
Sibyl Vane? She was nothing to him now. But the picture! What was he to say of that?

02:28:34.897 --> 02:28:41.697
It held the secret of his life and told his story. It had taught him to love his own beauty.

02:28:42.977 --> 02:28:48.617
Would it teach him to loathe his own soul? Would he ever look at it again?

02:28:49.637 --> 02:28:55.957
No. It was merely an illusion wrought on the troubled senses. The horrible night that he had

02:28:55.957 --> 02:29:03.077
passed had left phantoms behind it. Suddenly there had fallen upon his brain that tiny scarlet speck

02:29:03.077 --> 02:29:11.157
that makes men mad. The picture had not changed. It was folly to think so. Yet it was watching him,

02:29:11.177 --> 02:29:17.577
with its beautiful marred face and its cruel smile. Its bright hair gleamed in the early

02:29:17.577 --> 02:29:24.557
sunlight. Its blue eyes met his own. A sense of infinite pity, not for himself but for the

02:29:24.557 --> 02:29:33.517
painted image of himself, came over him. It had altered already and would alter more. Its gold

02:29:33.517 --> 02:29:41.957
would wither into grey. Its red and white roses would die. For every sin that he committed a stain

02:29:41.957 --> 02:29:48.337
would fleck and wreck its fairness. But he would not sin. The picture, changed or unchanged,

02:29:48.437 --> 02:29:54.637
would be to him the visible emblem of conscience. He would resist temptation. He would not see Lord

02:29:54.637 --> 02:29:58.957
Henry any more. Would not, at any rate, listen to those subtle poisonous theories that in Basil

02:29:58.957 --> 02:30:04.597
Hallward's garden had first stirred within him the passion for impossible things. He would go

02:30:04.597 --> 02:30:10.477
back to Sibyl Vane, make her amends, marry her, try to love her again. Yes, it was his duty to

02:30:10.477 --> 02:30:16.057
do so. She must have suffered more than he did, poor child. He had been selfish and cruel to her.

02:30:16.597 --> 02:30:21.837
The fascination that she had exercised over him would return. They would be happy together. His

02:30:21.837 --> 02:30:30.617
life with her would be beautiful and pure. He got up from his chair and drew a large screen

02:30:30.617 --> 02:30:34.717
right in front of the portrait, shuddering as he glanced at it.

02:30:34.717 --> 02:30:39.917
How horrible! he murmured to himself, and he walked across to the window and opened it.

02:30:40.337 --> 02:30:46.557
When he stepped out onto the grass he drew a deep breath. The fresh morning air seemed to drive

02:30:46.557 --> 02:30:53.037
away all his sombre passions he thought only of Sibyl Vane. A faint echo of his love came back to

02:30:53.037 --> 02:30:59.877
him. He repeated her name over and over again. The birds that were singing in the dew-drenched

02:30:59.877 --> 02:31:03.327
garden seemed to be telling the flowers about her.

02:31:27.727 --> 02:31:33.477
The Picture of Dorian Gray by Oscar Wilde.

02:31:45.907 --> 02:31:48.557
It was long past noon when he awoke.

02:31:49.097 --> 02:31:54.177
His valet had crept several times into the room on tiptoe to see if he was stirring,

02:31:54.737 --> 02:31:57.997
and had wondered what made his young master sleep so late.

02:31:58.797 --> 02:32:03.137
Finally his bell sounded, and Victor came in softly with a cup of tea,

02:32:03.377 --> 02:32:09.657
and a pile of letters on a small tray of gold-severate china, and drew back the olive

02:32:09.657 --> 02:32:15.077
satin curtains with their shimmering blue lining that hung in front of the three tall windows.

02:32:16.457 --> 02:32:20.377
"'Monsieur has slept well this morning,' he said, smiling.

02:32:21.177 --> 02:32:25.617
"'What o'clock is it, Victor?' asked Dorian Gray sleepily.

02:32:26.837 --> 02:32:28.857
"'One hour and a quarter, Monsieur.'

02:32:29.737 --> 02:32:37.477
How late it was! He sat up, and having sipped some tea, turned over his letters. One was from

02:32:37.477 --> 02:32:42.117
Lord Henry, and had been brought by hand that morning. He hesitated for a moment,

02:32:42.117 --> 02:32:47.937
and then put it aside. The others he opened listlessly. They contained the usual collection

02:32:47.937 --> 02:32:54.017
of cards, invitations to dinner, tickets for private views, programs of charity concerts,

02:32:54.117 --> 02:32:59.337
and the like, that are showered on fashionable young men every morning during the season.

02:33:00.197 --> 02:33:07.317
There was a rather heavy bill for a chased-silver Louis Keane's toilet set that he had not yet had

02:33:07.317 --> 02:33:11.737
the courage to send on to his guardians, who were extremely old-fashioned people,

02:33:11.737 --> 02:33:17.077
and did not realize that we live in an age when only unnecessary things are absolutely

02:33:17.077 --> 02:33:23.057
necessary to us. And there were several very courteously worded communications from German

02:33:23.057 --> 02:33:27.537
street money-lenders offering to advance any sum of money at a moment's notice,

02:33:28.097 --> 02:33:30.517
and at the most reasonable rates of interest.

02:33:31.617 --> 02:33:36.877
After about ten minutes he got up, and, throwing on an elaborate dressing-gown,

02:33:37.317 --> 02:33:42.977
passed into the onyx-paved bathroom. The cool water refreshed him after his long sleep.

02:33:43.697 --> 02:33:49.077
He seemed to have forgotten all that he had gone through. A dim sense of having taken part in some

02:33:49.077 --> 02:33:55.357
strange tragedy came to him once or twice, but there was the unreality of a dream about it.

02:33:56.157 --> 02:34:01.697
As soon as he was dressed, he went into the library and sat down to a light French breakfast

02:34:01.697 --> 02:34:07.777
that had been laid out for him on a small round table close to an open window. It was an exquisite

02:34:07.777 --> 02:34:15.477
day. The warm air seemed laden with spices, a bee flew in, and buzzed around the blue dragon bowl,

02:34:15.877 --> 02:34:22.977
filled with sulfur-yellow roses that stood in front of him. He felt perfectly happy.

02:34:24.197 --> 02:34:29.257
And suddenly his eye fell on the screen that he had placed in front of his portrait, and he started.

02:34:30.377 --> 02:34:34.597
"'Too cold, monsieur?' asked his valet, putting an omelette on the table.

02:34:35.097 --> 02:34:36.637
"'I shut the window.'

02:34:38.377 --> 02:34:48.037
Dorian Chooker said. "'I am not cold,' he murmured. Was it all true? Had the portrait really changed?

02:34:48.597 --> 02:34:54.657
Or had it been simply his own imagination that had made him see a look of evil where there had been

02:34:54.657 --> 02:35:01.777
a look of joy? Surely a painted canvas could not alter. The thing was absurd.

02:35:02.557 --> 02:35:09.157
It would serve as a tale to tell Basil some day. It would make him smile. And yet how vivid was

02:35:09.157 --> 02:35:15.177
his recollection of the whole thing. First in the dim twilight, then in the bright dawn, he had seen

02:35:15.177 --> 02:35:20.677
the touch of cruelty and the warped lips. He almost dreaded his valet leaving the room.

02:35:20.917 --> 02:35:27.337
He knew that when he was alone he would have to examine the portrait. He was afraid of certainty.

02:35:28.057 --> 02:35:31.197
When the coffee and cigarettes had been brought and the man turned to go,

02:35:31.377 --> 02:35:37.357
he felt a mad desire to tell him to remain. As the door closed behind him he called him back.

02:35:37.577 --> 02:35:42.157
The man stood waiting for his orders. Dorian looked at him for a moment.

02:35:43.457 --> 02:35:50.337
"'I am not home to anyone, Victor,' he said with a sigh. The man bowed and retired.

02:35:52.157 --> 02:35:58.957
He rose from the table, lit a cigarette, and flung himself down on a luxuriously cushioned couch that

02:35:58.957 --> 02:36:05.757
stood facing the screen. The screen was an old one of Spanish gilt leather, stamped and wrought with

02:36:05.757 --> 02:36:13.157
rather florid Louis XIV pattern. He scanned it curiously, wondering if it had ever before

02:36:13.157 --> 02:36:20.957
concealed the secret of a man's life. Should he move it aside, after all? Why not let it stay there?

02:36:21.377 --> 02:36:27.137
What was the use of knowing? If the thing was true, it was terrible. If it was not true,

02:36:27.177 --> 02:36:35.257
why trouble about it? But what if, by some fate or deadly a chance, other eyes than his spied behind

02:36:35.257 --> 02:36:42.037
him saw the horrible change? What should he do if Basil Hallward came and asked to look at his

02:36:42.037 --> 02:36:50.657
own picture? He would sure do that. No, the thing had to be examined at once. Anything would be

02:36:50.657 --> 02:36:58.037
better than this dreadful state of doubt.' He got up and locked both doors. At least he would be

02:36:58.037 --> 02:37:05.057
alone when he looked upon the mask of his shame. Then he drew the screen aside and saw himself

02:37:05.257 --> 02:37:16.037
face to face. It was perfectly true. The portrait had altered. As he often remembered afterwards,

02:37:16.177 --> 02:37:22.337
and always with no small wonder, he found himself at first gazing at the portrait with a feeling of

02:37:22.337 --> 02:37:29.297
almost scientific interest. That such a change should have taken place was incredible to him,

02:37:29.297 --> 02:37:35.557
and yet it was a fact. Was there some subtle affinity between the chemical atoms that

02:37:35.557 --> 02:37:40.917
shaped themselves into form and colour on the canvas, and the soul that was within him?

02:37:41.997 --> 02:37:49.977
Could it be that what that soul thought they realised? That what it dreamed they made true?

02:37:50.417 --> 02:37:55.637
Or was there some other, more terrible reason? He shuddered and felt afraid,

02:37:55.637 --> 02:38:00.457
and going back to the couch lay there, gazing at the picture in sickened horror.

02:38:02.077 --> 02:38:08.317
One thing, however, he felt that it had done for him. It had made him conscious how unjust,

02:38:08.437 --> 02:38:15.077
how cruel he had been to Sibyl Vane. It was not too late to make reparation for that. She could

02:38:15.077 --> 02:38:22.317
still be his wife. His unreal and selfish love would yield to some higher influence, would be

02:38:22.317 --> 02:38:28.417
transformed into some nobler passion, and the portrait that Basil Hallward had painted of him

02:38:28.417 --> 02:38:35.137
would be a guide to him through life, would be to him what holiness was to some and conscience

02:38:35.137 --> 02:38:42.657
was to others, and the fear of God to us all. There were opiates for remorse, drugs that could

02:38:42.657 --> 02:38:49.497
lull the moral sense to sleep, but here was a visible symbol of the degradation of sin.

02:38:50.137 --> 02:38:55.617
Here was an ever-present sign of the ruin men brought upon their souls.

02:38:57.137 --> 02:39:04.477
Three o'clock struck, and four and half past four, but he did not stir. He was trying to

02:39:04.477 --> 02:39:09.717
gather up the scarlet threads of his life and to weave them into a pattern, to find his way

02:39:09.717 --> 02:39:15.437
through the sanguine labyrinth of passion through which he was wandering. He did not know what to do

02:39:15.437 --> 02:39:20.637
or what to think. Finally he went over to the table and wrote a passionate letter to the girl

02:39:20.637 --> 02:39:26.977
he had loved, imploring her forgiveness and accusing himself of madness. He covered page

02:39:26.977 --> 02:39:34.957
after page with wild words of sorrow and wilder words of pain. There is a luxury in self-reproach.

02:39:35.237 --> 02:39:39.357
When we blame ourselves we feel that no one else has a right to blame us.

02:39:39.577 --> 02:39:43.937
It is the confession, not the priest, that gives us absolution.

02:39:44.917 --> 02:39:49.817
When Dorian Gray had finished the letter, he felt that he had been forgiven.

02:39:50.977 --> 02:39:54.997
Suddenly there came a knock to the door, and he heard Lord Henry's voice outside.

02:39:55.877 --> 02:40:01.857
My dear Dorian, I must see you. Let me in at once. I can't bear you shutting yourself up like this.

02:40:02.917 --> 02:40:09.297
He made no answer at first, but remained quite still. The knocking still continued and grew louder.

02:40:10.017 --> 02:40:15.997
Yes, it was better to let Lord Henry in, and to explain to him the new life he was going to lead,

02:40:16.377 --> 02:40:22.017
to quarrel with him if it had become necessary to quarrel, to part if parting was inevitable.

02:40:22.877 --> 02:40:26.837
He jumped up and drew the screen hastily across the picture and unlocked the door.

02:40:28.397 --> 02:40:33.237
I am so sorry for it all, my dear boy, said Lord Henry, coming in,

02:40:33.277 --> 02:40:35.557
but you must not think about it too much.

02:40:36.237 --> 02:40:39.917
Do you mean Sibyl Vane? asked Dorian.

02:40:40.517 --> 02:40:45.577
Yes, of course, answered Henry, sinking into a chair and slowly pulling his gloves off.

02:40:45.817 --> 02:40:49.657
It is dreadful, from one point of view, but it was not your fault.

02:40:50.297 --> 02:40:53.737
Tell me, did you go behind and see her after the play was over?

02:40:54.797 --> 02:40:58.997
Yes, I felt sure you had. Did you make a scene with her?

02:41:00.277 --> 02:41:03.337
I was brutal, Harry, perfectly brutal.

02:41:03.917 --> 02:41:09.357
But it is all right now. I am not sorry for anything that has happened.

02:41:10.297 --> 02:41:12.857
It has taught me to know myself better.

02:41:13.817 --> 02:41:18.017
Oh, Dorian, I am so glad you take it in that way.

02:41:18.297 --> 02:41:22.257
I was afraid I would find you plunged in remorse and tearing your nice hair.

02:41:23.917 --> 02:41:29.197
I have got through all that, said Dorian, shaking his head and smiling. I am perfectly happy now.

02:41:29.617 --> 02:41:32.417
I know what conscience is, to begin with.

02:41:32.417 --> 02:41:37.597
It is not what you told me it was. It is the divinest thing in us.

02:41:37.797 --> 02:41:41.597
Oh, don't sneer at it, Harry, any more. At least not before me.

02:41:41.717 --> 02:41:46.537
I want to be good. I can't bear the idea of my soul being hideous.

02:41:47.177 --> 02:41:52.557
A very charming artistic basis for ethics, Dorian. I congratulate you on it.

02:41:52.817 --> 02:41:54.637
But how are you going to begin?

02:41:55.597 --> 02:41:57.717
By marrying Sibyl Vane.

02:42:00.257 --> 02:42:06.037
Marrying Sibyl Vane? cried Lord Henry, standing up and looking at him in a perplexed amazement.

02:42:06.797 --> 02:42:11.257
But, my dear Dorian, yes, Harry, I know what you are going to say.

02:42:11.617 --> 02:42:16.317
Something dreadful about marriage. Don't say it. Don't ever say things of that kind to me again.

02:42:16.617 --> 02:42:23.357
Two days ago I asked Sibyl to marry me. I am not going to break my word to her. She is to be my wife.

02:42:25.117 --> 02:42:32.837
Your wife? Dorian, didn't you get my letter? I wrote to you this morning,

02:42:32.877 --> 02:42:34.877
and sent the note down by my own man.

02:42:35.737 --> 02:42:39.817
Your letter? Oh, yes, I remember. I have not read it yet, Harry.

02:42:40.337 --> 02:42:43.057
I was afraid there might be something in it that I wouldn't like.

02:42:45.137 --> 02:42:48.557
Lord Henry walked across the room, and, sitting down by Dorian,

02:42:48.557 --> 02:42:50.717
took both hands in his, and held them tightly.

02:42:51.517 --> 02:42:53.577
Dorian, he said.

02:42:53.757 --> 02:42:54.357
My letter?

02:42:55.077 --> 02:42:56.017
Don't be frightened.

02:42:57.397 --> 02:43:01.617
My letter was to tell you that Sibyl Vane is dead.

02:43:02.777 --> 02:43:06.577
A cry of pain rose from the lad's lips, and he leapt to his feet,

02:43:06.677 --> 02:43:08.957
tearing his hands away from Lord Henry's grasp.

02:43:09.637 --> 02:43:15.177
Dead? Sibyl dead? It is not true. It is a horrible lie.

02:43:16.157 --> 02:43:18.037
It is quite true, Dorian.

02:43:18.937 --> 02:43:20.857
Said Lord Henry gravely.

02:43:21.177 --> 02:43:27.517
It is in all the morning papers. I wrote down to you to ask you not to see anyone till I came.

02:43:28.357 --> 02:43:32.717
There will have to be an inquest, of course, and you must not be mixed up in it.

02:43:33.337 --> 02:43:38.877
Things like that make a man fashionable in Paris, but in London people are so prejudiced.

02:43:39.277 --> 02:43:42.557
Here one should never make one's debut with a scandal.

02:43:42.917 --> 02:43:46.097
One should reserve that to give an interest to one's old age.

02:43:46.857 --> 02:43:51.157
I don't suppose they know your name at the theatre. If they don't, it is all right.

02:43:51.677 --> 02:43:56.177
Did anyone see you going round to her room? That is an important point.

02:43:57.277 --> 02:44:01.857
Dorian did not answer for a few moments. He was dazed with horror.

02:44:03.097 --> 02:44:05.697
Finally he murmured in a stifled voice.

02:44:06.117 --> 02:44:09.257
Harry, did you say an inquest?

02:44:10.077 --> 02:44:11.757
What did you mean by that?

02:44:12.397 --> 02:44:14.377
Did Sibyl—oh,

02:44:14.957 --> 02:44:18.277
Harry, I can't bear it. But be quick, tell me everything at once.

02:44:18.837 --> 02:44:24.037
I have no doubt that it was not an accident, Dorian, though it must be put in that way to

02:44:24.037 --> 02:44:29.497
the public. As she was leaving the theatre with her mother, about half-past twelve or so,

02:44:30.657 --> 02:44:36.297
she said she had forgotten something upstairs. They waited some time for her, but she did not

02:44:36.297 --> 02:44:40.997
come down again. They ultimately found her lying dead on the floor of her dressing-room.

02:44:40.997 --> 02:44:46.857
She had swallowed something by mistake—some dreadful thing they use at theatres. I don't

02:44:46.857 --> 02:44:53.237
know what it was, but it was either prusic acid or white lead in it. I should fancy it was prusic

02:44:53.237 --> 02:45:00.337
acid, as she seems to have died instantaneously. It is very tragic, of course, but you must not

02:45:00.337 --> 02:45:05.877
get yourself mixed up in it. I see by the standard that she was seventeen. I should have thought she

02:45:05.877 --> 02:45:12.177
was almost younger than that. She looks such a child, and seemed to know so little about acting.

02:45:12.857 --> 02:45:16.497
Dorian, you mustn't let this thing get on your nerves. You must come and dine with me,

02:45:16.517 --> 02:45:22.437
and afterwards we'll go in at the opera. It is a patty-night, and everyone will be there.

02:45:22.777 --> 02:45:26.197
You can come to my sister's box. She has got some smart women with her.

02:45:27.717 --> 02:45:33.657
So I have murdered Sibyl Vane, said Dorian Gray, half to himself,

02:45:35.117 --> 02:45:38.837
murdered her as certainly as if I had cut her little throat with a knife.

02:45:40.017 --> 02:45:46.617
And the roses are not less lovely for all that. The birds sing just as happily in my garden,

02:45:47.097 --> 02:45:52.117
and tonight I am to dine with you, and then go on to the opera, and sup somewhere, I suppose,

02:45:52.117 --> 02:45:56.937
afterwards. How extraordinarily dramatic life is!

02:45:58.337 --> 02:46:03.917
If I had read all this in a book, Harry, I think I would have wept over it.

02:46:04.757 --> 02:46:12.097
Somehow, now that it has happened actually, and to me, it seems far too wonderful for tears.

02:46:13.317 --> 02:46:16.997
Here is the first passionate love letter I have ever written in my life.

02:46:17.877 --> 02:46:23.197
Strange that my first passionate love letter should have been addressed to a dead girl.

02:46:24.837 --> 02:46:29.777
Can they feel, I wonder, those silent people we call the dead?

02:46:31.557 --> 02:46:40.717
Sibyl? Can she feel, or know, or listen? Oh, Harry, how I loved her once!

02:46:41.617 --> 02:46:50.157
It seems years ago to me now. She was everything to me. Then came that dreadful night. Was it

02:46:50.157 --> 02:46:57.497
really only last night, when she played so badly and my heart almost broke? She explained it all

02:46:57.497 --> 02:47:08.017
to me. It was terribly pathetic. But I was not moved a bit. I thought her shallow.

02:47:08.997 --> 02:47:14.057
Then something happened that made me afraid. I can't tell you what it is, but it was awful.

02:47:14.677 --> 02:47:20.697
I said I would go back to her. I felt I had done wrong, and now she is dead.

02:47:22.317 --> 02:47:30.457
My God! My God! Harry, what shall I do? You don't know the danger I am in, and there is nothing to

02:47:30.457 --> 02:47:35.257
keep me straight. She would have done that for me. She had no right to kill herself. It was selfish

02:47:35.257 --> 02:47:41.617
of her. My dear Dorian, the only way a woman can ever reform a man is by boring him so

02:47:41.617 --> 02:47:46.757
completely that he loses all interest in life. If you had married this girl you would have been

02:47:46.757 --> 02:47:53.017
wretched. Of course you would have treated her kindly. One can always be kind to people about

02:47:53.017 --> 02:47:59.037
whom one cares nothing. But she would have soon found out that you were absolutely indifferent

02:47:59.037 --> 02:48:05.457
to her, and when a woman finds that out about her husband she either becomes dreadfully dowdy

02:48:05.457 --> 02:48:10.357
or wears some very smart bonnets that some other woman's husband has to pay for.

02:48:11.197 --> 02:48:15.617
I say nothing about the social mistake, but I assure you that in any case

02:48:16.057 --> 02:48:19.757
the whole thing would have been an absolute failure.

02:48:20.917 --> 02:48:26.397
I suppose it would, muttered the lad, walking up and down the room and looking horribly pale.

02:48:26.397 --> 02:48:33.017
But I thought it was my duty. It is not my fault that this terrible tragedy had prevented my

02:48:33.017 --> 02:48:38.357
doing what was right. I remember your saying once that there is a fatality about good resolutions,

02:48:39.297 --> 02:48:46.057
that they are always made too late. Mine certainly were. Good resolutions are simply

02:48:46.057 --> 02:48:53.157
a useless attempt to interfere with scientific laws. Their origin is pure vanity. Their result

02:48:53.157 --> 02:49:01.637
is absolutely nil. They give us, now and then, some of those luxurious sterile emotions

02:49:02.277 --> 02:49:08.057
that have a certain charm for us. That is all that can be said for them.

02:49:09.917 --> 02:49:13.997
Harry? cried Dorian Gray, coming over and sitting down beside him.

02:49:14.497 --> 02:49:17.997
Why is it that I cannot feel this tragedy as much as I want to?

02:49:18.757 --> 02:49:20.957
I don't think I am heartless, do you?

02:49:21.617 --> 02:49:25.237
You've done too many foolish things in your life to be entitled to give yourself

02:49:25.237 --> 02:49:29.677
that name, Dorian, answered Lord Henry, with his sweet melancholy smile.

02:49:30.537 --> 02:49:31.477
The lad frowned.

02:49:32.037 --> 02:49:38.417
I don't like that explanation, Harry, he rejoined. But I am glad you don't think I am heartless.

02:49:38.897 --> 02:49:44.637
I am nothing of that kind. I know I am not. And yet I must admit that this thing that has

02:49:44.637 --> 02:49:49.837
happened does not affect me as it should. It seems to me to be simply like a wonderful

02:49:49.837 --> 02:49:57.377
ending to a wonderful play. It is all the terrible beauty of a great tragedy, a tragedy

02:49:57.377 --> 02:50:01.337
in which I took part, but by which I have not been wounded.

02:50:03.037 --> 02:50:09.217
It is an interesting question, said Lord Henry, who found an exquisite pleasure in playing on the

02:50:09.217 --> 02:50:17.547
unconscious egotism. An extremely interesting question. I fancy that the explanation is this.

02:50:18.237 --> 02:50:24.657
It often happens that the real tragedies of life occur in such an inartistic manner

02:50:25.067 --> 02:50:29.937
that they hurt us by their cruel violence, their absolute incoherence,

02:50:30.417 --> 02:50:34.577
their absurd want of meaning, their entire lack of style.

02:50:35.797 --> 02:50:43.757
They affect us just as vulgarity affects us. They give us an impression of sheer brute force,

02:50:44.097 --> 02:50:51.237
and we revolt against that. Sometimes, however, a tragedy that has artistic elements of beauty

02:50:51.237 --> 02:50:58.777
crosses over our lives. If these elements of beauty are real, the whole thing simply appeals

02:50:58.777 --> 02:51:06.417
to our sense of dramatic effect. Suddenly we find that we are no longer the actors,

02:51:07.297 --> 02:51:14.097
but the spectators of the play, or rather we are both. We watch ourselves, and the mere wonder of

02:51:14.097 --> 02:51:18.957
the spectacle enthralls us. In the present case, what is it that has really happened?

02:51:19.777 --> 02:51:25.917
Someone has killed herself for love of you. I wish I had ever had such an experience.

02:51:26.757 --> 02:51:33.897
It would have made me in love with love for the rest of my life. The people who have adored me—there

02:51:33.897 --> 02:51:40.717
have not been very many, but there have been some—have always insisted on living on, long

02:51:40.717 --> 02:51:47.377
after I ceased to care for them, or they to care for me. They become stout and tedious,

02:51:48.037 --> 02:51:54.397
and when I meet them they go in at once for reminiscences. That awful memory of woman,

02:51:54.397 --> 02:51:59.717
what a fearful thing it is, and what an utter intellectual stagnation it reveals.

02:51:59.997 --> 02:52:05.197
One should absorb the colour of life, but one should never remember its details.

02:52:06.677 --> 02:52:14.457
Details are always vulgar. Of course now and then things linger. I once wore nothing but violets all

02:52:14.457 --> 02:52:19.597
and wore through one season, as mourning for a romance that would not die. Ultimately, however,

02:52:19.597 --> 02:52:27.117
it did die. I forget what killed it. I think it was her proposing to sacrifice the whole world

02:52:27.117 --> 02:52:34.577
for me. That is always a dreadful moment. It fills one with a terror of eternity.

02:52:35.377 --> 02:52:41.397
Well, would you believe it, a week ago at Lady Hampshire's I found myself seated at dinner

02:52:41.397 --> 02:52:50.437
next the lady in question. And she insisted on going over the whole thing again, and digging

02:52:50.437 --> 02:52:57.557
up the past and raking up the future. I had buried my romance in a bed of poppies. She dragged it out

02:52:57.557 --> 02:53:04.397
again and assured me that I had spoiled her life. I am bound to state that she ate an enormous dinner,

02:53:04.757 --> 02:53:10.457
so I did not feel any anxiety. But what a lack of taste she showed.

02:53:11.397 --> 02:53:18.097
The one charm of the past is that it is the past. But women never know when the curtain

02:53:18.097 --> 02:53:24.637
has fallen. They always want a sixth act, and as soon as the interest of the play is entirely over

02:53:24.637 --> 02:53:30.317
they propose to continue it. If they were allowed to have their way, every comedy would have a

02:53:30.317 --> 02:53:36.477
tragic ending, and every tragedy would culminate in a farce. They are charmingly artificial,

02:53:36.877 --> 02:53:44.597
but they have no sense of art. You are more fortunate than I am. I assure you, Dorian,

02:53:45.217 --> 02:53:50.397
that not one of the women I have known would have done for me what Sibyl Vane did for you.

02:53:51.217 --> 02:53:57.377
Ordinary women always console themselves. Some of them do it by going in for sentimental colours,

02:53:57.617 --> 02:54:04.257
never trust a woman who wears mauve, whatever her age may be, or a woman over 35 who is fond

02:54:04.257 --> 02:54:11.837
of pink ribbons. It always means they have a history. Others find a great consolation in

02:54:11.837 --> 02:54:17.437
suddenly discovering the good qualities of their husbands. They flaunt their conjugal felicity in

02:54:17.437 --> 02:54:25.677
one's face, as if it was the most fascinating of sins. Religion console some. Its mysteries

02:54:25.677 --> 02:54:33.077
have all the charm of a flotation, a woman once told me. I can quite understand it. Besides,

02:54:33.077 --> 02:54:38.697
nothing makes one so vain as being told that one is a sinner. There is really no end to the

02:54:38.697 --> 02:54:44.817
consolations that women find in modern life. Indeed, I have not mentioned the most important

02:54:44.817 --> 02:54:54.417
one of all. What is that, Harry? said Dorian, listlessly. Oh, the obvious one. Taking someone

02:54:54.417 --> 02:55:02.397
else's admirer when one loses one's own. In good society that always whitewashes a woman.

02:55:02.397 --> 02:55:07.877
But really, Dorian, how different Sibyl Vane must have been from all the women one meets.

02:55:08.697 --> 02:55:14.457
There is something to me quite beautiful about her death. I am glad I am living in a century

02:55:14.457 --> 02:55:21.077
when such wonders happen. They make one believe in the reality of the things that shallow fashioner

02:55:21.077 --> 02:55:29.297
people play with, such as romance, passion and love. I was terribly cruel to her, you forget that.

02:55:29.297 --> 02:55:35.817
I believe that women appreciate cruelty more than anything else. They have wonderfully primitive

02:55:35.817 --> 02:55:42.197
instincts. We have emancipated them, but they remain slaves looking for their masters all the

02:55:42.197 --> 02:55:48.837
same. They love being dominated. I am sure you were splendid. I have never seen you angry,

02:55:49.217 --> 02:55:54.877
but I can fancy how delightful you looked. And, after all, you said something to me the day

02:55:54.877 --> 02:56:00.317
before yesterday that seemed to me at the time to be mere fanciful, but that I see now

02:56:00.317 --> 02:56:08.637
was absolutely true, and it explains everything. What was that, Harry? You said to me that Sibyl

02:56:08.637 --> 02:56:16.737
Vane represented to you all the heroines of romance. That she was Desdemona one night and

02:56:16.737 --> 02:56:21.497
Ophelia the other. That if she died as Juliet she came to life as Imogen.

02:56:22.697 --> 02:56:29.017
She will never come to life again now, murmured the lad, burying his face in his hands. No,

02:56:29.217 --> 02:56:36.857
she will never come to life. She has played her last part. But you must think of that lonely death

02:56:36.857 --> 02:56:44.157
in the tawdry dressing-room simply as a strange lurid fragment from some Jacobian tragedy,

02:56:44.157 --> 02:56:49.357
as a wonderful scene from Webster, or Ford, or Cyril Touranet.

02:56:50.737 --> 02:56:57.617
The girl never really lived, and so she has never really died.

02:56:58.817 --> 02:57:05.337
To you, at least, she was always a dream, a phantom that flitted through Shakespeare's plays

02:57:05.337 --> 02:57:11.477
and left them lovelier for its presence, a reed through which Shakespeare's music sounded richer

02:57:11.477 --> 02:57:19.077
and more full of joy. The moment she touched actual life she marred it, and it marred her,

02:57:19.297 --> 02:57:25.497
and so she passed away. Mourn for Ophelia, if you like. Put ashes on your head because

02:57:25.497 --> 02:57:31.577
Cordelia was strangled. Cry out against heaven because the daughter of Brabantio died.

02:57:32.497 --> 02:57:38.017
But don't waste your tears over Sibyl Vane. She was less real than they are.

02:57:39.057 --> 02:57:45.757
There was a silence. The evening darkened in the room. Noiselessly, and with silver feet,

02:57:46.397 --> 02:57:52.377
the shadows crept in from the garden. The colours faded warily out of things.

02:57:54.257 --> 02:57:56.217
At some time Dorian looked up.

02:57:57.417 --> 02:58:03.437
You have explained to me myself, Harry, he murmured, with something of a sigh of relief.

02:58:04.197 --> 02:58:09.577
I felt all that you have said, but somehow I was afraid of it,

02:58:09.657 --> 02:58:14.157
and I could not express it to myself. How well you know me.

02:58:15.337 --> 02:58:21.037
But we will not talk again of what has happened. It has been a marvellous experience. That is all.

02:58:21.697 --> 02:58:25.697
I wonder if life has still in store for me anything as marvellous.

02:58:26.497 --> 02:58:32.377
Life has everything in store for you, Dorian. There is nothing that you,

02:58:32.497 --> 02:58:36.217
with your extraordinary good looks, will not be able to do.

02:58:37.397 --> 02:58:42.657
But, suppose, Harry, I become haggard and grey and wrinkled. What then?

02:58:43.557 --> 02:58:51.857
Ah, then, said Lord Henry, rising to go, then, my dear Dorian, you would have to fight for your

02:58:51.857 --> 02:58:58.957
victories. As it is, they are brought to you. No, you must keep your good looks. We live in

02:58:58.957 --> 02:59:06.077
an age that reads too much to be wise, and thinks too much to be beautiful. We cannot spare you.

02:59:06.477 --> 02:59:10.217
Now you had better dress and drive down to the club. We are rather late, as it is.

02:59:12.517 --> 02:59:17.317
I think I shall join you at the opera, Harry. I feel too tired to eat anything.

02:59:17.317 --> 02:59:24.377
What is the number of your sister's box? Twenty-seven, I believe. It is on the grand

02:59:24.377 --> 02:59:29.417
tier. You will see her name on the door. But I am sorry you won't come and dine.

02:59:29.957 --> 02:59:36.197
I don't feel up to it, said Dorian, warily. But I am awfully obliged to you for all that

02:59:36.197 --> 02:59:43.537
you have said to me. You are certainly my best friend. No one has ever understood me as you have.

02:59:44.437 --> 02:59:50.017
We are only at the beginning of our friendship, Dorian, answered Lord Henry, shaking him by the

02:59:50.017 --> 02:59:57.317
hand. Good-bye. I shall see you before nine-thirty, I hope. Remember, Patty is singing.

02:59:58.737 --> 03:00:03.797
As he closed the door behind him, Dorian touched the bell, and in a few minutes Victor appeared

03:00:03.797 --> 03:00:11.697
with lamps and drew the blinds down. He waited impatiently for him to go. The man seemed to take

03:00:11.697 --> 03:00:17.997
an interminable time about everything. As soon as he had left, he rushed to the screen and drew

03:00:17.997 --> 03:00:24.377
it back. No, there was no further change in the picture. It had received the news of Sybil Vane's

03:00:24.377 --> 03:00:30.617
death before he had known it himself. It was conscious of the events of life as they occurred.

03:00:31.277 --> 03:00:36.597
The vicious cruelty that marred the fine lines of the mouth had, no doubt, appeared at the very

03:00:36.597 --> 03:00:42.217
moment that the girl had drunk the poison, whatever it was. Or was it indifferent to results?

03:00:43.397 --> 03:00:48.277
Did it merely take cognizance of what had passed within the soul, he wondered,

03:00:48.917 --> 03:00:54.277
and hoped that some day he would see the change taking place before his very eyes,

03:00:54.997 --> 03:01:03.177
shuddering as he hoped it? Poor Sybil! What a romance it had all been! She had often mimicked

03:01:03.177 --> 03:01:08.377
death on the stage, and at last death himself had touched her, and brought her with him.

03:01:09.277 --> 03:01:18.277
How had she played that dreadful scene? Had she cursed him as she died? No. She had died for love

03:01:18.277 --> 03:01:25.177
of him, and love would always be a sacrament to him now. She had atoned for everything by the

03:01:25.177 --> 03:01:30.897
sacrifice she had made of her life. He would not think any more of what she had made him go through

03:01:30.897 --> 03:01:37.257
that horrible night to the theatre. When he thought of her, it would be a wonderful tragic

03:01:37.257 --> 03:01:43.417
figure to show love had been a great reality. A wonderful tragic figure!

03:01:44.857 --> 03:01:49.917
Tears came to his eyes as he remembered her childlike look, and winsome, fanciful ways,

03:01:49.997 --> 03:01:55.397
and shy, tremulous grace. He wiped them away hastily, and looked again at the picture.

03:01:56.187 --> 03:02:03.677
He felt that the time had really come for making his choice. Or had his choice already been made?

03:02:05.017 --> 03:02:11.877
Yes, life had decided that for him. Life and his own infinite curiosity about life.

03:02:12.557 --> 03:02:19.777
Eternal youth, infinite passion, pleasures subtle and secret, wild joys and wilder sins.

03:02:20.637 --> 03:02:29.337
He was to have all these things. The portrait was to bear the burden of his shame. That was all.

03:02:30.277 --> 03:02:36.077
A feeling of pain came over him as he thought of the desecration that was in store for the

03:02:36.077 --> 03:02:43.577
fair face on the canvas. Once, in boyish mockery of Narcissus, he had kissed, or feigned to kiss,

03:02:44.137 --> 03:02:50.997
those painted lips that now smiled so cruelly at him. Morning after morning he had sat before

03:02:50.997 --> 03:02:56.577
the portrait, wondering at its beauty, almost enamoured of it as it seemed to him at times.

03:02:57.577 --> 03:03:04.357
Was it to alter now with every mood to which he yielded? Was it to become a hideous and

03:03:04.357 --> 03:03:11.317
loathsome thing? To be hidden away in a locked room? To be shut out from the sunlight that

03:03:11.317 --> 03:03:19.317
so often touched to brighter gold the waving wonder of the hair? The pity of it! The pity of

03:03:19.317 --> 03:03:27.037
it! For a moment he thought of praying that the horrible sympathy that existed between him and

03:03:27.037 --> 03:03:34.317
the picture might cease. It had changed in an answer to a prayer, perhaps it might remain

03:03:34.317 --> 03:03:42.037
unchanged. And yet, who, that knew anything about life, would surrender the chance of remaining

03:03:42.037 --> 03:03:49.797
always young, however fantastic that chance might be, or with what fateful consequences it might be

03:03:49.797 --> 03:03:58.157
fraught? Besides, was it really under his control? Had it indeed been prayer that had produced the

03:03:58.157 --> 03:04:06.577
substitution? Might there not be some curious scientific reason for it all? If thought could

03:04:06.577 --> 03:04:12.937
exercise its influence upon a living organism, might not thought exercise an influence upon

03:04:12.937 --> 03:04:22.217
dead and inorganic things? Nay, without thought or conscious desire might not things external to

03:04:22.217 --> 03:04:29.797
themselves vibrate in unison with our moods and passions, atom calling to atom in secret love

03:04:29.797 --> 03:04:40.497
or in secret affinity? But the reason was of no importance. He would never again tempt by a prayer

03:04:40.497 --> 03:04:49.837
any terrible power. If the picture was to alter, it was to alter. That was all. Why inquire too

03:04:49.837 --> 03:04:57.617
closely into it? For there would be a real pleasure in watching it. He would be able to

03:04:57.617 --> 03:05:04.917
follow his mind into its secret places. This portrait would be to him the most magical of

03:05:04.917 --> 03:05:11.777
mirrors. As it had revealed to him his own body, so it would reveal to him his own soul.

03:05:12.657 --> 03:05:18.997
And when winter came upon it, he would still be standing where spring trebles on the verge of

03:05:18.997 --> 03:05:25.817
summer. When the blood crept from its face and left behind a pallid mask of chalk with

03:05:25.817 --> 03:05:33.957
leaden eyes, he would keep the glamour of boyhood. Not one blossom of his loveliness would ever fade.

03:05:34.837 --> 03:05:41.877
Not one pulse of his life would ever weaken. Like the gods of the Greeks, he would be strong

03:05:41.877 --> 03:05:47.637
and fleet and joyous. What did it matter what happened to the coloured image on the canvas?

03:05:48.417 --> 03:05:51.657
He would be safe. That was everything.

03:05:53.757 --> 03:05:59.517
He drew the screen back into its former place in front of the picture, smiling as he did so,

03:05:59.737 --> 03:06:06.057
and passed into his bedroom, where his valet was already waiting for him. An hour later

03:06:06.057 --> 03:06:11.637
he was at the opera, and Lord Henry was leaning over his chair.

03:06:50.744 --> 03:06:56.364
As he was sitting at breakfast next morning, Basil Hallward was shown into the room.

03:06:57.324 --> 03:07:01.344
"'I am so glad that I have found you, Dorian,' he said gravely.

03:07:01.524 --> 03:07:04.804
"'I called last night, and they told me you were at the opera.

03:07:05.244 --> 03:07:06.904
Of course I knew that was impossible.

03:07:07.544 --> 03:07:11.244
But I wish you had left word where you had really gone to.

03:07:11.384 --> 03:07:16.904
I passed a dreadful evening, half afraid that one tragedy might be followed by another.

03:07:17.724 --> 03:07:21.404
I think you might have telegraphed for me when you heard of it first.

03:07:21.784 --> 03:07:26.564
I read of it quite by chance in the late edition of the Globe that I picked up at the club.

03:07:26.944 --> 03:07:30.564
I came here at once, and was miserable at not finding you.

03:07:30.684 --> 03:07:33.784
I can't tell you how heartbroken I am about the whole thing.

03:07:34.144 --> 03:07:35.784
I know what you must suffer.

03:07:36.064 --> 03:07:37.284
But where were you?

03:07:37.644 --> 03:07:39.684
Did you go down and see the girl's mother?

03:07:40.224 --> 03:07:42.644
For a moment I thought of following you there.

03:07:43.384 --> 03:07:45.064
They gave the address in the paper.

03:07:45.284 --> 03:07:47.724
Somewhere in Euston Road, isn't it?

03:07:48.044 --> 03:07:51.704
But I was afraid of intruding upon a sorrow that I could not lighten.

03:07:51.744 --> 03:07:52.424
Poor woman!

03:07:52.984 --> 03:07:54.704
What a state she must be in!

03:07:54.984 --> 03:07:58.444
And her only childhood, what did she say about it all?'

03:07:59.144 --> 03:08:01.524
"'My dear Basil, how do I know?'

03:08:01.524 --> 03:08:06.724
murmured Dorian, sipping some pale yellow wine from a delicate gold-beaded bubble of

03:08:06.724 --> 03:08:09.404
Venetian glass, and looking dreadfully bored.

03:08:09.744 --> 03:08:10.984
I was at the opera.

03:08:11.684 --> 03:08:13.204
You should have come on there.

03:08:13.884 --> 03:08:17.864
I met Lady Gwendolyn, Harry's sister, for the first time.

03:08:18.044 --> 03:08:19.104
We were in her box.

03:08:19.884 --> 03:08:22.744
She is perfectly charming, and Patti sang divinely.

03:08:23.164 --> 03:08:24.904
Don't talk about horrid subjects.

03:08:25.704 --> 03:08:28.464
If one doesn't talk about a thing, it has never happened.

03:08:29.284 --> 03:08:33.584
It is simply expression, as Harry says, that gives reality to things.

03:08:34.504 --> 03:08:37.744
Tell me about yourself and what you are painting.'

03:08:37.744 --> 03:08:43.864
"'You went to the opera?' said Hallward, speaking very slowly, and with a strained touch of

03:08:43.864 --> 03:08:44.924
pain in his voice.

03:08:45.904 --> 03:08:53.424
"'You went to the opera, when Sibyl Vane was lying dead in some sordid lodging?

03:08:54.284 --> 03:08:59.484
You can talk to me of other women being charming, and of Patti singing divinely.

03:09:00.004 --> 03:09:04.904
Before the girl you loved has even the quiet of a grave to sleep in.'

03:09:06.784 --> 03:09:12.404
"'Man, there are horrors in store for that little white body of hers.'

03:09:12.404 --> 03:09:13.324
"'Stop, Basil.

03:09:13.824 --> 03:09:17.004
I won't hear it,' cried Dorian, leaping to his feet.

03:09:17.084 --> 03:09:19.104
You must not tell me those things.

03:09:19.304 --> 03:09:21.264
What is done is done.

03:09:21.684 --> 03:09:23.104
What is past is past.

03:09:24.544 --> 03:09:27.064
You called yesterday the past.

03:09:28.564 --> 03:09:32.044
What has the actual lapse of time got to do with it?

03:09:32.044 --> 03:09:36.604
It is only shallow people who require years to get rid of an emotion.

03:09:37.824 --> 03:09:43.124
A man who is master of himself can end a sorrow as easily as he can invent a pleasure.

03:09:43.944 --> 03:09:46.884
I don't want to be at the mercy of my emotions.

03:09:47.224 --> 03:09:50.624
I want to use them, to enjoy them, and to dominate them.

03:09:51.504 --> 03:09:52.964
Dorian, this is horrible.

03:09:53.984 --> 03:09:56.584
Something has changed you completely.

03:09:57.304 --> 03:10:03.244
You look exactly the same wonderful boy who used to come down to my studio day after day

03:10:03.244 --> 03:10:04.424
to sit for his picture.

03:10:04.464 --> 03:10:08.324
But you were simple, natural, and affectionate then.

03:10:08.864 --> 03:10:11.784
You were the most unspoiled creature in the whole world.

03:10:13.724 --> 03:10:16.344
Now I don't know what has come over you.

03:10:16.684 --> 03:10:19.704
You talk as if you had no heart, no pity in you.

03:10:20.204 --> 03:10:21.764
It is all Harry's influence.

03:10:21.984 --> 03:10:23.604
I can see that.'

03:10:23.604 --> 03:10:29.644
The lad flushed up and, going to the window, looked out on the green flickering garden

03:10:29.644 --> 03:10:30.704
for a few moments.

03:10:32.244 --> 03:10:37.244
"'I owe a great deal to Harry, Basil,' he said at last.

03:10:37.884 --> 03:10:39.484
"'More than I owe you.

03:10:40.504 --> 03:10:43.244
You only taught me to be vain.'

03:10:43.864 --> 03:10:47.754
"'Well, I am punished for that, Dorian, or shall be some day.'

03:10:49.004 --> 03:10:52.504
"'I don't know what you mean, Basil,' he exclaimed, turning round.

03:10:53.364 --> 03:10:55.084
"'I don't know what you want.

03:10:55.424 --> 03:10:57.104
What do you want?

03:10:58.044 --> 03:11:01.544
I want the Dorian Grey I used to know.'

03:11:02.524 --> 03:11:06.884
"'Basil,' said the lad, going over to him and putting his hand on his shoulder,

03:11:08.484 --> 03:11:10.904
"'you have come too late.'

03:11:12.204 --> 03:11:15.784
"'Yesterday, when I heard that Sibyl Vane had killed herself—'

03:11:16.304 --> 03:11:17.644
"'Killed herself!

03:11:17.864 --> 03:11:18.504
Good heavens!

03:11:18.784 --> 03:11:20.884
Is there no doubt about that?'

03:11:20.884 --> 03:11:23.864
cried Hallward, looking up at him with an expression of horror.

03:11:24.124 --> 03:11:28.624
"'My dear Basil, surely you don't think it was a vulgar accident?

03:11:28.744 --> 03:11:30.384
Of course she killed herself.

03:11:31.304 --> 03:11:34.224
It is one of the great romantic tragedies of the age.

03:11:34.684 --> 03:11:39.344
As a rule, people who act lead the most commonplace lives.

03:11:39.604 --> 03:11:43.044
They are good husbands, or faithful wives, or something tedious.

03:11:44.684 --> 03:11:46.084
You know what I mean.

03:11:46.384 --> 03:11:49.764
Middle-class virtue, and all that kind of thing.

03:11:49.764 --> 03:11:51.884
How different Sibyl was!

03:11:52.284 --> 03:11:54.624
She lived her finest tragedy.

03:11:55.244 --> 03:11:57.204
She was always a heroine.

03:11:57.584 --> 03:12:04.524
The night she played, the night you saw her, she acted badly because she had known the reality of love.

03:12:05.404 --> 03:12:10.524
When she knew its unreality, she died, as Juliet might have died.

03:12:11.604 --> 03:12:14.484
She passed into the sphere of art.

03:12:15.204 --> 03:12:17.824
There is something of the martyr about her.

03:12:17.824 --> 03:12:23.984
Her death has all the pathetic uselessness of martyrdom, all its wasted beauty.

03:12:24.684 --> 03:12:29.264
But, as I was saying, you must not think I have not suffered.

03:12:29.784 --> 03:12:40.444
If you had come in yesterday at a particular moment, about half-past five, perhaps, or a quarter to six, you would have found me in tears.

03:12:40.984 --> 03:12:47.644
Even Harry, who was here, who brought me the news, in fact, had no idea what I was going through.

03:12:47.644 --> 03:12:48.984
I suffered immensely.

03:12:49.704 --> 03:12:51.644
Then he passed away.

03:12:52.684 --> 03:12:54.524
I cannot repeat an emotion.

03:12:54.764 --> 03:12:57.384
No one can, except sentimentalists.

03:12:57.944 --> 03:13:00.144
And you are awfully unjust, Basil.

03:13:00.464 --> 03:13:02.084
You come down here to console me.

03:13:02.104 --> 03:13:03.264
That is charming of you.

03:13:03.484 --> 03:13:06.084
You find me consoled, and you are furious.

03:13:07.064 --> 03:13:08.864
Oh, like a sympathetic person!

03:13:09.084 --> 03:13:14.924
You remind me of a story Harry told me about a certain philanthropist who spent twenty years of his life

03:13:14.924 --> 03:13:19.164
trying to get some grievance redressed, or some unjust law altered.

03:13:19.364 --> 03:13:20.844
I forget exactly what it was.

03:13:21.124 --> 03:13:25.004
Finally, he succeeded, and nothing could exceed his disappointment.

03:13:25.924 --> 03:13:33.284
He had absolutely nothing to do, almost died of ennui, and became a confirmed misanthrope.

03:13:33.604 --> 03:13:40.904
And besides, my dear old Basil, if you really want to console me, teach me rather to forget what has happened,

03:13:40.904 --> 03:13:46.104
or to see it from a proper artistic point of view.

03:13:47.064 --> 03:13:52.624
Was it not Gautier, who used to write about la consolation de l'art?

03:13:53.284 --> 03:14:00.784
I remember picking up a little vellum-coloured book in your studio one day, and chancing on that delightful phrase.

03:14:01.044 --> 03:14:05.544
Well, I am not like that young man you told me of when we were down at Marlowe together,

03:14:05.544 --> 03:14:11.244
the young man who used to say that yellow satin could console one for all the miseries of life.

03:14:11.724 --> 03:14:15.104
I love beautiful things that one can touch and handle.

03:14:15.604 --> 03:14:24.264
Old bricades, green bronzes, lacquerwork, carved ivories, exquisite surroundings, luxury, pomp.

03:14:24.864 --> 03:14:27.664
There is much to be gotten from all of these.

03:14:28.204 --> 03:14:34.744
But the artistic temperament that they create, or at any rate reveal, is still more to me.

03:14:34.744 --> 03:14:42.264
To become the spectator of one's own life, as Harry says, is to escape the suffering of life.

03:14:42.684 --> 03:14:45.824
I know you are surprised at my talking to you like this.

03:14:45.904 --> 03:14:47.764
You have not realised how I have developed.

03:14:48.404 --> 03:14:50.584
I was a schoolboy when you knew me.

03:14:50.724 --> 03:14:51.944
I am a man now.

03:14:52.664 --> 03:14:55.564
I have new passions, new thoughts, new ideas.

03:14:56.064 --> 03:14:57.024
I am different.

03:14:57.584 --> 03:14:58.904
But you must not like me less.

03:14:58.924 --> 03:15:02.644
I am changed, but you must always be my friend.

03:15:02.644 --> 03:15:08.524
Of course, I am very fond of Harry, but I know that you are better than he is.

03:15:08.844 --> 03:15:10.084
You are not stronger.

03:15:10.684 --> 03:15:12.284
Not too much afraid of life.

03:15:12.504 --> 03:15:13.604
But you are better.

03:15:14.284 --> 03:15:16.104
And how happy we used to be together!

03:15:16.164 --> 03:15:19.424
Don't leave me, Basil, and don't quarrel with me.

03:15:20.224 --> 03:15:22.204
I am what I am.

03:15:23.324 --> 03:15:25.204
There is nothing more to be said.

03:15:27.284 --> 03:15:29.824
Hallward felt strangely moved.

03:15:30.764 --> 03:15:35.124
Rugged and straightforward as he was, there was something in his nature that was purely

03:15:35.124 --> 03:15:36.584
feminine in its tenderness.

03:15:38.044 --> 03:15:44.284
The lad was infinitely dear to him, and his personality had been the great turning point

03:15:44.284 --> 03:15:44.924
of his art.

03:15:45.984 --> 03:15:48.804
He could not bear the idea of reproaching him any more.

03:15:49.404 --> 03:15:54.704
After all, his indifference was probably merely a mood that would pass away.

03:15:55.384 --> 03:15:57.644
There was so much in him that was good.

03:15:58.344 --> 03:16:00.204
So much in him that was noble.

03:16:01.344 --> 03:16:05.164
Well, Dorian, he said at length, with a sad smile,

03:16:06.284 --> 03:16:10.464
I won't speak to you again about this horrible thing after to-day.

03:16:11.244 --> 03:16:14.204
I only trust your name won't be mentioned in connection with it.

03:16:14.564 --> 03:16:17.984
The inquest is to take place this afternoon, if they summon you.

03:16:18.224 --> 03:16:22.284
Dorian shook his head, and a look of annoyance passed over his face at the mention of the

03:16:22.284 --> 03:16:23.184
word inquest.

03:16:23.184 --> 03:16:27.344
There was something so crude and vulgar about everything of the kind.

03:16:27.904 --> 03:16:30.644
They don't know my name, he answered.

03:16:31.124 --> 03:16:32.704
But surely she did.

03:16:33.364 --> 03:16:37.564
Only my Christian name, and that I am quite sure she never mentioned to anyone.

03:16:38.964 --> 03:16:44.884
She told me once that they were all rather curious to learn who I was, and that she invariably

03:16:44.884 --> 03:16:47.424
told them my name was Prince Charming.

03:16:48.284 --> 03:16:50.344
It was very pretty of her.

03:16:50.344 --> 03:16:53.004
You must do me a drawing of her, Basil.

03:16:53.644 --> 03:16:58.524
I should like to have something more of her than the memory of a few kisses and some broken

03:16:58.524 --> 03:16:59.764
pathetic words.

03:17:01.144 --> 03:17:04.984
I will try and do something, Dorian, if it would please you.

03:17:05.524 --> 03:17:07.724
But you must come and sit to me yourself again.

03:17:08.984 --> 03:17:11.584
I can't get on without you.

03:17:12.084 --> 03:17:14.424
I will never sit to you again, Basil.

03:17:14.964 --> 03:17:18.124
It is impossible, he exclaimed, starting back.

03:17:19.604 --> 03:17:21.084
Hallward stared at him.

03:17:21.584 --> 03:17:23.804
My dear boy, what nonsense! he cried.

03:17:24.784 --> 03:17:27.784
Do you mean to say you don't like what I did of you?

03:17:28.864 --> 03:17:29.844
Where is it?

03:17:30.444 --> 03:17:32.864
Why have you pulled that screen in front of it?

03:17:32.944 --> 03:17:34.064
Let me look at it.

03:17:34.064 --> 03:17:36.264
It is the best thing I have ever painted.

03:17:36.864 --> 03:17:38.764
Do take that screen away, Dorian.

03:17:38.764 --> 03:17:41.984
It is simply horrid of your servant hiding my work like that.

03:17:42.504 --> 03:17:45.584
I felt that the room looked different as I came in.

03:17:46.464 --> 03:17:48.724
My servant has nothing to do with it, Basil.

03:17:49.364 --> 03:17:52.324
You don't imagine I let him arrange my room for me?

03:17:52.484 --> 03:17:55.444
He settles my flowers for me sometimes, that is all.

03:17:55.644 --> 03:17:57.924
No, I did it myself.

03:17:58.144 --> 03:18:00.864
The light was too strong on the portrait.

03:18:01.864 --> 03:18:02.904
Too strong?

03:18:03.464 --> 03:18:04.784
Impossible, my dear fellow.

03:18:05.204 --> 03:18:07.044
It is an admirable place for it.

03:18:07.064 --> 03:18:07.924
Let me see it.

03:18:07.924 --> 03:18:10.504
And Hallward walked towards the corner of the room.

03:18:10.984 --> 03:18:15.444
A cry of terror broke from Dorian Gray's lips, and he rushed between Hallward and the screen.

03:18:15.444 --> 03:18:20.524
Basil, he said, looking very pale, you must not look at it.

03:18:20.584 --> 03:18:21.884
I don't wish you to.

03:18:22.824 --> 03:18:24.784
Not look at my own work.

03:18:25.384 --> 03:18:26.384
You are not serious.

03:18:26.424 --> 03:18:27.784
Why shouldn't I look at it?

03:18:27.964 --> 03:18:29.304
exclaimed Hallward, laughing.

03:18:29.884 --> 03:18:35.744
If you try to look at it, Basil, on my word of honour I will never speak to you again as long as I live.

03:18:36.684 --> 03:18:37.884
I am quite serious.

03:18:38.564 --> 03:18:41.824
I don't offer an explanation, and you are not to ask for any.

03:18:41.824 --> 03:18:47.704
But remember, if you touch this screen, everything is over between us.

03:18:49.164 --> 03:18:50.644
Hallward was thunderstruck.

03:18:51.744 --> 03:18:54.104
He looked at Dorian in absolute amazement.

03:18:54.824 --> 03:18:56.984
He had never seen him like this before.

03:18:57.664 --> 03:19:00.644
The lad was absolutely pallid with rage.

03:19:01.084 --> 03:19:05.344
His hands were clenched, and the pupils of his eyes were like disks of blue fire.

03:19:05.624 --> 03:19:06.964
He was trembling all over.

03:19:08.704 --> 03:19:09.024
Dorian?

03:19:09.584 --> 03:19:10.404
Don't speak.

03:19:10.404 --> 03:19:12.244
But what is the matter?

03:19:12.844 --> 03:19:21.164
Of course I won't look at it if you don't want me to, he said rather coldly, turning on his heel and going over towards the window.

03:19:22.004 --> 03:19:29.264
But really it seems rather absurd that I shouldn't see my own work, especially as I am going to exhibit it in Paris in the autumn.

03:19:30.684 --> 03:19:36.724
I should probably have to give it another coat of varnish before that, so I must see it some day.

03:19:37.184 --> 03:19:38.464
And why not to-day?

03:19:38.464 --> 03:19:40.564
To exhibit it?

03:19:41.224 --> 03:19:43.844
You want to exhibit it?

03:19:44.624 --> 03:19:48.224
exclaimed Dorian Gray, a strange sense of terror creeping over him.

03:19:49.024 --> 03:19:51.664
Was the world going to be shown his secret?

03:19:52.724 --> 03:19:55.064
Were people to gape at the mystery of his life?

03:19:55.244 --> 03:19:56.124
That was impossible.

03:19:57.004 --> 03:20:01.064
Something, he did not know what, had to be done at once.

03:20:01.904 --> 03:20:02.544
Yes.

03:20:03.304 --> 03:20:05.964
I don't suppose you will object to that.

03:20:06.704 --> 03:20:14.704
Georges Petit is going to collect all my best pictures for a special exhibition in the Rue de Cès, which will open the first week in October.

03:20:15.864 --> 03:20:18.524
The portrait will only be away a month.

03:20:19.044 --> 03:20:21.744
I should think you could easily spare it for that time.

03:20:21.944 --> 03:20:23.724
In fact you are sure to be out of town.

03:20:24.604 --> 03:20:29.764
And if you hide it always behind a screen you can't care much about it.

03:20:30.564 --> 03:20:33.204
Dorian Gray passed his hand over his head.

03:20:33.204 --> 03:20:35.524
There were beads of perspiration there.

03:20:36.184 --> 03:20:39.524
He felt that he was on the brink of a horrible danger.

03:20:40.904 --> 03:20:44.924
You told me a month ago that you would never exhibit it.

03:20:45.144 --> 03:20:46.404
Why have you changed your mind?

03:20:46.964 --> 03:20:51.124
You people who go in for being consistent have just as many moods as others.

03:20:52.064 --> 03:20:55.324
The only difference is that your moods are rather meaningless.

03:20:56.104 --> 03:21:03.044
You can't have forgotten that you assured me most solemnly that nothing in the world would induce you to send it to any exhibition.

03:21:03.644 --> 03:21:05.864
You told Harry exactly the same thing.

03:21:06.424 --> 03:21:09.384
He stopped suddenly, and a gleam of light came into his eyes.

03:21:10.124 --> 03:21:14.884
He remembered that Lord Henry had said to him once, half seriously and half in jest,

03:21:15.704 --> 03:21:22.064
If you want to have an interesting quarter of an hour, get Basil to tell you why he won't exhibit your picture.

03:21:22.064 --> 03:21:26.644
He told me why he wouldn't, and it was a revelation to me.

03:21:27.644 --> 03:21:30.624
Yes, perhaps Basil too had a secret.

03:21:31.344 --> 03:21:33.064
He would ask him and try.

03:21:33.724 --> 03:21:39.384
Basil, he said, coming over quite close and looking him straight in the face.

03:21:40.444 --> 03:21:42.804
We have each of us a secret.

03:21:43.124 --> 03:21:46.364
Let me know yours, and I will tell you mine.

03:21:47.544 --> 03:21:50.744
What was your reason for refusing to exhibit my picture?

03:21:53.224 --> 03:21:55.004
Hallward shuddered in spite of himself.

03:21:56.284 --> 03:22:02.004
Dorian, if I told you, you might like me less than you do, and you would certainly laugh at me.

03:22:02.304 --> 03:22:05.064
I could not bear your doing either of those two things.

03:22:05.684 --> 03:22:08.464
If you wish me to never look at your picture again, I am content.

03:22:09.164 --> 03:22:10.864
I have always you to look at.

03:22:11.324 --> 03:22:15.444
If you wish the best work I have ever done to be hidden from the world, I am satisfied.

03:22:15.844 --> 03:22:19.564
Your friendship is dearer to me than any fame or reputation.

03:22:19.564 --> 03:22:23.484
No, Basil, you must tell me," murmured Dorian Gray.

03:22:24.324 --> 03:22:26.324
I think I have a right to know.

03:22:26.944 --> 03:22:31.004
His feeling of terror had passed away, and curiosity had taken its place.

03:22:31.644 --> 03:22:35.204
He was determined to find out Basil Hallward's mystery.

03:22:36.004 --> 03:22:40.264
Let us sit down, Dorian," said Hallward, looking pale and pained.

03:22:40.264 --> 03:22:41.804
Let us sit down.

03:22:42.644 --> 03:22:46.164
I will sit in the shadow, and you shall sit in the sunlight.

03:22:47.264 --> 03:22:48.824
Our lives are like that.

03:22:48.824 --> 03:22:50.984
Just answer me one question.

03:22:52.044 --> 03:23:01.064
Have you noticed in the picture something that you did not like, something that probably at first did not strike you, but that revealed itself to you suddenly?

03:23:02.824 --> 03:23:09.944
Basil," cried the lad, clutching the arms of his chair with trembling hands and gazing at him with wild, startled eyes.

03:23:10.624 --> 03:23:12.844
I see you did. Don't speak.

03:23:14.104 --> 03:23:16.084
Wait till you hear what I have to say.

03:23:17.044 --> 03:23:25.044
It is quite true that I have worshipped you with far more romance of feeling than a man usually gives to a friend.

03:23:26.484 --> 03:23:28.844
Somehow I had never loved a woman.

03:23:29.464 --> 03:23:30.964
I suppose I never had time.

03:23:31.684 --> 03:23:40.744
Perhaps, as Harry says, grand passion is the privilege of those who have nothing to do, and that is the use of idle classes in a country.

03:23:40.744 --> 03:23:47.344
Well, for the moment I met you your personality had the most extraordinary influence over me.

03:23:48.664 --> 03:23:53.224
I admit that I adored you madly, extravagantly, absurdly.

03:23:53.584 --> 03:23:56.284
I was jealous of every one to whom you spoke.

03:23:57.084 --> 03:23:59.124
I wanted to have you all to myself.

03:24:00.164 --> 03:24:02.324
I was only happy when I was with you.

03:24:02.544 --> 03:24:05.424
When I was away from you, you were still present in my heart.

03:24:05.824 --> 03:24:07.644
It was all wrong and foolish.

03:24:07.644 --> 03:24:09.884
It is all wrong and foolish still.

03:24:10.664 --> 03:24:13.064
Of course I never let you know anything about this.

03:24:13.284 --> 03:24:14.444
It would have been impossible.

03:24:15.464 --> 03:24:16.904
You would not have understood it.

03:24:17.504 --> 03:24:19.544
I did not understand it myself.

03:24:20.504 --> 03:24:23.564
One day I determined to paint a wonderful portrait of you.

03:24:23.764 --> 03:24:25.784
It was to have been my masterpiece.

03:24:27.004 --> 03:24:28.484
It is my masterpiece.

03:24:29.344 --> 03:24:35.204
But as I worked at it, every flake and film of colour seemed to reveal my secret.

03:24:35.204 --> 03:24:38.964
I grew afraid that the world would know of my idolatry.

03:24:39.384 --> 03:24:43.824
I felt, Dorian, that I had told too much.

03:24:44.924 --> 03:24:49.324
Then it was that I resolved never to allow the picture to be exhibited.

03:24:49.784 --> 03:24:54.424
You were a little annoyed, but that you did not realise all that it meant to me.

03:24:55.184 --> 03:24:59.084
Harry, to whom I talked about it, laughed at me.

03:24:59.204 --> 03:25:00.824
But I did not mind that.

03:25:00.824 --> 03:25:06.144
When the picture was finished and I sat alone with it, I felt that I was right.

03:25:06.904 --> 03:25:14.304
Well, after a few days the portrait left my studio, and as soon as I got rid of the intolerable fascination of its presence,

03:25:14.524 --> 03:25:20.144
it seemed to me that I had been foolish in imagining that I had not said anything in it,

03:25:20.764 --> 03:25:23.904
more than you were extremely good-looking and that I could paint.

03:25:23.904 --> 03:25:34.084
Even now I cannot help feeling that it is a mistake to think that the passion one feels in creation is ever really shown in the work one creates.

03:25:35.124 --> 03:25:37.604
Art is more abstract than we fancy.

03:25:38.164 --> 03:25:43.544
Form and colour tell us of form and colour, that is all.

03:25:43.944 --> 03:25:49.944
It often seems to me that art conceals the artist far more completely than it ever reveals him.

03:25:49.944 --> 03:25:56.564
And so when I got this offer from Paris, I determined to make your portrait the principal thing in my exhibition.

03:25:57.944 --> 03:26:00.024
It never occurred to me that you would refuse.

03:26:01.024 --> 03:26:02.404
I see now that you were right.

03:26:02.864 --> 03:26:04.244
The picture must not be shown.

03:26:04.424 --> 03:26:08.464
You must not be angry with me, Dorian, for what I have told you.

03:26:08.584 --> 03:26:12.644
As I said to Harry once, you were made to be worshipped.

03:26:15.144 --> 03:26:17.124
Dorian Gray drew a long breath.

03:26:17.784 --> 03:26:22.464
The colour came back to his cheeks and a smile played across his lips.

03:26:23.604 --> 03:26:25.364
The peril was over.

03:26:25.944 --> 03:26:27.584
He was safe for the time.

03:26:28.344 --> 03:26:35.704
Yet he could not help feel infinite pity for the young man who had just made this strange confession to him.

03:26:36.544 --> 03:26:41.344
He wondered if he would ever be so dominated by the personality of a friend.

03:26:41.344 --> 03:26:46.244
Lord Harry had the charm of being very dangerous, but that was all.

03:26:46.404 --> 03:26:49.944
He was too clever and too cynical to be really fond of.

03:26:51.424 --> 03:26:56.744
Would there ever be someone who would fill him with a strange idolatry?

03:26:58.064 --> 03:27:00.744
Was that one of the things that life had in store?

03:27:01.164 --> 03:27:06.764
It is extraordinary to me, Dorian, said Hallward, that you should have seen this in the picture.

03:27:07.244 --> 03:27:09.284
Did you really see it?

03:27:09.284 --> 03:27:11.364
Of course I did.

03:27:13.664 --> 03:27:18.944
Well, you don't mind my looking at it now, Dorian Gray shook his head.

03:27:19.604 --> 03:27:21.344
You must not ask me that puzzle.

03:27:22.304 --> 03:27:26.664
I could not possibly let you stand in front of that picture.

03:27:28.044 --> 03:27:29.304
You will some day, surely?

03:27:30.544 --> 03:27:31.144
Never.

03:27:33.364 --> 03:27:36.284
Well, perhaps you are right.

03:27:36.944 --> 03:27:38.564
And now good-bye, Dorian.

03:27:39.264 --> 03:27:44.244
You have been the one person in my life of whom I have been really fond.

03:27:45.604 --> 03:27:48.384
I don't suppose I shall often see you again.

03:27:49.524 --> 03:27:55.224
You don't know what it cost me to tell you all that I have told you.

03:27:55.504 --> 03:27:59.324
My dear Basil, cried Dorian, what have you told me?

03:27:59.984 --> 03:28:02.824
Simply that you felt that you liked me too much?

03:28:04.184 --> 03:28:06.104
That is not even a compliment.

03:28:08.024 --> 03:28:10.664
It was not intended as a compliment.

03:28:11.084 --> 03:28:14.604
It was a confession, a very disappointing one.

03:28:15.044 --> 03:28:16.624
Why, what did you expect, Dorian?

03:28:17.284 --> 03:28:19.384
You didn't see anything else in that picture, did you?

03:28:19.404 --> 03:28:20.804
There was nothing else to see?

03:28:21.644 --> 03:28:24.064
No, there was nothing else to see.

03:28:24.144 --> 03:28:24.964
Why do you ask?

03:28:25.584 --> 03:28:28.484
But you mustn't talk about not meeting me again, or anything of that kind.

03:28:28.544 --> 03:28:29.924
You and I are friends, Basil.

03:28:30.764 --> 03:28:33.024
We must always remain so.

03:28:33.504 --> 03:28:36.884
You've got Harry, said Hallward sadly.

03:28:37.204 --> 03:28:41.024
Oh, Harry! cried the lad with a ripple of laughter.

03:28:41.424 --> 03:28:47.264
Harry spends his days in saying what is incredible, and his evenings in doing what is improbable.

03:28:47.964 --> 03:28:53.544
Just the sort of life I would like to lead, but still I don't think I would go to Harry if I was in trouble.

03:28:54.224 --> 03:28:56.164
I would sooner go to you, Basil.

03:28:57.344 --> 03:28:59.084
But you won't sit to me again?

03:29:00.564 --> 03:29:01.124
Impossible.

03:29:02.744 --> 03:29:05.484
You've spoiled my life as an artist by refusing, Dorian.

03:29:06.764 --> 03:29:10.504
No man comes across two ideal things.

03:29:10.984 --> 03:29:12.344
Few comes across one.

03:29:12.964 --> 03:29:18.184
I can't explain it to you, Basil, but I must never sit to you again.

03:29:18.744 --> 03:29:20.384
I will come and have tea with you.

03:29:20.384 --> 03:29:21.784
This will be just as pleasant.

03:29:22.564 --> 03:29:25.344
Pleasanter for you, I'm afraid, remembered Hallward regretfully.

03:29:26.104 --> 03:29:27.184
And now good-bye.

03:29:27.184 --> 03:29:31.184
I am sorry you won't let me look at the picture once again, but that can't be helped.

03:29:32.044 --> 03:29:34.584
I quite understand what you feel about it.

03:29:35.344 --> 03:29:38.784
As he left the room, Dorian Gray smiled to himself.

03:29:39.384 --> 03:29:40.144
Poor Basil!

03:29:40.884 --> 03:29:44.084
How little he knew of the true reason.

03:29:45.124 --> 03:29:55.264
And how strange it was that instead of being forced to reveal his own secret, he had succeeded almost by chance in wrestling a secret from his friend.

03:29:56.424 --> 03:30:00.024
How much that strange confession explained to him.

03:30:00.764 --> 03:30:08.984
Basil's absurd fits of jealousy, his wild devotion, his extravagant penegery, his curious reticences.

03:30:09.804 --> 03:30:12.844
He understood them all now, and he felt sorry.

03:30:13.624 --> 03:30:16.944
There was something tragic in a friendship so coloured by romance.

03:30:17.624 --> 03:30:19.284
He sighed and touched the bell.

03:30:19.864 --> 03:30:22.984
The portrait must be hidden away at all costs.

03:30:22.984 --> 03:30:26.244
He could not run such a risk of discovery again.

03:30:26.304 --> 03:30:36.324
It had been mad of him to have the thing remain, even for an hour, in a room to which any of his friends had access.

03:30:59.838 --> 03:31:03.158
THE PICTURE OF DORIAN GREY

03:31:17.858 --> 03:31:23.238
When his servant entered, he looked at him steadfastly, and wondered if he had thought

03:31:23.238 --> 03:31:28.738
of peering behind the screen. The man was quite impassive and waited for his orders.

03:31:29.778 --> 03:31:35.098
Dorian lit a cigarette and walked over to the glass and glanced into it. He could see

03:31:35.098 --> 03:31:41.838
the reflection of Victor's face perfectly. It was like a placid mask of servility. There

03:31:41.838 --> 03:31:48.298
was nothing to be afraid of there, yet he thought it best to be on his guard. Speaking

03:31:48.298 --> 03:31:54.818
very slowly, he told him to tell the housekeeper that he wanted to see her, and then to go

03:31:54.818 --> 03:32:00.098
to the frame-makers and ask him to send two of his men round at once. It seemed to him

03:32:00.098 --> 03:32:05.958
that as the man left the room he peered in the direction of the screen, or was that only

03:32:05.958 --> 03:32:06.698
his fancy?

03:32:07.638 --> 03:32:13.438
After a few moments Mrs. Leaf, a dear old lady in a black silk dress with a photograph

03:32:13.438 --> 03:32:18.938
of the late Mr. Leaf framed in a large gold brooch at her neck, and an old-fashioned

03:32:18.938 --> 03:32:22.538
thread mittens on her wrinkled hands bustled into the room.

03:32:23.578 --> 03:32:28.538
Well, Master Dorian, she said, what can I do for you? I beg your pardon, sir. Here came

03:32:28.538 --> 03:32:33.358
a courtesy. I shouldn't call you Master Dorian any more, but, Lord bless you, sir, I have

03:32:33.358 --> 03:32:37.918
known you since you were a baby. And many's the trick you've played on poor old Leaf.

03:32:37.918 --> 03:32:43.518
Not that you are not always a good boy, sir, but boys will be boys, Master Dorian, and

03:32:43.518 --> 03:32:47.338
jam is a temptation to the young, isn't it, sir?' He laughed.

03:32:48.078 --> 03:32:54.418
"'You must always call me Master Dorian, Leaf. I will be very angry with you if you don't.

03:32:54.518 --> 03:33:00.038
And I assure you I am quite as fond of jam now as I used to be. Only when I am asked

03:33:00.038 --> 03:33:05.178
out to tea I am never offered any. I want you to give me the key of the room at the

03:33:05.178 --> 03:33:06.258
top of the house.'

03:33:06.258 --> 03:33:11.938
"'The old school-room, Master Dorian? Why, it's full of dust. I must get it arranged

03:33:11.938 --> 03:33:15.858
and put straight before you get into it. It is not fit for you to see, Master Dorian.

03:33:15.878 --> 03:33:20.778
It is not, indeed. I don't want it put straight. Leaf, I only want the key.'

03:33:21.918 --> 03:33:27.298
"'Well, Master Dorian, you'll be covered with cobwebs if you goes into it. Why, it hasn't

03:33:27.298 --> 03:33:31.958
been open for nearly five years, not since his lordship died.'

03:33:31.958 --> 03:33:36.978
He winced at the mention of his dead uncle's name. He had hateful memories of him.

03:33:37.738 --> 03:33:42.738
"'That does not matter, Leaf,' he replied. All I want is the key.'

03:33:42.738 --> 03:33:47.338
"'And here is the key, Master Dorian,' said the old lady, after going over the contents

03:33:47.338 --> 03:33:53.138
of a bunch with tremulously uncertain hands. Here is the key. I'll have it off the ring

03:33:53.138 --> 03:33:57.758
in a moment, but you don't think of living up there, Master Dorian, and you're so comfortable

03:33:57.758 --> 03:33:58.338
here.'

03:33:58.338 --> 03:34:03.418
"'No, Leaf, I don't. I merely want to see the place, and perhaps store something in it.

03:34:03.498 --> 03:34:09.838
That is all. Thank you, Leaf. I hope your rheumatism is better. And mind you, send me

03:34:09.838 --> 03:34:15.218
up jam for breakfast.' Mrs. Leaf shook her head. Them foreigners don't understand jam,

03:34:15.218 --> 03:34:21.278
Master Dorian. They calls it compot. But I'll bring it to you myself some morning, if you

03:34:21.278 --> 03:34:22.398
lets me.'

03:34:22.398 --> 03:34:27.178
"'That will be very kind of you, Leaf,' he answered, looking at the key, and having

03:34:27.178 --> 03:34:32.718
made him an elaborate courtesy, the old lady left the room, her face wreathed in smiles.

03:34:33.618 --> 03:34:38.918
She had a strong objection to the French valet. It was a poor thing, she felt, for anyone

03:34:38.918 --> 03:34:45.378
to be born a foreigner. As the door closed, Dorian put the key in his pocket and looked

03:34:45.378 --> 03:34:51.158
round the room. His eye fell on a large purple satin coverlet heavily embroidered with gold,

03:34:51.378 --> 03:34:56.258
a splendid piece of late seventeenth-century Venetian work that his uncle had found in

03:34:56.258 --> 03:35:02.938
a convent near Bologna. Yes, that would serve to wrap the dreadful thing in. It had perhaps

03:35:02.938 --> 03:35:08.018
served often as a pall for the dead. Now it was to hide something that had a corruption

03:35:08.018 --> 03:35:13.878
of its own, worse than the corruption of death itself, something that would breed horrors

03:35:13.878 --> 03:35:15.578
and yet would never die.

03:35:17.158 --> 03:35:22.358
What the worm was to the corpse, his sins would be to the painted image on the canvas.

03:35:22.908 --> 03:35:28.218
They would mar its beauty and eat away its grace. They would defile it and make it shameful.

03:35:29.098 --> 03:35:34.678
And yet the thing would still live on. It would always be alive.

03:35:35.858 --> 03:35:40.578
He shuddered, and for a moment he regretted that he had not told Basil the true reason

03:35:40.578 --> 03:35:45.758
why he had wished to hide the picture away. Basil would have helped him to resist Lord

03:35:45.758 --> 03:35:51.138
Henry's influence, and the still more poisonous influences that came from his own temperament,

03:35:51.758 --> 03:35:57.998
the love that he bore him, for it was really love, had something noble and intellectual

03:35:57.998 --> 03:36:04.538
in it. It was not that merely physical admiration of beauty that is born of the senses and that

03:36:04.538 --> 03:36:11.278
dies when the senses tire. It was such a love as Michelangelo had known, and Montaigne and

03:36:11.278 --> 03:36:17.298
Winkleman and Shakespeare himself. Yes, Basil could have saved him, but it was too late

03:36:17.298 --> 03:36:17.738
now.

03:36:18.818 --> 03:36:26.478
The past could always be annihilated. Regret, denial, or forgetfulness could do that. But

03:36:26.478 --> 03:36:33.178
the future was inevitable. There were passions in him that would find their terrible outlet,

03:36:34.638 --> 03:36:38.298
dreams that would make the shadow of their evil real.

03:36:39.018 --> 03:36:43.738
He took up from the couch the great purple and gold texture that covered it, and, holding

03:36:43.738 --> 03:36:50.258
it in his hands, passed behind the screen. Was the face on the canvas viler than before?

03:36:51.298 --> 03:36:56.758
It seemed to him that it was unchanged, and yet his loathing of it was intensified. Gold

03:36:56.758 --> 03:37:04.298
hair, blue eyes, and rose-red lips, they all were there. It was simply the expression that

03:37:04.298 --> 03:37:13.718
had altered. That was horrible in its cruelty. Compared to what he saw in it of censure or

03:37:13.718 --> 03:37:19.438
Basil's reproaches about Sibyl Vane had been, how shallow, and of what little account. His

03:37:19.438 --> 03:37:25.318
own soul was looking out at him from the canvas and calling him to judgment. A look of pain

03:37:25.318 --> 03:37:31.038
came across him, and he flung the rich pall over the picture. As he did so, a knock came

03:37:31.038 --> 03:37:34.378
to the door. He passed out as his servant entered.

03:37:35.158 --> 03:37:41.098
The persons are here, monsieur. He felt that the man must be got rid of at once. He must

03:37:41.098 --> 03:37:45.938
not be allowed to know where the picture was being taken to. There was something sly about

03:37:45.938 --> 03:37:52.238
him, and yet thoughtful, treacherous eyes. Sitting down at the writing-table, he scribbled

03:37:52.238 --> 03:37:56.618
a note to Lord Henry, asking him to send round something to read, and reminding him that

03:37:56.618 --> 03:37:58.758
they were to meet at eight-fifteen that evening.

03:37:59.578 --> 03:38:05.198
"'Wait for an answer,' he said, handing it to him, and, "'Show the men in here.' In two

03:38:05.198 --> 03:38:09.898
or three minutes there was another knock, and Mr. Ashton himself, the celebrated frame-maker

03:38:09.898 --> 03:38:16.638
of South Audley Street, came in with a somewhat rough-looking young assistant. Mr. Ashton

03:38:16.638 --> 03:38:23.218
was a florid red-whiskered little man, whose admiration for art was considerably tempered

03:38:23.218 --> 03:38:30.918
by the inveterate impeccuinosity of most of the artists who dealt with him. As a rule,

03:38:31.158 --> 03:38:36.978
he never left his shop. He waited for people to come to him, but he always made an exception

03:38:36.978 --> 03:38:42.258
in favour of Dorian Gray. There was something about Dorian that charmed everybody. It was

03:38:42.258 --> 03:38:43.858
a pleasure even to see him.

03:38:45.338 --> 03:38:50.658
"'What can I do for you, Mr. Gray?' he said, rubbing his fat freckled hands.

03:38:50.918 --> 03:38:56.698
"'I thought I would do myself the honour of coming round in person. I have just got

03:38:56.698 --> 03:39:02.698
a beauty of a frame, sir, picked it up at a sale, old Florentine. Came from Fontill,

03:39:02.698 --> 03:39:09.698
I believe. Admirably suited for a religious picture, Mr. Gray. I'm sorry you have given

03:39:09.698 --> 03:39:13.978
yourself the trouble of coming round, Mr. Ashton. I will certainly drop in and look

03:39:13.978 --> 03:39:18.858
at the frame, though I don't go in much for religious art, but to-day I only want a picture

03:39:18.858 --> 03:39:23.458
carried to the top of the house for me. It is rather heavy, so I thought I would ask

03:39:23.458 --> 03:39:25.418
you to lend me a couple of your men.'

03:39:25.418 --> 03:39:31.878
"'No trouble at all, Mr. Gray. I am delighted to be of any service to you. Which is the

03:39:31.878 --> 03:39:34.018
work of art, sir?'

03:39:34.018 --> 03:39:37.318
"'This,' replied Dorian, moving the screen back.

03:39:37.638 --> 03:39:42.218
"'Can you move it, covering it all, just as it is? I don't want it to get scratched

03:39:42.218 --> 03:39:43.238
going upstairs.'

03:39:43.898 --> 03:39:48.698
"'There will be no difficulty, sir,' said the genial frame-maker, beginning, with the

03:39:48.698 --> 03:39:53.638
aid of his assistant, to unhook the picture from the long brass chain by which it was

03:39:53.638 --> 03:40:01.858
suspended. And now where shall we carry it to, Mr. Gray? I will show you the way, Mr.

03:40:01.858 --> 03:40:06.158
Ashton. Perhaps you better go in front. I am afraid it is right at the top of the house.

03:40:06.478 --> 03:40:10.878
You will go up at the front staircase, as it is wider.'

03:40:10.878 --> 03:40:16.298
He held the door open for them, and they passed out into the hall and began the ascent. The

03:40:16.298 --> 03:40:22.298
elaborate character of the frame has made the picture extremely bulky. And now and then,

03:40:22.438 --> 03:40:27.658
in spite of the obsequious protests of Mr. Ashton, who had a true tradesman's dislike

03:40:27.658 --> 03:40:33.378
of seeing a gentleman do anything useful, Dorian put his hand to it so as to help them.

03:40:34.198 --> 03:40:39.038
"'Something of a load to carry, sir,' gasped the little man, when they reached the top

03:40:39.038 --> 03:40:41.518
landing, and he wiped his shiny forehead.

03:40:42.158 --> 03:40:47.598
"'A terrible load to carry,' murmured Dorian, as he unlocked the door that opened into the

03:40:47.598 --> 03:40:53.218
room that was to keep for him the curious secret of his life and hide his soul from

03:40:53.218 --> 03:40:54.618
the eyes of men.

03:40:56.018 --> 03:41:02.038
"'He had not entered the place for more than four years. Not, indeed, since he had used

03:41:02.038 --> 03:41:06.678
it first as a playroom when he was a child, and then as a study when he grew somewhat

03:41:06.678 --> 03:41:12.978
older. It was a large, well-proportioned room which had been specially built by the last

03:41:12.978 --> 03:41:18.338
Lord Sherrod, for the use of the little nephew whom, being himself childless, and perhaps

03:41:18.338 --> 03:41:24.078
for other reasons, he had always hated and desired to keep at a distance. It did not

03:41:24.078 --> 03:41:30.778
appear to Dorian to have much changed. There was the huge Italian casson with its fantastically

03:41:30.778 --> 03:41:36.678
painted panels and its tarnished gilt mouldings, in which he had so often hidden himself as

03:41:36.678 --> 03:41:42.378
a boy. There was a satin-wood bookcase filled with his dogged school books. On the wall

03:41:42.378 --> 03:41:48.698
behind it was hanging the same ragged Flemish tapestry where a faded king and queen were

03:41:48.698 --> 03:41:53.718
playing chess in a garden while a company of hawkers rode by carrying hooded birds on

03:41:53.718 --> 03:42:00.738
their gauntleted wrists. How well he recalled it all! Every moment of his lonely childhood

03:42:00.738 --> 03:42:06.578
came back to him as he looked round. He remembered the stainless purity of his boyish life, and

03:42:06.578 --> 03:42:11.498
it seemed horrible to him that it was here that the fatal portrait was to be hidden away.

03:42:12.058 --> 03:42:19.638
How little he had thought in those dead days of all that was in store for him! But there

03:42:19.638 --> 03:42:23.938
was no other place in the house so secure from prying eyes as this. He had the key,

03:42:23.978 --> 03:42:29.718
and no one else could enter it. Beneath its purple pall, the face painted on the canvas

03:42:29.718 --> 03:42:36.238
could grow bestial, sodden and unclean. What did it matter? No one could see it. He himself

03:42:36.238 --> 03:42:41.758
would not see it. Why should he watch the hideous corruption of his soul? He kept his

03:42:41.758 --> 03:42:48.478
youth, that was enough. And besides, might not his nature grow finer after all? There

03:42:48.478 --> 03:42:54.138
was no reason that the future should be so full of shame. Some love might come across

03:42:54.138 --> 03:42:59.618
his life and purify him, and shield him from those sins that seemed to be already stirring

03:42:59.618 --> 03:43:07.298
in spirit and in flesh, those curious unpictured sins whose very mystery lent them their subtlety

03:43:07.298 --> 03:43:13.838
and their charm. Perhaps, some day, the cruel look would have passed away from the scarlet's

03:43:13.838 --> 03:43:21.478
sensitive mouth, and he might show to the world Basil Hallward's masterpiece. No, that

03:43:21.478 --> 03:43:26.998
was impossible. The thing upon the canvas was growing old, hour by hour and week by

03:43:26.998 --> 03:43:34.118
week. Even if it escaped the hideousness of sin, the hideousness of age was in store for

03:43:34.118 --> 03:43:43.698
it. The cheeks would become hollow or flaccid. The yellow crow's feet would creep round the

03:43:43.698 --> 03:43:50.258
brightness. The mouth would gape, droop, would be foolish or gross as the mouths of

03:43:50.258 --> 03:43:56.818
old men are. There would be the wrinkled throat, the cold, blue-veined hands, the twisted body

03:43:56.818 --> 03:44:03.658
that he remembered in the uncle who had been so stern to him in his boyhood. The picture

03:44:03.658 --> 03:44:07.798
had to be concealed. There was no help for it.

03:44:08.358 --> 03:44:12.558
"'Bring it in, Mr. Ashton, please,' he said, wearily, turning around.

03:44:13.258 --> 03:44:17.778
"'I'm sorry I kept you so long. I was thinking of something else.'

03:44:17.778 --> 03:44:22.938
"'Always glad to have a rest, Mr. Grey,' answered the frame-maker, who was still gasping

03:44:22.938 --> 03:44:25.778
for breath. "'Where shall we put it, sir?'

03:44:25.778 --> 03:44:30.958
"'Oh, anywhere. Here, this will do. I don't want to have it hung up. Just lean it against

03:44:30.958 --> 03:44:36.738
the wall. Thanks. Might one look at the work of art, sir?' Dorian started.

03:44:37.758 --> 03:44:42.958
"'It would not interest you, Mr. Ashton,' he said, keeping his eye on the old man. He

03:44:42.958 --> 03:44:46.778
felt ready to leap on him and fling him to the ground if he dared to lift the gorgeous

03:44:46.778 --> 03:44:48.978
hanging that concealed the secret of his life.

03:44:49.938 --> 03:44:54.058
"'I won't trouble you any more now. I am much obliged for your kindness in coming round.'

03:44:54.998 --> 03:44:59.458
"'Not at all, not at all, Mr. Grey. Ever ready to do anything for you, sir?'

03:44:59.458 --> 03:45:04.158
And Mr. Ashton trapped downstairs, followed by the assistant, who glanced back at Dorian

03:45:04.158 --> 03:45:11.098
with a look of shy wonder in his rough, uncomely face. He had never seen anyone so marvellous.

03:45:13.298 --> 03:45:17.858
When the sound of their footsteps had died away, Dorian locked the door and put the key

03:45:17.858 --> 03:45:25.258
in his pocket. He felt safe now. No one would ever look on the horrible thing. No eye but

03:45:25.258 --> 03:45:27.478
his would ever see his shame.

03:45:28.698 --> 03:45:33.198
On reaching the library he found that it was after five o'clock, and that the tea had already

03:45:33.198 --> 03:45:40.018
been brought up. On a little table of dark-perfumed wood thickly encrusted with nakra, a present

03:45:40.018 --> 03:45:45.938
from his guardian's wife, Lady Radley, who had spent the preceding winter in Cairo, was

03:45:45.938 --> 03:45:51.558
lying a note from Lord Henry, and beside it was a book bound in yellow paper, the cover

03:45:51.558 --> 03:45:57.618
slightly torn and the edges soiled. A copy of the third edition of St. James's Gazette

03:45:57.618 --> 03:46:04.018
had been placed on the tea-tray. It was evident that Victor had returned. He wondered if he

03:46:04.018 --> 03:46:08.298
had met the men in the hall as they were leaving the house, and had wormed out of them what

03:46:08.298 --> 03:46:13.298
they had been doing. He would be sure to miss the picture, had no doubt missed it already

03:46:13.298 --> 03:46:18.378
while he had been laying the tea-things. The screen had not been replaced, and the blank

03:46:18.378 --> 03:46:23.438
space on the wall was visible. Perhaps some night he might find him creeping upstairs

03:46:23.438 --> 03:46:28.738
and trying to force the door of the room. It was a horrible thing to have a spy in

03:46:28.738 --> 03:46:33.098
one's house. He had heard of rich men who had been blackmailed all their lives by some

03:46:33.098 --> 03:46:38.518
servant who had read a letter, or overheard a conversation, or picked up a card with an

03:46:38.518 --> 03:46:45.758
address, or found beneath a pillow a withered flower, or a bit of crumpled lace. He sighed,

03:46:46.158 --> 03:46:51.398
and having poured himself out some tea, opened Lord Henry's note. It was simply to say that

03:46:51.398 --> 03:46:56.098
he sent him round the evening paper and a book that might interest him, and that he

03:46:56.098 --> 03:47:01.158
would be at the club at eight fifteen. He opened the St. James's Langwoodly and looked

03:47:01.158 --> 03:47:06.038
through it. A red pencil mark on the fifth page caught his eye. He read the following

03:47:06.038 --> 03:47:06.758
paragraph.

03:47:08.618 --> 03:47:10.398
Inquest on an Actress

03:47:10.398 --> 03:47:16.538
An inquest was held this morning at the Bell Tavern, Hoxton Road, by Mr. Danby, the District

03:47:16.538 --> 03:47:22.558
Coroner, on the body of Sybil Vane, a young actress recently engaged at the Royal Theatre

03:47:22.558 --> 03:47:23.678
Holburne.

03:47:24.358 --> 03:47:30.098
A verdict of death by misadventure was returned. Considerable sympathy was expressed for the

03:47:30.098 --> 03:47:35.298
mother of the deceased, who was greatly affected during the giving of her own evidence, and

03:47:35.298 --> 03:47:42.498
that of Dr. Birel, who had made the post-mortem examination of the deceased. He frowned slightly,

03:47:42.898 --> 03:47:47.538
and tearing the paper in two, went across the room and flung the pieces into a gilt

03:47:47.538 --> 03:47:54.998
basket. How ugly it all was, and how horribly real ugliness made things! He felt a little

03:47:54.998 --> 03:47:59.258
annoyed with Lord Henry for having sent him the account, and it was certainly stupid of

03:47:59.258 --> 03:48:05.378
him to have marked it with a red pencil. Victor might have read it. The man knew more than

03:48:05.378 --> 03:48:11.678
enough English for that. Perhaps he had read it, and had begun to suspect something.

03:48:12.658 --> 03:48:13.198
And?

03:48:14.098 --> 03:48:19.618
And yet what did it matter? What had Dorian Gray to do with Sybil Vane's death? There

03:48:19.618 --> 03:48:25.818
was nothing to fear. Dorian Gray had not killed her. His eye fell on the yellow book that

03:48:25.818 --> 03:48:28.458
Lord Henry had sent him. What was it, he wondered?

03:48:28.958 --> 03:48:33.858
He went towards the little pearl-coloured octagonal stand that had always looked to

03:48:33.858 --> 03:48:39.938
him like the work of some strange Egyptian bees who rotten silver, and took the volume

03:48:39.938 --> 03:48:45.498
up. He flung himself into an arm-chair and began to turn over the leaves. After a few

03:48:45.498 --> 03:48:50.318
minutes he became absorbed. It was the strangest book he had ever read.

03:48:50.878 --> 03:48:56.918
It seemed to him that in exquisite raiment and to the delicate sound of flutes the sins

03:48:56.918 --> 03:49:04.098
of the world were passing in dumb show before him. Things that he had dimly dreamed of were

03:49:04.098 --> 03:49:09.798
suddenly made real to him. Things of which he had never dreamed were gradually revealed.

03:49:11.338 --> 03:49:18.538
It was a novel without a plot, and with only one character being, indeed, simply a psychological

03:49:18.538 --> 03:49:24.498
study of a certain young Parisian who spent his life trying to realise in the nineteenth

03:49:24.498 --> 03:49:29.858
century all the passions and modes of thought that belonged to every century except his

03:49:29.858 --> 03:49:35.818
own, and to sum up, as it were, in himself the various moods through which the world's

03:49:35.818 --> 03:49:42.498
spirit had ever passed, loving, for their mere artificiality, those renunciations that

03:49:42.498 --> 03:49:49.098
men had unwisely called virtue, as much as those natural rebellions that wise men still

03:49:49.098 --> 03:49:55.988
call sin. The style in which it was written was that curious jeweled style, vivid and

03:49:55.988 --> 03:50:02.708
obscure at once, full of argot and archaisms, of technical expressions and of elaborate

03:50:02.708 --> 03:50:08.828
paraphrases that characterises the work of some of the finest artists of the French school

03:50:08.828 --> 03:50:17.208
of decadence. There were in it metaphors as monstrous as orchids and as evil in colour.

03:50:17.928 --> 03:50:24.628
The life of the senses were described in the terms of mystical philosophy. One hardly knew

03:50:24.628 --> 03:50:30.508
at times whether one was reading the spiritual ecstasies of some medieval saint or the morbid

03:50:30.508 --> 03:50:37.648
confessions of a modern sinner. It was a poisonous book. The heavy odour of incense seemed to

03:50:37.648 --> 03:50:43.508
cling about its pages and to trouble the brain. The mere cadence of the senses, the subtle

03:50:43.508 --> 03:50:49.968
monotony of their music, so full, as it was, of complex refrains and movements elaborately

03:50:49.968 --> 03:50:56.108
repeated, produced in the mind of the lad, as he passed from chapter to chapter, a form

03:50:56.108 --> 03:51:02.288
of reverie, a malady of dreaming, that made him unconscious of the falling day and the

03:51:02.288 --> 03:51:11.128
creeping shadows. Cloudless and pierced by one solitary star, a copper-green sky gleamed

03:51:11.128 --> 03:51:17.648
through the windows. He read on by its one light till he could read no more. Then, after

03:51:17.648 --> 03:51:22.708
his valet had reminded him several times of the lateness of the hour, he got up, and going

03:51:22.708 --> 03:51:27.608
into the next room placed the book on the little Florentine table that always stood

03:51:27.608 --> 03:51:33.508
at his bedside, and began to dress for dinner. It was almost nine o'clock before he reached

03:51:33.508 --> 03:51:38.728
the club, where he found Lord Henry sitting alone in the morning-room, looking very bored.

03:51:40.248 --> 03:51:45.768
"'I am so sorry, Harry,' he cried, "'but really it is entirely your fault. That book

03:51:45.768 --> 03:51:49.048
you sent me so fascinated me, I forgot what the time was.'

03:51:50.468 --> 03:51:55.108
"'I thought you would like it,' replied his host, rising from his chair.

03:51:55.688 --> 03:52:00.008
"'I didn't say I liked it, Harry, I said it fascinated me. There is a great difference.'

03:52:00.768 --> 03:52:06.728
"'Ah, if you have discovered that, you have discovered a great deal,' murmured Lord Henry,

03:52:06.768 --> 03:52:13.188
with his curious smile. "'Come, let us go into dinner. It is dreadfully late, and I am afraid

03:52:13.188 --> 03:52:23.688
the champagne will be too much iced.'

03:52:23.688 --> 03:52:24.068
Grey

03:52:50.892 --> 03:52:52.292
PILOT

03:52:56.872 --> 03:53:07.392
For years Dorian Gray could not free himself from the memory of this book. Or perhaps it would be more accurate to say that he never sought to free himself from it.

03:53:07.392 --> 03:53:26.032
He procured from Paris no less than five large paper copies of the first edition, and had them bound in different colors so that they might suit his various moods, and the changing fancies of a nature over which he seemed, at times, to have almost entirely lost control.

03:53:26.032 --> 03:53:48.152
The hero, the wonderful young Parisian, in whom the romantic temperament and the scientific temperament were so strangely blended, became to him a kind of prefiguring type of himself, and indeed the whole book seemed to him to contain the story of his own life, written before he had lived it.

03:53:48.952 --> 03:54:15.072
In one point he was more fortunate than the book's fantastic hero. He never knew, never indeed had any cause to know, that somewhat grotesque dread of mirrors, and polished metal surfaces, and still water, which came upon the young Parisian so early in his life and was occasioned by the sudden decay of a beauty that had once, apparently, been so remarkable.

03:54:15.072 --> 03:54:40.832
It was with an almost cruel joy, and perhaps in nearly every joy, as certainly in every pleasure cruelty has its place, that he used to read the latter part of the book, with its really tragic, if somewhat overemphasized, account of the sorrow and despair of one who had lost himself what in others, and in the world he had most valued.

03:54:42.072 --> 03:55:09.432
He, at any rate, had no cause to fear that. The boyish beauty that had so fascinated Basil Hallward, and many others beside him, seemed to never leave him. Even those who had heard the most evil things against him, and from time to time strange rumors about his mode of life crept through London, and became the chatter of clubs, could not believe anything to his dishonour when they saw him.

03:55:09.432 --> 03:55:29.332
He had always the look of one who had kept himself unspotted from the world. Men who talked grossly became silent when Dorian Gray entered the room. There was something in the purity of his face that rebuked them. His mere presence seemed to recall to them the innocence that they had tarnished.

03:55:29.332 --> 03:55:59.312
They wondered how one so charming and graceful as he was, could have escaped the stain of an age that was at once sordid and sensuous. He himself, on returning home from one of those mysterious and prolonged absences that gave rise to such strange conjecture among those who were his friends, or thought that they were so, would creep upstairs to the locked room, open the door with the key that never left him, and stand, with a mirror, in front of the porch of the room, and look out the window.

03:55:59.332 --> 03:56:11.212
This was the portrait that Basil Hallward had painted of him, looking now at the evil and aging face on the canvas, and now at the fair young face that laughed back at him from the polished glass.

03:56:11.212 --> 03:56:24.492
The very sharpness of the contrast used to quicken his sense of pleasure. He grew more and more enamored of his own beauty, more and more interested in the corruption of his own soul.

03:56:24.492 --> 03:56:43.832
He would examine with minute care, and often with a monstrous and terrible delight, the hideous lines that seared the wrinkling forehead or crawled around the heavy sensual mouth, wondering sometimes which were the more horrible, the signs of sin or the signs of age.

03:56:43.832 --> 03:56:54.092
He would place his white hands beside the coarse bloated hands of the picture and smile. He mocked the misshapen body and failing limbs.

03:56:54.892 --> 03:57:10.612
There were moments, indeed, at night, when, lying sleepless in his own delicately scented chamber or in the sordid room of the little ill-famed tavern near the docks which, under an assumed name and in disguise, it was his habit to frequent,

03:57:10.612 --> 03:57:21.492
he would think of the ruin he had brought upon his soul with a pity that was all the more poignant because it was purely selfish. But moments such as these were rare.

03:57:22.512 --> 03:57:37.312
The curiosity about life that, many years before Lord Henry had first stirred in him as they sat together in the garden of their friend, seemed to increase with gratification. The more he knew, the more he desired to know.

03:57:37.312 --> 03:57:57.572
He had mad hungers that grew more ravenous as he fed them. Yet he was not really reckless. At any rate, in his relations to society, once or twice every month during the winter and on each Wednesday evening, while the season lasted, he would throw open to the world his beautiful house

03:57:57.572 --> 03:58:15.872
and have the most celebrated musicians of the day to charm his guests with the wonders of their art. His little dinners, in the setting of which Lord Henry always assisted him, were noted as much for the careful selection and placing of those invited as for the exquisite

03:58:15.872 --> 03:58:41.672
decoration of the table, with its subtle symphonic arrangements of exotic flowers and embroidered cloths, and antique plate of gold and silver. Indeed, there were many, especially among the very young men, who saw, or fancied that they saw, in Dorian Gray the true realization of a type of which they had often dreamed in Eaton or Oxford days.

03:58:41.672 --> 03:59:09.372
A type that was to combine something of the real culture of the scholar with all the grace and distinction and perfect manner of a citizen of the world. To them, he seemed to belong to those whom Dante describes as having sought to make themselves perfect by the worship of beauty. Like Gautier, he was one for whom the visible world existed.

03:59:10.772 --> 03:59:35.892
And certainly, to him, life itself was the first, the greatest of the arts. And for it, all the other arts seemed to be but a preparation. Fashion, by which it is really fantastic, comes for a moment universal. And dandyism, which, in its own way, is an attempt to assert the absolute modernity of beauty, had of course their fascination for him.

03:59:35.892 --> 03:59:58.892
His mode of dressing, and the particular styles that he affected from time to time, had their marked influence on the young exquisites of the Mayfair balls and the Paul Moll Club windows, who copied him in everything that he did, and tried to reproduce the accidental charm of his graceful, though to him only half serious, fopperies.

03:59:59.732 --> 04:00:18.812
For, while he was but too ready to accept the position that was almost immediately offered to him on his coming of age, and found, indeed, a subtle pleasure in the thought that he might really become, to the London of his own day, what to imperial Neronian Rome, the author of the Satyricon, had once been.

04:00:18.812 --> 04:00:48.212
Yet in his inmost heart he desired to be something more than a mere arbiter, elegantarium. To be consulted on the wearing of a jewel, or the knotting of a necktie, or the conduct of a cane, he sought to elaborate some new scheme of life that would have its reasoned philosophy and its ordered principles, and find in the spiritualizing of the senses its highest realization.

04:00:50.072 --> 04:01:08.552
The worship of the senses has often, and with much justice, been decried, men feeling a natural instinct of terror about passions and sensations that seem stronger than ourselves, and that we are conscious of sharing with the less highly organized forms of existence.

04:01:08.552 --> 04:01:35.132
But it appeared to Dorian Gray that the true nature of the senses had never been understood, and that they remained savage and animal merely because the world had sought to starve them into submission, or to kill them by pain, instead of aiming at making them elements of a new spirituality, of which a fine instinct for beauty was to be their dominant characteristic.

04:01:35.132 --> 04:01:47.252
As he looked back upon man moving through history, he was haunted by a feeling of loss. So much had been surrendered, and to such little purpose.

04:01:47.252 --> 04:02:07.212
There had been mad willful rejections, monstrous forms of self-torture and self-denial, whose origin was fear, and whose result was a degradation infinitely more terrible than the fancy degradation from which, in their ignorance, they had sought to escape.

04:02:07.212 --> 04:02:18.712
Nature, in her wonderful irony, driving the anchorite out to herd with the wild animals of the desert, and giving to the hermit the beasts of the field as his companions.

04:02:20.652 --> 04:02:36.392
Yes, there was to be, as Lord Henry had prophesied, a new hedonism that was to recreate life, and to save it from that harsh, uncomely puritanism that is having, in our own day, its curious revival.

04:02:36.992 --> 04:02:57.412
It was to have its service of the intellect, certainly. Yet it was never to accept any theory or system that would involve the sacrifice of any mode of passionate experience. Its aim, indeed, was to be experience itself, and not the fruits of experience, sweet or bitter as they might be.

04:02:57.412 --> 04:03:15.412
Of the asceticism that deadens the senses, as of the vulgar profligacy that dulls them, it was to know nothing. But it was to teach man to concentrate himself upon the moments of a life that is itself but a moment.

04:03:15.412 --> 04:03:34.912
There are few of us who have not sometimes wakened before dawn, either after one of those dreamless nights that make one almost enamored of death, or one of those nights of horror and misshapen joy, when through the chambers of the brain sweep phantoms more terrible than reality itself.

04:03:34.912 --> 04:03:53.292
An instinct with that vivid life that lurks in our grotesques, and that lends to Gothic art its enduring vitality, this art being, one might fancy, especially the art of those whose minds have been troubled with the melody of reverie.

04:03:54.212 --> 04:04:21.612
Gradually white fingers creep through the curtains, and they appear to tremble. Black fantastic shadows crawl into the corners of the room and crouch there. Outside there is the stirring of birds among the leaves, or the sound of men going forth to their work, or the sigh and sob of the wind coming down from the hills and wandering round the silent house, as though it feared to awake the sleepers.

04:04:21.612 --> 04:04:35.572
Veil after veil of thin dusky gauze is lifted, and by degrees the forms and colours of things are restored to them, and we watch the dawn remaking the world in its antique pattern.

04:04:36.232 --> 04:04:56.992
The wan mirrors get back their mimic life. The flameless tapers stand where we have left them, and beside them lies the half-read book that we had been studying, or the wired flower that we had worn at the ball, or the letter that we had been afraid to read, or that we had read too often.

04:04:57.792 --> 04:05:26.972
Nothing seems to us changed. Out of the unreal shadows of the night come back the real life that we had known. We have to resume it where we had left off, and there steals over us a terrible sense of the necessity, for the continuance of energy in the same worrisome round of stereotyped habits, or a wild longing, it may be, that our eyelids might open some morning upon a world that we had never known.

04:05:26.972 --> 04:05:49.552
A world that had been refashioned new from our pleasure in the darkness. A world in which things would have fresh shapes and colours, and be changed, or have other secrets. A world in which the past would have little or no place, or survive at any rate in no conscious form of obligation or regret.

04:05:49.552 --> 04:06:08.352
The remembrance even of joy having its bitterness, and the memories of pleasure, their pain. It was the creation of such worlds as these that seemed Dorian Gray to be the true object, or among the true objects, of life.

04:06:08.352 --> 04:06:25.452
And in his search for sensations that would be at once new and delightful, and possess that element of strangeness that is so essential to romance, he would often adopt certain modes of thought that he knew to be really alien to his nature.

04:06:25.452 --> 04:06:48.992
Abandon himself to their subtle influences, and then, having, as it were, caught their colour and satisfied his intellectual curiosity, leave them with that curious indifference that is not incompatible with a real ardour of temperament, and that indeed, according to certain modern psychologists, is often a condition of it.

04:06:50.252 --> 04:07:18.972
It was rumoured of him once that he was about to join the Roman Catholic communion, and certainly the Roman ritual had always a great attraction for him. The daily sacrifice, more awful really than all the sacrifices of the antique world, stirred him as much as its superb rejection of the evidence of the senses, as by the primitive simplicity of its elements and the eternal pathos of the human tragedy that it sought to symbolise.

04:07:18.972 --> 04:07:45.012
He loved to kneel down on the cold marble pavement, and with the priest, in his stiff flowered cope, slowly and with white hands moving aside the veil of the tabernacle, and raising aloft the jeweled lantern-shaped monstrance with that pallid wafer that at times, one would fain think, is indeed the Panis Caelestis, the Bread of Angels.

04:07:45.012 --> 04:08:04.232
Or, robed in the garments of the Passion of Christ, breaking the host into the chalice and smiting his breast for his sins, the fuming censors that the grave boys in their lace and scarlet tossed into the air like great gilt flowers had their subtle fascination for him.

04:08:04.232 --> 04:08:19.132
As he passed out, he used to look with wonder at the black confessionals, and longed to sit in the dim shadow of them and listen to men and women whispering through the tarnished grating the true story of their lives.

04:08:19.132 --> 04:08:40.992
But he never fell into the error of arresting his intellectual development by any formal acceptance of creed or system, or of mistaking, for a house in which to live, an inn that is but suitable for the sojourn of a night, or for a few hours of a night in which there are no stars and the moon is in travail,

04:08:41.952 --> 04:08:54.732
mysticism, with its marvelous power of making common things strange to us, and the subtle antimonianism that always seems to accompany it, moved him for a season.

04:08:54.732 --> 04:09:20.992
And for a season he inclined to the materialistic doctrines of the Darwinismist movement in Germany, and found a curious pleasure in tracing the thoughts and passions of men to some pearly cell in the brain or some white nerve in the body, delighting in the conception of the absolute dependence of the spirit on certain physical conditions, morbid or healthy, normal or diseased.

04:09:20.992 --> 04:09:40.992
Yet, as has been said of him before, no theory of life seemed to him to be of any importance compared with life itself. He felt keenly conscious of how barren all intellectual speculation is when separated from action and experiment.

04:09:40.992 --> 04:09:59.272
He knew that the senses, no less than the soul, have their mysteries to reveal. And so he would now study perfumes, and the secrets of their manufacture distilling heavily scented oils and burning odorous gums from the East.

04:09:59.272 --> 04:10:21.052
He saw that there was no mood of the mind which had not its counterpart in the sensuous life, and set himself to discover their true relations, wondering what there was in frankincense that made one mystical, and in ambergris that stirred one's passions, and in violets that woke the memory of dead romances,

04:10:21.052 --> 04:10:43.252
and in musk that troubled the brain, and in champac that stained the imagination, and seeking often to elaborate a real psychology of perfumes, and to estimate the several influences of sweet-smelling roots and scented pollen-laden flowers, of aromatic balms, and of dark and fragrant woods,

04:10:43.252 --> 04:10:53.012
of spikenard that sickens, of havinia that makes men mad, and of aloes that are said to be able to expel melancholy from the soul.

04:10:53.012 --> 04:11:13.172
At another time he devoted himself entirely to music, and in a long, latticed room, with a vermilion and gold ceiling, and walls of olive-green lacquer, he used to give curious concerts in which mad gypsies tore wild music from little zithers,

04:11:13.172 --> 04:11:37.372
or grave yellow-shald Tunisians, plucked at the strained strings of monstrous lutes, while grinning negroes beat monotonously upon copper drums, or turbaned Indians crouching upon scarlet mats, blew through long pipes of reed or brass, and charmed, or feigned to charm, great hooded snakes and horrible horned adders.

04:11:37.372 --> 04:11:53.392
The harsh intervals and shrill discords of barbaric music stirred him at times when Schubert's grace, or Chopin's beautiful sorrows, and the mighty harmonies of Beethoven himself fell unheeded on his ear.

04:11:53.392 --> 04:12:11.032
He collected together from all parts of the world the strangest instruments that could be found, either in the tombs of dead nations, or among the few savage tribes that had survived contact with Western civilizations, and loved to touch and try them.

04:12:11.032 --> 04:12:41.012
He had the mysterious Juru-Paris of the Rio Negro Indians that women are not allowed to look at, and that even youths may not see till they have been subjected to fasting and scourging, and the earthen jards of the Peruvians that have the shrill cries of birds, and flutes of human bones such as Alfando de Oval heard in Chile, and the sonorous green stones that are found near Cusco, and the

04:12:44.232 --> 04:13:10.012
He had painted gourds filled with pebbles that rattled when they were shaken, the long clarin of the Mexicans into which the performer does not blow, but through which he inhales the air, the harsh touré of the Amazon tribes that is sounded by the sentinels who sit all day long in trees, and that can be heard, it is said, at a distance of three leagues.

04:13:11.732 --> 04:13:39.992
The Tiponazatele that has two vibrating tongues of wood and is beaten with sticks that are smeared with an elastic gum obtained from the milky substance of plants, the yottle bells of the Aztecs that are hung in clusters like grapes, and a huge cylindrical drum covered with the skins of great serpents, like the one that Bernal Diaz saw when he went with Cortes into the Mexican temple, and it is said that he is the sonorous green stones that

04:13:39.992 --> 04:14:09.892
and of whose doleful sound he has left us so vivid a description. The fantastic character of these instruments fascinated him, and he had a curious delight in the thought that art, like nature, has her monsters, things of bestial shape and with hideous voices, yet after some time he worried of them, and would sit in his box at the opera either alone or with Lord Henry, listening in rapt pleasure to Tannhäuser,

04:14:09.892 --> 04:14:29.212
and seeing in that great work of art a presentation of the tragedy of his own soul. On another occasion he took up the study of jewels and appeared at a costume ball as Anne de Joyeuse, Admiral of France, in a dress covered with 560 pearls.

04:14:29.212 --> 04:14:52.432
He would often spend a whole day settling and resettling in their cases the various stones that he had collected, such as the olive green chryso-barrel that turns red by lamplight, the chemophane with its wire-like line of silver, the pistachio-colored periodot, rose pink and wine-yellow topazes,

04:14:52.432 --> 04:15:08.272
carbuncles of fiery scarlet with tremulous four-rayed stars, flame-red cinnamastones, orange and violet spinels, and amethysts with their alternate layers of ruby and sapphire.

04:15:08.272 --> 04:15:31.632
He loved the red gold of the sunstone, and the moonstone's pearly whiteness, and the broken rainbow of the milky opal. He procured from Amsterdam three emeralds of extraordinary size and richness of color, and had a turquoise de la vieille roche that was the envy of all the connoisseurs.

04:15:31.632 --> 04:15:51.892
He discovered wonderful stories also about jewels. In Alfonso's Clericales Disciplina a serpent was mentioned with the eyes of real Jackson, and in the Romantic History of Alexander he was said to have found snakes in the Vale of Jordan with collars of real emeralds growing on their backs.

04:15:51.892 --> 04:16:05.112
There was a gem in the brain of the dragon, Philostratus told us, and by the exhibition of gold letters and a scarlet robe the monster could be thrown into a magical sleep and slain.

04:16:05.112 --> 04:16:15.332
According to the great alchemist Pierre de Boniface, the diamond rendered a man invisible, and the agate of India made him eloquent.

04:16:15.332 --> 04:16:34.212
The Cornelian appeased anger, and the hyacinth provoked sleep, and the amethyst drove away the fumes of wine. The garnet cast out demons, and the hydropicus deprived the moon of her color. The selenite waxed and wand with the moon.

04:16:34.212 --> 04:16:51.292
And the Molossius that discovers thieves could be affected only by the blood of kids. Leonardo's Camelus had seen a white stone taken from the brain of a newly killed toad that was a certain antidote against poison.

04:16:51.292 --> 04:17:08.252
The bezoar that was found in the heart of the Arabian deer was a charm that could cure the plague. In the nests of Arabian birds was the aspalates that, according to Democritus, kept the wearer from any danger of fire.

04:17:09.292 --> 04:17:29.272
The king of Selan rode through his city with a large ruby in his hand as the ceremony of his coronation. The gates of the palace of John the priest were made of sardius with the horn of the horned snake in rot so that no man might bring poison within.

04:17:29.272 --> 04:17:40.372
Over the gable were two golden apples, in which were two carbuncles, so that the gold might shine by day and the carbuncles by night.

04:17:40.372 --> 04:18:03.212
In Loge's strange romance A Marguerite of America, it was stated that in the chamber of Marguerite were seen all the chaste ladies of the world, inchaste out of silver, looking through fair mirrors of chrysalites, carbuncles, sapphires, and green emeralds.

04:18:03.212 --> 04:18:21.852
Marco Polo had watched the inhabitants of Zapango Place a rose-coloured pearl in the mouth of the dead. A sea monster had been enamoured of the pearl that the diver brought to King Perose's, and had slain the thief, and mourned for seven moons over his loss.

04:18:21.852 --> 04:18:36.792
When the Huns lured the king into the great pit, he flung it away, Procopius tells the story. Nor was it ever found again, though the emperor Anastasius offered five hundred weight of gold pieces for it.

04:18:36.792 --> 04:18:46.672
The king of Malabar had shown a Venetian a rosary of one hundred and four pearls, one for every god that he worshipped.

04:18:46.672 --> 04:19:04.672
When the duke de Valentois, son of Alexander VI., visited Louis XII. of France, his horse was loaded with gold leaves, according to Brantôme, and his cap had double rows of rubies that threw out a great light.

04:19:04.672 --> 04:19:18.822
Charles of England had ridden in stirrups hung with three hundred and twenty-one diamonds. Richard II. had a coat, valued at thirty thousand marks, which was covered with ballast rubies.

04:19:18.822 --> 04:19:37.982
Paul described Henry VIII. on his way to the tower previous to his coronation as wearing a jacket of raised gold, the placard embroidered with diamonds and other rich stones, and a great boderique about his neck of large balaces.

04:19:37.982 --> 04:19:58.962
The favourites of James I. wore earrings of emeralds set in gold filigrane. Edward II. gave to Piers Geveston a suit of red-gold armour studded with jacksons, and a collar of gold roses set with turquoise stones and a skullcap parsem with pearls.

04:19:58.962 --> 04:20:19.082
Henry II. wore jewelled gloves reaching to the elbow, and had a hawk-glove set with twelve rubies and fifty-two great pearls. The ducal hat of Charles the Rash, the last duke of Burgundy of his race, was studded with sapphires and hung with pear-shaped pearls.

04:20:20.262 --> 04:20:31.502
How exquisite life had once been! How gorgeous in its pomp and decoration! Even to read of the luxury of the dead was wonderful.

04:20:34.102 --> 04:21:01.482
Then he turned his attention to embroideries and to the tapestries that performed the office of frescoes in the chill rooms of the northern nations of Europe. As he investigated the subject, and he always had extraordinary faculty of becoming absolutely absorbed for the moment in whatever he took up, he was almost saddened by the reflection of the ruin that time brought on beautiful and wonderful things.

04:21:01.482 --> 04:21:25.162
He, at any rate, had escaped that. Summer followed summer and the yellow jonkills bloomed and died many times, and nights of horror repeated the story of their shame. But he was unchanged. No winter marred his face or stained his flower-like bloom. How different it was with material things!

04:21:26.082 --> 04:21:50.522
Where had they gone to? Where was the great crocus-colored robe on which the gods fought against the giants that had been worked for Athena? Where the huge velarium that Nero had stretched across the Colosseum at Rome, on which were represented the starry sky and Apollo driving a chariot drawn by white-gilt-reigned steeds?

04:21:50.522 --> 04:22:20.502
He longed to see the curious table-napkins wrought by Elagabalus, on which were displayed all the dainties and viands that could be wanted for a feast, the mortuary-cloth of King Chiliparic with its three hundred gold beads, the fantastic robes that excited with indignation of the Bishop of Pontus, and were figured with lions, panthers, bears, dogs, forests, rocks, etc.

04:22:20.522 --> 04:22:48.642
all, in fact, that a painter can copy from nature, and the coat that Charles of Orléans once wore, on the sleeves of which were embroidered the verses of a song beginning, Madame, je suis ton joyeux, the musical accompaniment of the words being wrought in gold thread, and each note a square shape, in those days, formed with four pearls.

04:22:48.642 --> 04:23:17.302
He read of the poem that was prepared at the palace at Rhine, for the use of Queen Joan of Burgundy, and was decorated with thirteen hundred and twenty-one parrots, made in brewery, and blazoned with the King's arms in five hundred and sixty-one butterflies, whose wings were similarly ornamented with the arms of the Queen, the whole worked in gold.

04:23:18.142 --> 04:23:44.402
Catherine de Medici's had a morning-bed made for her of black velvet powdered with crescents and suns. Its curtains were of damask with leafy wreaths and garlands, figured upon a gold and silver background, and fringed along the edges with broideries of pearls, and it stood in a room hung with rows of the Queen's devices in cut black velvet upon cloth of silver.

04:23:44.402 --> 04:24:11.402
Louis XIV had gold-embroidered keratides fifteen feet high in his apartment. The state bed of Sobieski, King of Poland, was made of smear and a gold briquette embroidered in turquoises with verses from the Koran. Its supports were of silver gilt, beautifully chased, and profusely set with enameled and jeweled medallions.

04:24:11.402 --> 04:24:18.842
It had been taken from the Turkish camp before Vienna, and the standard of Mohammed had stood under it.

04:24:19.762 --> 04:24:39.822
And so, for a whole year he sought to accumulate the most exquisite specimens that he could find, of textile and embroidered work, getting the dainty deli muslims, finely wrought with gold-thread palimates, and stitched over with iridescent beetleswings.

04:24:39.822 --> 04:25:02.082
The dacca gauzes, that from their transparency are known in the East as woven air and running water and evening dew, strange figured cloths from Java, elaborate yellow Chinese hangings, books bound in tawny satins, or fair blue silks and wrought with fleur-de-lis, birds and images,

04:25:02.702 --> 04:25:19.702
veils of laces worked in Hungary Point, Sicilian brocades, and stiff Spanish velvets, Georgian work with its gilt coins and Japanese focuses, with their green-toned golds and their marvellously plumaged birds.

04:25:20.782 --> 04:25:29.282
He had a special passion also for ecclesiastical vestments, as indeed he had for everything connected with the service of the Church.

04:25:32.082 --> 04:25:57.222
In the long cedar chests that line the west gallery of his house he had stored away many rare and beautiful specimens of what is really the raiment of the Bride of Christ, who must wear purple and jewels and fine linen, that she may hide the pallid, macerated body that is worn by the suffering that she seeks for, and wounded by self-inflicted pain.

04:25:57.222 --> 04:26:15.202
He had a gorgeous cope of crimson silk and gold-thread damask, figured with a repeating pattern of gold pomegranates set in six-petalled formal blossoms, beyond which, on either side, was the pineapple device wrought in seed-pearls.

04:26:15.202 --> 04:26:28.702
The orphies were divided into panels representing scenes from the life of the Virgin, and the coronation of the Virgin was figured in coloured silks upon the hood. This was Italian work of the 15th century.

04:26:29.442 --> 04:26:44.182
Another cope was of green velvet, embroidered with heart-shaped groups of acanthus leaves, from which spread long-stemmed white blossoms, the details of which were picked out with silver thread and coloured crystals.

04:26:45.202 --> 04:26:49.942
The morse bore a seraph's head in gold thread-raised work.

04:26:51.122 --> 04:27:00.602
The orphies were woven in a diaper of red and gold silk, and were starred with medallions of many saints and martyrs, among whom was St. Sebastian.

04:27:00.602 --> 04:27:19.782
He had chosables, also, of amber-coloured silk and blue silk and gold-brickade, and yellow silk damask and cloth of gold, figured with representations of the Passion and Crucifixion of Christ, and embroidered with lions and peacocks and other emblems,

04:27:19.782 --> 04:27:35.962
dalmatics of white satin and pink silk damask, decorated with tulips and dolphins and fleur-de-lis, altar-frontals of crimson velvet and blue linen, and many corporals, chalice veils and sudaria.

04:27:35.962 --> 04:27:42.582
In the mystic offices to which these things were put, there was something that quickened his imagination.

04:27:42.962 --> 04:27:58.942
For these things, and everything that he collected in his lovely house, were to be to him means of forgetfulness, modes by which he could escape, for a season, from the fear that seemed to him at times to be almost too great to be borne.

04:27:59.842 --> 04:28:18.822
Upon the walls of the lonely locked room where he had spent so much of his boyhood, he had hung, with his own hands, the terrible portrait whose changing features showed him the real degradation of his life, and had draped the purple and gold-poll in front of it as a curtain.

04:28:18.822 --> 04:28:30.642
For weeks he would not go there, would forget the hideous painted thing, would get back his light heart, his wonderful joyousness, his passionate pleasure in mere existence.

04:28:31.422 --> 04:28:43.182
Then, suddenly, some night he would creep out of the house, go down to dreadful places near Blue Gate fields, and stay there, day after day, until he was driven away.

04:28:43.182 --> 04:29:04.442
On his return, he would sit in front of the picture, sometimes loathing it and himself, but filled, at other times, with that pride of rebellion that is half the fascination of sin, and smiling, with secret pleasure, at the misshapen shadow that had to bear the burden that should have been his own.

04:29:04.442 --> 04:29:20.142
After a few years he could not endure to be long out of England, and gave up the villa that he had shared at Truville with Lord Henry, as well as the little white walled-in house at Algiers where he had more than once spent his winter.

04:29:20.142 --> 04:29:35.402
He hated to be separated from the picture that was such a part of his life, and he was also afraid that during his absence someone might gain access to the room, in spite of the elaborate bolts and bars that he had caused to be placed upon the door.

04:29:35.402 --> 04:29:50.462
He was quite conscious that this would tell them nothing. It was true that the portrait still preserved, under all the foulness and ugliness of the face, its marked likeness to himself, but what could they learn from that?

04:29:50.462 --> 04:29:59.982
He would laugh at anyone who tried to taunt him. He had not painted it. What was it to him how vile and full of shame it looked, even if he told them, would they believe it?

04:30:01.222 --> 04:30:28.742
Yet he was afraid. Sometimes, when he was down at his great house in Nottinghamshire, entertaining the fashionable young men of his own rank, who were his chief companions, and astounding the country by the wanton luxury and gorgeous splendour of his mode of life, he would suddenly leave his guests and rush back to town to see that the door had not been tampered with, and that the picture was still there.

04:30:29.982 --> 04:30:42.142
What if it should be stolen? The mere thought made him cold with horror. Surely the world would know his secret then. Perhaps the world already suspected it.

04:30:42.902 --> 04:31:06.702
For, while he fascinated many, there were not a few who distrusted him. He was blackballed at a West End club of which his birth and social position fully entitled him to become a member, and on one occasion, when he was brought by a friend to the smoking-room of the Carlton, the Duke of Berwick and another gentleman got up in a marked manner and went out.

04:31:07.622 --> 04:31:24.562
Curious stories became current about him after he passed his twenty-fifth year. It was said that he had been seen brawling with foreign sailors in a low den in the distant parts of Whitechapel, and that he consorted with thieves and coiners and knew the mysteries of their trade.

04:31:25.282 --> 04:31:42.802
His extraordinary absences became notorious, and, when he used to reappear again in society, men would whisper to each other in corners, or pass him with a sneer, or look at him with cold, searching eyes, as if they were determined to discover his secret.

04:31:43.502 --> 04:32:08.442
Of such insolences and attempted slights he, of course, took no notice. And in the opinion of most people, his frank debonair manner, his charming boyish smile, and the infinite grace of that wonderful youth that seemed never to leave him, were in themselves a sufficient answer to the calumnies, for so they called them, that were circulated about him.

04:32:08.442 --> 04:32:16.562
It was remarked, however, that those who had been most intimate with him appeared, after a time, to shun him.

04:32:17.232 --> 04:32:39.602
Of all his friends, or so-called friends, Lord Henry Wooten was the only one who remained loyal to him. Women who had wildly adored him and, for his sake, had braved all social censure and set convention at defiance were seen to grow pallid with shame or horror if Dorian Gray entered the room.

04:32:40.342 --> 04:33:01.422
Yet these whispered scandals only lent him, in the eyes of many, his strange and dangerous charm. His great wealth was a certain element of security. Society, civilized society at least, is never very ready to believe anything to the detriment of those who are both rich and charming.

04:33:01.422 --> 04:33:13.642
It feels instinctively that manners are of more importance than morals, and the highest respectability is of less value in its opinion than the possession of a good chef.

04:33:14.522 --> 04:33:27.782
And, after all, it is a very poor consolation to be told that the man who has given one a bad dinner or poor wine is irreproachable in his private life.

04:33:28.432 --> 04:33:50.302
Even the cardinal virtues cannot atone for cold entrees, as Lord Henry remarked once, in a discussion on the subject. And there is possibly a good deal to be said for his view, for the canons of good society are, or should be, the same as the canons of art. Form is absolutely essential to it.

04:33:50.982 --> 04:34:14.282
It should have the dignity of a ceremony, as well as its unreality, and should combine the insincere character of a romantic play with the wit and beauty that makes such plays charming. Is insincerity such a terrible thing? I think not. It is merely a method by which we can multiply our personalities.

04:34:14.282 --> 04:34:35.502
Such, at any rate, was Dorian Gray's opinion. He used to wonder at the shallow psychology of those who conceive the ego in man as a thing simple, permanent, reliable, and of one essence. To him, man was a being with myriad lives and myriad sensations.

04:34:36.232 --> 04:34:56.482
A complex, multi-form creature that bore within itself strange legacies of thought and passion, and whose very flesh was tainted with the monstrous maladies of the dead. He loved to stroll through the gaunt portraits of those whose blood flowed in his veins.

04:34:56.482 --> 04:35:17.982
Here was Philip Herbert, described by Francis Osborne in his memoirs of the reigns of Queen Elizabeth and King James, as the one who was caressed by the court for his handsome face, which kept him not long company. Was it young Herbert's life that he sometimes led?

04:35:18.902 --> 04:35:40.482
Had some strange poisonous germ crept from body to body till it had reached his own? Was it some dim sense of that ruined grace that had made him so suddenly, and almost without cause, give utterance in Basil Hallward's studio to that mad prayer that had so changed his life?

04:35:40.482 --> 04:35:58.102
Here, in gold-embroidered red doublet, jeweled surcoat, and gilt-edged ruff in waistband stood Sir Anthony Sherrard, with his silver and black armour piled at his feet. What had this man's legacy been?

04:35:58.102 --> 04:36:11.502
Had the lover of Giovanna of Naples bequeathed him some inheritance of sin and shame? Were his own actions merely the dreams that the dead man had not dared to realise?

04:36:12.222 --> 04:36:30.302
Here, from the fading canvas, smiled Lady Elizabeth Evero, in her gauze hood, pearl-stomacher, and pink-slashed sleeves. A flower was in her right hand, and her left clasped an enamelled collar of white and damask roses.

04:36:31.282 --> 04:36:56.042
On a table by her side lay a mandolin and an apple. There were large green rosettes upon her little pointed shoes. He knew her life and the strange stories that were told about her lovers. Had he something of her temperament in him, those oval, heavy-lidded eyes that seemed to look curiously at him?

04:36:56.722 --> 04:37:10.182
What of George Willoughby, with his powdered hair and fantastic patches? How evil he looked! The face was saturnine and swarthy, and the sensual lips seemed to be twisted with disdain.

04:37:12.002 --> 04:37:24.402
Delicate lace ruffles fell over the lean yellow hands that were so overladen with rings. He had been a macaroni of the eighteenth century, and the friend, in his youth, of Lord Ferrars.

04:37:25.162 --> 04:37:45.582
What of the second Lord Chirard, the companion of the Prince Regent in his wildest days, and one of the witnesses at the secret marriage of Mrs. Fitzherbert? How proud and handsome he was, with his chestnut curls and insolent pose! What passions had he bequeathed!

04:37:45.582 --> 04:38:05.142
The world had looked upon him as infamous. He had led the orgies at Carlton House, the star of the garter glittered upon his breast. Beside him hung the portrait of his wife, a pallid, thin-lipped woman in black. Her blood also stirred within him. How curious it all seemed!

04:38:05.902 --> 04:38:20.562
Yet one had ancestors in literature, as well as in one's own race, near perhaps in type and temperament many of them, and certainly with an influence of which one was more absolutely conscious.

04:38:21.522 --> 04:38:49.582
There were times when it seemed to Dorian Gray that the whole of history was merely the record of his own life, not as he lived it in act and circumstance, but as his imagination had created it for him, as it had been in his brain and in his passions. He felt that he had known them all, those strange, terrible figures that had passed across the stage of the world, and made sin so marvellous and evil so full of wonder.

04:38:50.562 --> 04:38:56.962
It seemed to him that in some mysterious way their lives had been his own.

04:38:58.842 --> 04:39:26.922
The hero of a dangerous novel that had so influenced his life had himself had this curious fancy. In a chapter of the book he tells how, crowned with laurel, lest lightning might strike him, he had sat, as Tiberius, in a garden at Capri, reading the shameful books of Elefantis, while dwarves and peacocks strutted round him, and the flute player mocked the swinger of the censer.

04:39:26.922 --> 04:39:53.102
And, as Caligula, had corrals with the green-shirted jockeys in their stables, and supped in an ivory manger with a jewel-frontleted horse, and, as Domitian, had wandered through a corridor lined with marble mirrors, looking round with haggard eyes for the reflection of the dagger that was to end his days, and sick with that, on we, that tedium vitae,

04:39:53.102 --> 04:40:23.042
that comes on those to whom life denies nothing, and had peered through a clear emerald at the red shambles of the circus, and then, in a litter of pearl and purple drawn by silver-shod mules, had carried through the streets of pomegranate to a house of gold, and heard men cry on Nero Caesar as he passed by, and, as Elagabalus had painted his face with colours, and ply the distaff among the women,

04:40:23.102 --> 04:40:29.102
and brought the moon from Carthage, and given her in a mystic marriage to the sun.

04:40:30.182 --> 04:40:53.262
Over and over again Dorian used to read this fantastic chapter, and the chapter immediately following, in which the hero describes the curious tapestries that he had woven for him from Gustave Moreau's designs, and on which were pictured the awful and beautiful forms of those whom vice and blood and weariness had made monstrous or mad.

04:40:54.082 --> 04:40:59.862
Filippo, Duke of Milan, who slew his wife, and painted her lips with a scarlet poison.

04:41:00.642 --> 04:41:16.122
Pietro Barbie, the Venetian, known as Paul II, who sought in his vanity to assume the title of Formosus, and whose tiara, valued at 200,000 florins, was bought at the price of a terrible sin.

04:41:18.182 --> 04:41:25.742
Gianmaria Visconti, who used hounds to chase living men, and whose murdered body was covered with roses by a harlot who had loved him.

04:41:26.682 --> 04:41:34.402
The Borgia, on his white horse, with Fratricide riding beside him, and his mantle stained with the blood of Porotto.

04:41:35.402 --> 04:41:59.242
Pietro Ruario, the young Cardinal Archbishop of Florence, child and minion of Sixtus IV., whose beauty was equaled only by his debauchery, and who had received Leonora of Aragon in a pavilion of white and crimson silk, filled with nymphs and centaurs, and gilded a boy that he might serve her at the feast as Ganymede or Hylus.

04:42:00.622 --> 04:42:09.502
Ezelin, whose melancholy could be cured only by the spectacle of death, and who had a passion for red blood, as other men have for red wine.

04:42:10.342 --> 04:42:17.302
The son of the fiend, as was reported, and one who had cheated his father at Dice when gambling with him for his own soul.

04:42:18.002 --> 04:42:28.602
Gian Battista Sibo, who in mockery took the name of Innocent, and into whose torpid veins the blood of three lads was infused by a Jewish doctor.

04:42:29.202 --> 04:42:44.702
Sigismondo Malatesta, the lover of Isotta, and the lord of Rimini, whose effigy was burned at Rome as the enemy of God and manned, who straggled Polisena with a napkin, and gave poison to Geneva d'Este.

04:42:44.702 --> 04:42:52.342
In a cup of emerald, and in honor of a shameful passion, built a pagan church for Christian worship.

04:42:53.242 --> 04:43:07.102
Charles VI, who had so wildly adored his brother's wife that a leper had warned him of the insanity that was coming on him, and who could only be soothed by sericin cards painted with the images of love and death and madness.

04:43:07.862 --> 04:43:35.502
And in his trimmed jerkin and jeweled cap and acanthus-like curls, Grinfonetto Baglioni, who slew Astore with his bride, and Sigmonezzo with his page, and whose comeliness was such that, as he lay dying in the yellow piazza of Prarugia, those who had hated him could not choose but weep, and Atalanta, who had cursed him, blessed him.

04:43:36.142 --> 04:43:58.842
There was a horrible fascination in them all. He saw them at night, and they troubled his imagination in the day. The Renaissance knew of strange manners of poisoning, poisoning by a helmet and a lighted torch, by an embroidered glove and a jeweled fan, by a gilded palmander and by an amber chain.

04:43:59.542 --> 04:44:12.802
Dorian Gray had been poisoned by a book. There were moments when he looked on evil simply as a mode through which he could realize his own conception of the beautiful.

04:44:28.842 --> 04:44:31.222
Thank you for your attention.

04:45:02.226 --> 04:45:09.346
It was on the seventh day of November, the eve of his own thirty-second birthday, as

04:45:09.346 --> 04:45:15.846
he often remembered afterwards. He was walking home about eleven o'clock from Lord Henry's,

04:45:15.846 --> 04:45:22.346
where he had been dining, and was wrapped in heavy furs as the night was cold and foggy.

04:45:22.586 --> 04:45:27.566
At the corner of Grosvenor Square and south Audley Street a man passed him in the midst,

04:45:27.566 --> 04:45:34.426
walking very fast, and with the collar of his gray ulster turned up. He had a bag in his hand.

04:45:34.846 --> 04:45:41.226
He recognized him. It was Basil Hallward. A strange sense of fear, for which he could

04:45:41.226 --> 04:45:46.886
not account, came over him. He made no sign of recognition, and went on slowly in the

04:45:46.886 --> 04:45:51.366
direction of his own house. But Hallward had seen him.

04:45:52.766 --> 04:45:59.646
Dorian had heard him first stopping, and then hurrying after him. In a few moments his hand

04:45:59.646 --> 04:46:07.066
was on his arm. Dorian, what an extraordinary piece of luck! I have been waiting for you ever

04:46:07.066 --> 04:46:12.686
since nine o'clock in your library. Finally I took pity on your tired servant, and told him to go to

04:46:12.686 --> 04:46:18.766
bed as he let me out. I am off to Paris by midnight train, and I wanted particularly to see you before

04:46:18.766 --> 04:46:23.906
I left. I thought it was you, or rather your fur coat, as you passed me, but I wasn't quite sure.

04:46:24.046 --> 04:46:31.986
Didn't you recognize me? In this fog, my dear Basil, why, I can't even recognize Grosvenor Square.

04:46:32.566 --> 04:46:37.706
I believe my house is somewhere about here, but I don't feel at all certain about it. I am sorry

04:46:37.706 --> 04:46:43.746
you are going away, as I have not seen you for ages, but I suppose you will be back soon? No,

04:46:43.746 --> 04:46:49.646
I am going to be out of England for six months. I intend to take a studio in Paris, and shut myself

04:46:49.646 --> 04:46:55.566
up till I have finished a great picture I have in my head. However, it wasn't about myself I wanted

04:46:55.566 --> 04:47:01.466
to talk. Here we are at your door. Let me come in for a moment. I have something to say to you.

04:47:02.026 --> 04:47:08.926
I shall be charmed. But won't you miss your train? said Dorian Gray languidly, as he passed up the

04:47:08.926 --> 04:47:16.346
steps, and opened the door with his latch-key. The lamp-light struggled out through the fog,

04:47:16.426 --> 04:47:18.006
and Hallward looked at his watch.

04:47:19.066 --> 04:47:27.226
I have heaps of time, he answered. The train doesn't go till 12.15, and it is only just 11. In fact,

04:47:27.226 --> 04:47:32.426
I was on my way to the club to look for you when I met you. You see, I shan't have any delay about

04:47:32.426 --> 04:47:38.566
luggage, as I have sent on my heavy things. All I have with me is in this bag, and I can easily

04:47:38.566 --> 04:47:40.486
get to Victoria in twenty minutes.

04:47:41.266 --> 04:47:42.626
Dorian looked at him and smiled.

04:47:43.326 --> 04:47:48.646
What a way for a fashionable painter to travel! A gladstone bag and an ulster?

04:47:49.666 --> 04:47:55.046
Come in, or the fog will get into the house. And mind you don't talk about anything serious.

04:47:55.326 --> 04:47:58.526
Nothing is serious nowadays. At least nothing should be.

04:48:00.146 --> 04:48:03.926
Hallward shook his head as he entered, and followed Dorian into the library.

04:48:04.746 --> 04:48:11.826
There was a bright wood-fire blazing in the large open hearth. The lamps were lit, and an open Dutch

04:48:11.826 --> 04:48:18.926
silver spirit-case stood, with some siphons of soda-water and large cut glass tumblers on a little table.

04:48:20.706 --> 04:48:25.746
You see, your servant made me quite at home, Dorian. He gave me everything I wanted,

04:48:25.946 --> 04:48:31.366
including your best cigarettes. He is a most hospitable creature. I like him better than the

04:48:31.366 --> 04:48:35.246
Frenchman you used to have. What has become of the Frenchman, by the by?

04:48:36.966 --> 04:48:38.546
Dorian shrugged his shoulders.

04:48:39.766 --> 04:48:45.826
I believe he married Lady Ashton's maid, and has established her in Paris as an English dressmaker.

04:48:47.586 --> 04:48:53.766
Anglomani is very fashionable over there now, I hear. Seems silly of the French, doesn't it? But do you know,

04:48:53.966 --> 04:49:00.086
he was not at all a bad servant. I never liked him, but I doth to complain about. One often imagines

04:49:00.086 --> 04:49:05.746
things that are quite absurd. He was really very devoted to me, and seemed quite sorry when he went away.

04:49:05.986 --> 04:49:12.686
Have another brandy and soda? Or would you like a hock and seltzer? I always take hock and seltzer myself.

04:49:13.046 --> 04:49:15.026
There is sure to be some in the next room.

04:49:15.866 --> 04:49:21.886
Thanks, I won't have anything more, said Hallward, taking his cap and coat off, and throwing them on the bag

04:49:21.886 --> 04:49:29.266
that he had placed in the corner. And now, my dear fellow, I want to speak to you seriously. Don't frown like that.

04:49:29.266 --> 04:49:32.266
You make it so much more difficult for me.

04:49:32.646 --> 04:49:39.966
What is it all about? cried Dorian, in his petulant way, flinging himself down on the sofa.

04:49:40.606 --> 04:49:46.326
I hope it is not about myself. I am tired of myself tonight. I should like to be somebody else.

04:49:46.826 --> 04:49:56.426
It is about yourself, answered Hallward in his grave deep voice, and I must say it to you. I shall only keep you half an hour.

04:49:57.986 --> 04:49:59.946
Dorian sighed and lit a cigarette.

04:50:00.406 --> 04:50:03.126
Half an hour? he murmured.

04:50:04.466 --> 04:50:09.966
It is not much to ask of you, Dorian, and it is entirely for your own sake that I am speaking.

04:50:10.706 --> 04:50:19.466
I think it right that you should know that the most dreadful things are being said about you in London, things that I could hardly repeat to you.

04:50:19.466 --> 04:50:29.466
I don't wish to know anything about them. I love scandals about other people, but scandals about myself don't interest me. They have not got the charm of novelty.

04:50:30.406 --> 04:50:39.766
They must interest you, Dorian. Every gentleman is interested in his good name. You don't want people to talk of you as something vile and degraded.

04:50:40.006 --> 04:50:46.446
Of course you have your position and your wealth and all that kind of thing, but position and wealth are not everything.

04:50:47.126 --> 04:50:52.146
Mind you, I don't believe these rumors at all. At least I can't believe them when I see you.

04:50:54.026 --> 04:51:01.266
Sin is a thing that writes itself across a man's face. It cannot be concealed.

04:51:01.946 --> 04:51:06.786
People talk of secret vices. There are no such things as secret vices.

04:51:07.346 --> 04:51:15.266
If a wretched man has a vice, it shows itself in the lines of his mouth, the droop of his eyelids, the moulding of his hands even.

04:51:15.886 --> 04:51:21.546
Somebody, I won't mention his name, but you know him, came to me last year to have his portrait done.

04:51:21.886 --> 04:51:31.286
I had never seen him before and had never heard anything about him at the time, though I had heard a good deal since. He offered an extravagant price. I refused him.

04:51:32.106 --> 04:51:40.966
There was something in the shape of his fingers that I hated. I now know that I was quite right in what I fancied about him. His life is dreadful.

04:51:42.126 --> 04:51:51.986
But you, Dorian, with your pure, bright, innocent face and your marvellous, untroubled youth, I can't believe anything against you.

04:51:52.026 --> 04:52:04.306
And yet I see you very seldom, and you never come down to the studio now, and when I am away from you and I hear all these hideous things that people are whispering about you, I don't know what to say.

04:52:04.886 --> 04:52:11.806
Why is it, Dorian, that a man like the Duke of Berwick leaves the room of a club when you enter it?

04:52:12.386 --> 04:52:17.766
Why is it that so many gentlemen in London will neither go to your house nor invite you to theirs?

04:52:18.686 --> 04:52:22.646
You used to be a friend of Lord Cardor. I met him at dinner last week.

04:52:23.106 --> 04:52:27.366
Your name happened to come up in conversation in connection with the miniatures you have

04:52:28.086 --> 04:52:29.326
at the Dudley.

04:52:30.266 --> 04:52:35.306
Cardor curled his lip and said that you might have the most artistic taste,

04:52:35.866 --> 04:52:41.426
but that you were a man whom no pure-minded girl should be allowed to know,

04:52:42.186 --> 04:52:45.906
and whom no chaste woman would sit in the same room with.

04:52:46.406 --> 04:52:49.986
I reminded him that I was a friend of yours and asked him what he meant. He told me.

04:52:50.526 --> 04:52:53.886
He told me right out before everybody. It was horrible.

04:52:54.566 --> 04:52:57.426
Why is your friendship so fateful to young men?

04:52:58.326 --> 04:53:02.466
There was that Richard Boy in the guards who committed suicide. You were his great friend.

04:53:03.646 --> 04:53:08.146
There was Sir Henry Ashton who had to leave England with a tarnished name.

04:53:08.486 --> 04:53:12.766
You and he were inseparable. What about Adrian Singleton and his dreadful end?

04:53:13.346 --> 04:53:16.226
What about Lord Kent's only son and his career?

04:53:17.226 --> 04:53:22.746
I met his father yesterday in St. James Street. He seemed broken with shame and sorrow.

04:53:23.466 --> 04:53:28.506
What about the young Duke of Perth? What sort of life has he got now?

04:53:29.246 --> 04:53:35.646
What gentleman would associate with him, Dorian? Dorian, your reputation is infamous.

04:53:36.206 --> 04:53:39.906
I know you and Harry are great friends. I say nothing about that now, but surely

04:53:40.506 --> 04:53:44.026
you need not have made his sister's name a byword.

04:53:45.346 --> 04:53:50.326
When you met Lady Gwendolyn not a breath of scandal had ever touched her.

04:53:50.326 --> 04:53:55.126
Is there a single decent woman in London now who would drive with her in the park

04:53:55.126 --> 04:53:58.306
while even her children are not allowed to live with her?

04:53:58.746 --> 04:54:04.826
Then there are other stories. Stories that you have been seen creeping at dawn out of dreadful

04:54:04.826 --> 04:54:11.486
houses and slinking in disguise into the foulest dens in London. Are they true? Can they be true?

04:54:12.606 --> 04:54:17.186
When I first heard them I laughed. I hear them now and they make me shudder.

04:54:17.186 --> 04:54:20.906
What about your country house and the life that is led there? Dorian,

04:54:21.466 --> 04:54:26.586
you don't know what is said about you. I won't tell you that I don't want to preach to you.

04:54:26.866 --> 04:54:30.726
I remember Harry saying once that every man who turned himself into an amateur

04:54:30.726 --> 04:54:37.426
curate for the moment always said that and then broke his word. I do want to preach to you.

04:54:38.386 --> 04:54:42.646
I want you to lead such a life as will make the world respect you.

04:54:43.126 --> 04:54:45.986
I want you to have a clean name and a fair record.

04:54:47.186 --> 04:54:51.666
I want you to get rid of the dreadful people you associate with. Don't shrug your shoulders

04:54:51.666 --> 04:55:00.806
like that. Don't be so indifferent. You have a wonderful influence. Let it be for good, not for

04:55:00.806 --> 04:55:07.686
evil. They say that you corrupt every one whom you become intimate with and that it is quite

04:55:07.686 --> 04:55:14.086
sufficient for you to enter a house for shame of some kind to follow after you. I don't know

04:55:14.086 --> 04:55:19.226
whether it is so or not. How should I know? But it is said of you.

04:55:20.266 --> 04:55:23.366
I am told things that it seems impossible to doubt.

04:55:24.366 --> 04:55:31.106
Lord Gloucester was one of my greatest friends at Oxford. He showed me a letter that his wife had

04:55:31.106 --> 04:55:36.646
written to him when she was dying alone in her villa at Menton. Your name was implicated in

04:55:36.646 --> 04:55:42.206
the most terrible confession I ever read. I told him that it was absurd that I knew you thoroughly

04:55:42.206 --> 04:55:50.586
and that you were incapable of anything of the kind. Know you. I wonder, do I know you?

04:55:50.746 --> 04:55:54.366
Before I could answer that, I should have to see your soul.

04:55:55.666 --> 04:56:03.646
To see my soul? muttered Dorian Gray, starting up from the sofa and turning almost white from fear.

04:56:05.126 --> 04:56:11.746
Yes, answered Hallward gravely, and with infinite sorrow in his voice. To see your soul.

04:56:12.206 --> 04:56:18.106
But only God can do that. A bitter laugh of mockery broke from the lips of the younger man.

04:56:19.066 --> 04:56:24.686
You shall see it yourself to-night, he cried, seizing a lamp from the table. Come,

04:56:25.206 --> 04:56:32.086
it is your own handiwork. Why shouldn't you look at it? You can tell the world all about it afterwards

04:56:32.086 --> 04:56:37.406
if you choose. Nobody would believe you. If they did believe you, they'd like me all the better for

04:56:37.406 --> 04:56:43.186
it. I know the age better than you do, though you will prate about it so tediously. Come,

04:56:43.486 --> 04:56:50.206
I tell you. You've chatted enough about corruption. Now you shall look at it face to face.

04:56:50.866 --> 04:56:56.306
There was the madness of pride in every word he uttered. He stamped his foot upon the ground in

04:56:56.306 --> 04:57:02.886
his boyish, insolent manner. He felt a terrible joy the thought that some one else was to share

04:57:02.886 --> 04:57:09.046
his secret, and that the man who had painted the portrait that was the origin of all his shame was

04:57:09.046 --> 04:57:14.206
to be burdened for the rest of his life with the hideous memory of what he had done.

04:57:16.826 --> 04:57:22.386
Yes, he continued, coming closer to him and looking steadfastly into his stern eyes.

04:57:23.266 --> 04:57:30.406
I will show you my soul. You shall see the thing that you fancy only God can see.

04:57:31.806 --> 04:57:33.366
All words started back.

04:57:33.826 --> 04:57:39.126
That is blasphemy, Dorian, he cried. You must not say things like that. They are horrible,

04:57:39.266 --> 04:57:40.826
and they don't mean anything.

04:57:41.646 --> 04:57:48.166
You don't think so? He laughed again. I know so. As for what I have said to you tonight,

04:57:48.266 --> 04:57:53.106
I said it for your own good. You know I have been always devoted to you.

04:57:53.966 --> 04:57:57.006
Don't touch me. Finish what you have to say.

04:57:58.746 --> 04:58:03.686
A twisted flash of pain shot across Hollywood's face. He paused for a moment,

04:58:04.286 --> 04:58:09.866
and a wild feeling of pity came over him. After all, what right had he to pry into the life of

04:58:09.866 --> 04:58:16.686
Dorian Gray? If he had done a tithe of what was rumoured about him, how much he must have suffered.

04:58:17.626 --> 04:58:21.586
Then he straightened himself up and walked over to the fireplace and stood there,

04:58:21.646 --> 04:58:26.606
looking at the burning logs with their frost-like ashes and their throbbing cores of flame.

04:58:27.286 --> 04:58:32.186
I am waiting, Basil, said the young man in a hard, clear voice.

04:58:33.406 --> 04:58:34.226
He turned round.

04:58:34.766 --> 04:58:39.606
What I have to say is this, he cried. You must give me some answer to these horrible

04:58:39.606 --> 04:58:44.986
charges that are made against you. If you tell me that they are absolutely untrue from beginning

04:58:44.986 --> 04:58:51.946
to end, I will believe you. Deny them, Dorian, deny them. Can't you see what I am going through?

04:58:52.006 --> 04:58:54.246
My God, don't tell me that you are infamous.

04:58:55.686 --> 04:58:59.506
Dorian Gray smiled. There was a curl of contempt in his lips.

04:58:59.946 --> 04:59:06.126
Come upstairs, Basil, he said quietly. I keep a diary of my life from day to day,

04:59:06.346 --> 04:59:12.466
and it never leaves the room in which it is written. I will show it to you if you come with me.

04:59:14.126 --> 04:59:19.906
I will come with you, Dorian, if you wish it. I see I have missed my train. That makes no

04:59:19.906 --> 04:59:26.166
I can go tomorrow. But don't ask me to read anything tonight. All I want is a plain answer

04:59:26.166 --> 04:59:32.706
to my question. That will be given to you upstairs. I could not give it here.

04:59:33.246 --> 04:59:36.106
You won't have to read long. Don't keep me waiting.

05:00:00.592 --> 05:00:09.422
The Picture of Dorian Gray by Oscar Wilde.

05:00:20.532 --> 05:00:26.422
He passed out of the room and began the ascent, Basil Hallward following close behind.

05:00:27.022 --> 05:00:33.962
They walked softly, as men instinctively do at night. The lamp cast fantastic shadows on the wall

05:00:33.962 --> 05:00:40.762
and staircase. A rising wind made some of the windows rattle. When they reached the top landing,

05:00:41.142 --> 05:00:47.322
Dorian set the lamp down on the floor, and, taking out the key, turned it in the lock.

05:00:48.122 --> 05:00:52.562
"'You insist on knowing, Basil?' he asked in a low voice.

05:00:54.862 --> 05:01:01.322
"'Yes, I am delighted,' he murmured, smiling. Then he added, somewhat bitterly,

05:01:02.242 --> 05:01:08.582
"'You are the one man in the world who is entitled to know everything about me. You have had more to

05:01:08.582 --> 05:01:13.842
do with my life than you think.' And, taking up the lamp, he opened the door and went in.

05:01:14.442 --> 05:01:21.202
A cold current of air passed them, and the light shot up for a moment in a flame of murky orange.

05:01:22.202 --> 05:01:27.862
He shuddered. "'Shut the door behind you,' he said as he placed the lamp on the table.

05:01:29.162 --> 05:01:34.462
Hallward glanced around him with a puzzled expression. The room looked as if it had not

05:01:34.462 --> 05:01:42.202
been lived in for years. A faded Flemish tapestry, a curtained picture, an old Italian casson,

05:01:42.202 --> 05:01:47.762
and an almost empty bookcase—that was all that it seemed to contain, besides a chair and table.

05:01:48.342 --> 05:01:53.022
As Dorian Gray was lighting a half-burned candle that was standing on the mantel shelf,

05:01:53.682 --> 05:02:00.342
he saw that the whole place was covered with dust, and that the carpet was in holes. A mouse

05:02:00.342 --> 05:02:05.042
round scuffling behind the wainscotting. There was a damp odour of mildew.

05:02:05.602 --> 05:02:10.122
"'So you think that it is only God who sees the soul, Basil?'

05:02:10.122 --> 05:02:12.572
Draw that curtain back, and you will see mine."

05:02:13.902 --> 05:02:17.142
The voice that spoke was cold and cruel.

05:02:18.142 --> 05:02:23.762
"'You are mad, Dorian, or playing a part,' muttered Hallward, frowning.

05:02:23.922 --> 05:02:24.572
"'You won't?'

05:02:25.462 --> 05:02:31.642
"'Then I must do it myself,' said the young man, and he tore the curtain from its rod

05:02:31.642 --> 05:02:38.142
and flung it on the ground. An exclamation of horror broke from Hallward's lips as he

05:02:38.142 --> 05:02:44.362
saw in the dim light the hideous thing on the canvas leering at him. There was something in

05:02:44.362 --> 05:02:51.902
its expression that filled him with disgust and loathing. Good heavens, it was Dorian Gray's own

05:02:51.902 --> 05:02:58.802
face that he was looking at. The horror, whatever it was, had not yet entirely marred that marvellous

05:02:58.802 --> 05:03:04.482
beauty. There was still some gold in the thinning hair and some scarlet on the sensual lips.

05:03:05.262 --> 05:03:10.302
The sodden eyes had kept something of the loveliness of their blue. The noble curves

05:03:10.302 --> 05:03:17.262
had not yet passed entirely from chiselled nostrils and from plastic throat. Yes,

05:03:17.262 --> 05:03:22.522
it was Dorian himself, but who had done it? He seemed to recognise his own brushwork,

05:03:22.542 --> 05:03:27.842
and the frame was his own design. The idea was monstrous, yet he felt afraid.

05:03:28.482 --> 05:03:31.322
He seized the lighted candle and held it to the picture.

05:03:32.002 --> 05:03:38.782
In the left-hand corner was his own name, traced in long letters of bright vermilion.

05:03:40.462 --> 05:03:47.002
It was some foul parody, some infamous, ignobled satire. He had never done that.

05:03:47.782 --> 05:03:54.122
Still, it was his own picture. He knew it, and he felt as if his blood had changed from fire to

05:03:54.122 --> 05:04:01.762
sluggish ice in a moment. His own picture! What did it mean? Why had it altered?

05:04:02.342 --> 05:04:05.162
He turned and looked at Dorian with the eyes of a sick man.

05:04:06.182 --> 05:04:12.122
His mouth twitched, and his parched tongue seemed unable to articulate. He passed his

05:04:12.122 --> 05:04:18.522
hand across his forehead. It was dank with clammy sweat. The young man was leaning against the

05:04:18.522 --> 05:04:22.842
mantel-shelf, watching him with that strange expression that is on the faces of those who

05:04:22.842 --> 05:04:28.562
are absorbed in a play when a great artist is acting. There was neither real sorrow in it,

05:04:28.582 --> 05:04:34.802
nor real joy. There was simply the passion of the spectator, with perhaps a flicker of triumph in

05:04:34.802 --> 05:04:40.882
the eyes. He had taken the flower out of his coat and was smelling it, or pretending to do so.

05:04:42.102 --> 05:04:49.382
What does this mean? cried Hallward, at last. His own voice sounded shrill and curious in his ears.

05:04:51.322 --> 05:04:54.682
"'Years ago, when I was a boy,' said Dorian Gray,

05:04:54.682 --> 05:05:00.242
"'you met me, devoted yourself to me, flattered me, and taught me to be vain of my good looks.

05:05:01.222 --> 05:05:06.242
One day you introduced me to a friend of yours, who explained to me the wonder of youth, and

05:05:06.242 --> 05:05:12.082
you finished a portrait of me that revealed to me the wonder of beauty. In a mad moment,

05:05:12.362 --> 05:05:19.142
that I don't know even now whether I regret or not, I made a wish. Perhaps you would call it

05:05:20.122 --> 05:05:27.182
prayer.' I remember it. Oh, how well I remember it. No, the thing is impossible. The room is damp.

05:05:27.262 --> 05:05:32.922
The mildew has gotten into the canvas. The paints I had used had some wretched mineral poison in them.

05:05:32.922 --> 05:05:34.822
I tell you, the thing is impossible.'

05:05:35.422 --> 05:05:42.642
"'What is impossible?' murmured the young man, going over to the window and leaning his forehead

05:05:42.642 --> 05:05:45.222
against the cold, mist-stained glass.

05:05:46.302 --> 05:05:52.602
"'You told me you destroyed it. I was wrong. It has destroyed me. I don't believe it is my picture.

05:05:52.842 --> 05:05:56.282
Can't you see your romance in it?' said Dorian bitterly.

05:05:56.802 --> 05:06:04.842
"'My romance, as you call it, as you called it. There was nothing evil in it, nothing shameful.

05:06:04.982 --> 05:06:12.102
This is the face of a satyr. It is the face of my soul. God, what a thing I must have worshipped.

05:06:12.102 --> 05:06:17.262
This has the eyes of a devil. Each of this has heaven and hell in him, Basil,'

05:06:17.262 --> 05:06:19.302
cried Dorian with a gesture of despair.

05:06:20.662 --> 05:06:23.542
Hallward turned again to the portrait and gazed at it.

05:06:23.982 --> 05:06:26.602
"'My God, if it is true,' he exclaimed,

05:06:26.602 --> 05:06:32.282
"'and this is what you have done with your life. Why, you must be worse even than those who talk

05:06:32.282 --> 05:06:38.462
against you fancy you to be.' He held the light up again to the canvas and examined it. The surface

05:06:38.462 --> 05:06:45.202
seemed to be quite undisturbed, and as he had left it, it was from within, apparently,

05:06:45.222 --> 05:06:51.762
that the foulness and horror had come. Through some strange quickening of inner life the

05:06:51.762 --> 05:06:57.582
leprosies of sin were slowly eating the thing away. The rotting of a corpse in a watery grave

05:06:57.582 --> 05:07:03.062
was not so fearful. His hand shook, and the candle fell from its socket on the floor and

05:07:03.642 --> 05:07:09.202
sputtering. He placed his foot on it and put it out. Then he flung himself into the rickety

05:07:09.202 --> 05:07:12.942
chair that was standing by the table and buried his face in his hands.

05:07:14.142 --> 05:07:17.142
Good God, Dorian, what an awful lesson!'

05:07:18.402 --> 05:07:22.962
There was no answer, but he could hear the young man sobbing at the window.

05:07:23.802 --> 05:07:30.282
"'Pray, Dorian, pray,' he murmured. What is it that one taught to say in one's boyhood?

05:07:30.282 --> 05:07:35.622
Lead us not into temptation, forgive us our sins, wash away our inequities. Let us say that

05:07:35.622 --> 05:07:40.802
together. The prayers of your pride has been answered. The prayer of your repentance will

05:07:40.802 --> 05:07:45.842
be answered also. I worshiped you too much. I am punished for it. You worshiped yourself too much.

05:07:45.882 --> 05:07:53.722
We are both punished.' Dorian Gray turned slowly around and looked at him with tear-dimmed eyes.

05:07:55.022 --> 05:07:58.402
"'It is too late, Basil,' he murmured.

05:07:59.122 --> 05:08:04.002
"'It is never too late, Dorian. Let us kneel down and try, if we can remember a prayer.

05:08:04.642 --> 05:08:09.462
Isn't there a verse somewhere, though our sins be a scarlet, yet I will make them as white as snow?'

05:08:09.462 --> 05:08:15.742
Those words mean nothing to me now. Hush, don't say that. You've done enough evil in your life.

05:08:15.762 --> 05:08:22.822
My God, don't you see that accursed thing leering at us?' Dorian Gray glanced at the picture, and

05:08:22.822 --> 05:08:29.722
an uncontrollable feeling of hatred for Basil Hallward came over him. The mad passions of a

05:08:29.722 --> 05:08:35.082
hunted animal stirred within him, and he loathed the man who was seated at the table more than he

05:08:35.082 --> 05:08:42.182
had ever loathed anything in his whole life. He glanced wildly around. Something glimmered

05:08:42.182 --> 05:08:46.682
on the top of the painted chest that faced him. His eye fell on it. He knew what it was.

05:08:47.482 --> 05:08:51.422
It was a knife that he had brought up some days before to cut a piece of cord,

05:08:51.422 --> 05:08:56.522
and had forgotten to take it away with him. He moved slowly towards it, passing Hallward as he

05:08:56.522 --> 05:09:01.962
did so. As soon as he got behind him, he seized it and turned round. Hallward moved in his chair

05:09:01.962 --> 05:09:07.462
as if he was going to rise. He rushed at him and dug the knife into the great vein that is behind

05:09:07.462 --> 05:09:13.662
the ear, crushing the man's head down to the table and stabbing again and again. There was a stifled

05:09:13.662 --> 05:09:20.922
groan, and the horrible sound of someone choking with blood. The outstretched arm shut up convulsively

05:09:20.922 --> 05:09:26.922
three times, waving grotesque stiff-fingered hands in the air. He stabbed it once more,

05:09:27.262 --> 05:09:33.942
but the man did not move. Something began to trickle on the floor. He waited for a moment,

05:09:34.182 --> 05:09:39.922
still pressing the head down. Then he threw the knife on the table and listened.

05:09:41.842 --> 05:09:47.242
He could hear nothing but the drip-drip on the threadbare carpet.

05:09:48.102 --> 05:09:55.342
He opened the door and went out onto the landing. The house was quite quiet. No one was stirring.

05:09:56.542 --> 05:10:00.922
He took out the key and returned to the room, locking himself in as he did so.

05:10:02.002 --> 05:10:06.062
The thing was still seated in the chair, straining over the table with bowed head,

05:10:06.562 --> 05:10:13.182
and humped back in long fantastic arms. Had it not been for the red jagged tear in the neck and

05:10:13.182 --> 05:10:20.642
clotted black pool that slowly widened on the table, one would have said that the man was simply

05:10:20.642 --> 05:10:31.002
asleep. How quickly had it all been done! He felt strangely calm and, walking over to the window,

05:10:31.262 --> 05:10:38.622
opened it and stepped out onto the balcony. The wind had blown the fog away and the sky was like

05:10:38.622 --> 05:10:45.762
monstrous peacock's tail, starred with myriads of golden eyes. He looked down and saw the policeman

05:10:45.762 --> 05:10:50.102
going his rounds and flashing a bull's-eye lantern on the doors of the silent houses.

05:10:51.302 --> 05:10:58.082
The crimson spot of a prowling handsome gleamed at the corner and then vanished. A woman in a

05:10:58.082 --> 05:11:03.622
ragged shawl was creeping around by the railing, staggering as she went. Now and then she stopped

05:11:03.622 --> 05:11:10.782
and peered back. Once again she began to sing in a hoarse voice. The policeman strolled over

05:11:10.782 --> 05:11:16.402
and said something to her as she stumbled away laughing. A bitter blast swept across the square.

05:11:16.922 --> 05:11:23.582
The gas lamps flickered and became blue, and the leafless trees shook their black iron branches

05:11:23.582 --> 05:11:31.122
as if in pain. He shivered and went back, closing the window behind him. He passed to the door,

05:11:31.122 --> 05:11:37.102
turned the key, and opened it. He did not even glance at the murdered man. He felt that the

05:11:37.102 --> 05:11:43.902
secret of the whole thing was not to realize the situation. The friend who had painted the fatal

05:11:43.902 --> 05:11:51.202
portrait, the portrait to which all his misery had been due, had gone out of his life. That was

05:11:51.202 --> 05:11:57.142
enough. Then he remembered the lamp. It was a rather curious one of Moorish

05:11:57.142 --> 05:12:03.922
workmanship made of dull silver inlaid with arabesques of burnished steel. Perhaps it might

05:12:03.922 --> 05:12:08.302
be missed by a servant and questions would be asked. He turned back and took it from the table.

05:12:09.442 --> 05:12:18.462
Still the man was. How horribly white the long hands looked. He was like a dreadful wax image.

05:12:19.182 --> 05:12:24.782
He locked the door behind him and crept quietly downstairs. The woodwork creaked and seemed to

05:12:24.782 --> 05:12:31.682
fly out as if in pain. He stopped several times and waited. No, everything was still.

05:12:32.542 --> 05:12:34.762
It was merely the sound of his own footsteps.

05:12:36.922 --> 05:12:42.382
When he reached the library he saw the bag and coat in the corner. They must be hidden away

05:12:42.382 --> 05:12:46.682
somewhere. He unlocked a secret press that was in the wainscotting and put them into it.

05:12:46.882 --> 05:12:52.642
He could easily burn them afterwards. Then he pulled out his watch. It was twenty minutes to two.

05:12:53.382 --> 05:13:01.322
He sat down and began to think. Every year, every month almost, men were strangled in England for

05:13:01.322 --> 05:13:08.122
what he had done. There had been a madness of murder in the air. Some red star had come too

05:13:08.122 --> 05:13:16.402
close to the earth. Evidence? What evidence was there against him? Basil Hallward had left the

05:13:16.402 --> 05:13:22.342
house at eleven. No one had seen him come in again. Most of the servants were at Selby Royal.

05:13:22.622 --> 05:13:30.622
His valet had gone to bed. Paris? Yes, it was to Paris that Basil had gone by the midnight train,

05:13:30.642 --> 05:13:37.642
as he had intended. With his curious reserved habits it would be months before any suspicions

05:13:37.642 --> 05:13:45.182
would be aroused. Months. Everything could be destroyed long before then. A sudden thought

05:13:45.182 --> 05:13:52.362
struck him. He put on his fur coat and hat and went out into the hall. There he paused, hearing

05:13:52.362 --> 05:13:57.742
the slow heavy tread of the policeman outside on the pavement and seeing the flash of the lantern

05:13:57.742 --> 05:14:04.782
reflected in the window. He waited, holding his breath. After a few moments he opened the front

05:14:04.782 --> 05:14:09.982
door and slipped out, shutting it very gently behind him. Then he began ringing the bell.

05:14:10.642 --> 05:14:15.102
It was about ten minutes, his valet appeared, half-dressed and looking very drowsy.

05:14:16.082 --> 05:14:19.862
I am sorry to have had to wake you up, Francis, he said, stepping in.

05:14:20.422 --> 05:14:22.922
But I had forgotten my latchkey. What time is it?

05:14:23.662 --> 05:14:27.962
Five minutes past two, sir, answered the man, looking at the clock and yawning.

05:14:28.822 --> 05:14:35.442
Five minutes past two! How horribly late! You must wake me up at nine tomorrow. I have some work to do.

05:14:36.082 --> 05:14:41.742
All right, sir. Did anyone call this evening? Mr. Hallward, sir, he stayed here till eleven.

05:14:42.202 --> 05:14:48.082
Then he went away to catch his train. Oh, I am sorry I didn't see him. Did he leave any message?

05:14:48.702 --> 05:14:51.242
No, sir, except that he would write to you.

05:14:51.802 --> 05:14:55.522
That will do, Francis. Don't forget to call me at nine tomorrow.

05:14:56.042 --> 05:14:59.662
No, sir, the man shabbled down the passage in his slippers.

05:15:00.882 --> 05:15:05.622
Dorian Gray threw his hat and coat upon the yellow marble table and passed into the library.

05:15:06.322 --> 05:15:10.362
He walked up and down the room for a quarter of an hour, biting his lip and thinking.

05:15:11.862 --> 05:15:17.122
Then he took the blue book down from one of the shelves and began to turn over the leaves.

05:15:17.842 --> 05:15:27.762
Alan Campbell, 152 Hurtford Street, Mayfair. Yes, that was the man he wanted.

05:16:09.053 --> 05:16:14.693
At nine o'clock the next morning his servant came in with a cup of chocolate on a tray,

05:16:15.133 --> 05:16:20.253
and opened the shutters. Dorian was sleeping quite peacefully, lying on his right side,

05:16:20.313 --> 05:16:25.613
with one hand underneath his cheek. He looked like a boy who had been tired out with play

05:16:25.613 --> 05:16:32.513
or study. The man had to touch him twice on the shoulder before he awoke, and as he opened

05:16:32.513 --> 05:16:39.053
his eyes a faint smile passed across his lips, as though he had been having some delightful

05:16:39.053 --> 05:16:45.653
dream, yet he had not dreamed at all. His night had been untroubled by any images of

05:16:45.653 --> 05:16:52.773
pleasure or of pain, but youth smiles without any reason. It is one of its chiefest charms.

05:16:53.713 --> 05:17:01.053
He turned round, and leaning on his elbow, began to drink his chocolate. The mellow November

05:17:01.053 --> 05:17:07.473
sun was streaming into the room. The sky was bright blue, and there was a genial warmth

05:17:07.473 --> 05:17:11.333
in the air. It was almost like a morning in May.

05:17:13.033 --> 05:17:18.733
Gradually the events of the preceding night crept with a silent, blood-stained feet into

05:17:18.733 --> 05:17:24.913
his brain, and reconstructed themselves there with terrible distinctness. He winced at the

05:17:24.913 --> 05:17:30.913
memory of all that he had suffered, and for a moment the same curious feeling of loathing

05:17:30.913 --> 05:17:36.653
for Basil Hallward, that had made him kill him as he sat in the chair, came back to him,

05:17:36.933 --> 05:17:42.873
and he grew cold with passion. The dead man was still sitting there, too, and in the sunlight

05:17:42.873 --> 05:17:49.633
now. How horrible that was! Such hideous things were for the darkness, not for the day.

05:17:50.653 --> 05:17:56.053
He felt that if he brooded on what he had gone through he would sicken or grow mad.

05:17:56.053 --> 05:18:01.373
There were sins whose fascination was more in the memory than in the doing of them, strange

05:18:01.373 --> 05:18:07.053
triumphs that gratified the pride more than the passions, and gave to the intellect a

05:18:07.053 --> 05:18:12.293
quickened sense of joy greater than any joy they brought or could ever bring to the senses.

05:18:14.553 --> 05:18:21.433
But this was not one of them. It was a thing to be driven out of the mind, to be drugged

05:18:21.433 --> 05:18:25.733
with poppies, to be strangled, lest it might strangle one itself.

05:18:26.573 --> 05:18:32.293
He passed his hand across his forehead, and then got up hastily, and dressed himself with

05:18:32.293 --> 05:18:37.313
even more than his usual attention, giving a good deal of care to the selection of his

05:18:37.313 --> 05:18:43.993
neck-tie and scarf-pin, and had changed his rings more than once. He spent a long time

05:18:43.993 --> 05:18:50.553
over breakfast, tasting the various dishes, talking to his valid about some new liveries

05:18:50.553 --> 05:18:55.733
that he was thinking of getting made for the servants at Celebi, and going through his

05:18:55.733 --> 05:19:02.513
correspondence. Over some of the letters he smiled. Three of them bored him. One he read

05:19:02.513 --> 05:19:07.973
several times over, and then tore it up with a slight look of annoyance in his face. That

05:19:07.973 --> 05:19:12.633
awful thing! A woman's memory, as Lord Henry had once said.

05:19:13.733 --> 05:19:21.313
When he drank his coffee he sat down at the table, and wrote two letters. One he put in

05:19:21.313 --> 05:19:24.393
his pocket, the other he handed to the valet.

05:19:25.233 --> 05:19:31.553
Take this round to 152 Hurtford Street, Francis, and if Mr. Campbell is out of town, get his

05:19:31.553 --> 05:19:37.653
address. As soon as he was alone he lit a cigarette, and began sketching upon a piece

05:19:37.653 --> 05:19:44.573
of paper, drawing flowers and bits of architecture first, and then faces. Suddenly he remarked

05:19:44.573 --> 05:19:49.733
that every face that he drew seemed to have an extraordinary likeness to Basil Hallward.

05:19:50.153 --> 05:19:55.213
He frowned, and getting up, went over to the bookcase, and took out a volume at Hazard.

05:19:55.733 --> 05:20:01.713
He was determined that he would not think about what had happened, till it became absolutely

05:20:02.033 --> 05:20:03.253
necessary to do so.

05:20:04.413 --> 05:20:10.573
When he stretched himself on the sofa he looked at the title page of the book. It was gautier

05:20:10.573 --> 05:20:22.853
Émaux à calmes. The binding was citrine-green leather with a design of gilt trellis work

05:20:22.853 --> 05:20:30.093
and dotted pomegranates. It had been given to him by Adrian Singleton. As he turned over

05:20:30.093 --> 05:20:36.593
the pages his eye fell on the poem about the hand of La Sénère, the cold yellow hand

05:20:36.593 --> 05:20:45.153
du souplice encore mal levé, with its downy red hairs and its doigt de faim. He glanced

05:20:45.153 --> 05:20:51.473
at his own white taper fingers and passed on, till he came to those lovely verses upon

05:20:51.473 --> 05:20:52.033
Venice.

05:20:53.413 --> 05:21:00.073
Sur une gamme chromatique les scènes des perles russelon lave-nous des lièdrettes

05:21:00.093 --> 05:21:10.133
de l'huile son corps rose et blanque. Le dôme, sur l'azur des ondes, soulevait la phrase

05:21:10.653 --> 05:21:19.513
à peu contour. C'est efflué comme des gores rondes que soulevait un soupir d'humour. Les

05:21:19.513 --> 05:21:27.253
squiffes à bord et de mes disposés jetant son amarde à pilier. Devant une façade rose

05:21:28.093 --> 05:21:38.693
sur les maubres d'une escalier. How exquisite they were! As one read them one seemed to

05:21:38.693 --> 05:21:45.633
be floating down the green waterways of the pink and pearl city, lying in a black gondola

05:21:45.633 --> 05:21:51.833
with silver prow and trailing curtains. The mere lines looked to him like those straight

05:21:51.833 --> 05:21:58.193
lines of turquoise-blue that follow as one pushes out to the lido. The sudden flashes

05:21:58.193 --> 05:22:03.573
of colour reminded him of the gleam of the opal and iris-throoted birds that flutter

05:22:03.573 --> 05:22:11.313
round the tall honeycomb campanal, or stalk, with such stately grace through the dim arcades.

05:22:12.613 --> 05:22:17.793
Leaning back with half-closed eyes, he kept saying over and over to himself,

05:22:18.633 --> 05:22:27.513
Devant une façade rose sur les maubres d'une escalier. The whole of Venice was in those

05:22:27.513 --> 05:22:34.193
two lines. He remembered the autumn that he had passed there, and a wonderful love that

05:22:34.193 --> 05:22:42.113
had stirred him to delightful, fantastic follies. There was romance in every place, but Venice,

05:22:42.573 --> 05:22:50.093
like Oxford, had kept the background for romance, and background was everything, or almost everything.

05:22:50.853 --> 05:22:56.613
Basil had been with him part of the time, and had gone wild over Tintorette. Poor Basil!

05:22:56.833 --> 05:22:58.853
What a horrible way for a man to die!

05:22:59.433 --> 05:23:05.413
He sighed, and took up the book again, and tried to forget. He read of the swallows that

05:23:05.413 --> 05:23:11.573
fly in and out of the little cafe at Smyrna, where the hajis sit counting their amber beans

05:23:11.573 --> 05:23:16.993
and their turbaned merchants smoke their long, tasseled pipes, and talk gravely to

05:23:16.993 --> 05:23:24.113
each other, of the obelisk in the Palace de la Concorde, that weeps tears of granite in

05:23:24.113 --> 05:23:31.033
its lonely, sunless exile, and longs to be back by the hot, lotus-covered Nile, where

05:23:31.033 --> 05:23:38.113
there are sphinxes and rose-red ibises and white vultures with gilded claws and crocodiles,

05:23:38.113 --> 05:23:45.293
with small barrel-eyes that crawl over the green steaming mud, and of that curious statue

05:23:45.293 --> 05:23:55.553
that Gautier compares to a contralto voice, the monstre charmant that couches in the porphyry

05:23:55.553 --> 05:23:57.033
room at the Louvre.

05:23:57.973 --> 05:24:02.753
But after a time the book fell from his hand, he grew nervous, and a horrible fit of terror

05:24:02.753 --> 05:24:09.353
came over him. What if Alan Campbell should be out of England? Days would elapse before

05:24:09.353 --> 05:24:14.733
he could come back. Perhaps he might refuse to come. What could he do then? Every moment

05:24:14.733 --> 05:24:16.513
was of vital importance.

05:24:18.893 --> 05:24:25.133
They had been great friends once, five years before, almost inseparable indeed. Then the

05:24:25.133 --> 05:24:32.733
intimacy had come suddenly to an end. When they met in society now, it was only during

05:24:32.733 --> 05:24:36.473
Grey who smiled. Alan Campbell never did.

05:24:38.233 --> 05:24:44.093
He was an extremely clever young man, though he had no real appreciation of the visible

05:24:44.093 --> 05:24:49.573
arts, and whatever little sense of beauty of poetry he possessed he had gained entirely

05:24:49.573 --> 05:24:56.293
from Dorian. His dominant intellectual passion was for science. At Cambridge he had spent

05:24:56.293 --> 05:25:03.793
a great deal of time working in the laboratory, and had taken a good class in the Natural

05:25:03.793 --> 05:25:10.593
Science Tripos of his year. Indeed, he was still devoted to the study of chemistry, and

05:25:10.593 --> 05:25:16.653
had a laboratory of his own, in which he used to shut himself up all day long, greatly to

05:25:16.653 --> 05:25:21.693
the annoyance of his mother, who had set her heart on his standing for Parliament, and

05:25:21.693 --> 05:25:27.293
had a vague idea that a chemist was a person who made up prescriptions. He was an excellent

05:25:27.293 --> 05:25:32.573
musician, however, as well, and played both the violin and the piano better than most

05:25:32.573 --> 05:25:38.993
amateurs. In fact, it was music that had first brought him and Dorian Grey together, music

05:25:38.993 --> 05:25:44.053
and the indefinable attraction that Dorian seemed to be able to exercise whenever he

05:25:44.053 --> 05:25:48.393
wished, and indeed exercised often without being conscious of it.

05:25:48.393 --> 05:25:53.613
They had met at Lady Berkshire's the night Rubenstein had played there, and after that

05:25:53.613 --> 05:25:59.913
used to be always seen together at the opera, and wherever good music was going on. For

05:25:59.913 --> 05:26:06.173
eighteen months their intimacy lasted. Campbell was always either at Selby Royal or in Grosvenor

05:26:06.173 --> 05:26:12.853
Square. To him, as to many others, Dorian Grey was the type of everything that is wonderful

05:26:12.853 --> 05:26:18.913
and fascinating in life. Whether or not a quarrel had taken place between them no one

05:26:18.913 --> 05:26:24.973
ever knew, but suddenly people remarked that they scarcely spoke when they met, and that

05:26:24.973 --> 05:26:30.413
Campbell seemed always to go away early from any party at which Dorian Grey was present.

05:26:31.293 --> 05:26:36.953
He had changed too, was strangely melancholy at times, appeared almost to dislike hearing

05:26:36.953 --> 05:26:43.513
music of any passionate character, and would never himself play, giving as an excuse when

05:26:43.513 --> 05:26:48.793
he was called upon that he was so absorbed in science that he had no time left to practice.

05:26:49.413 --> 05:26:54.093
And this was certainly true, every day he seemed to become more interested in biology,

05:26:54.653 --> 05:27:00.533
and his name appeared once or twice in some of the scientific reviews in connection with

05:27:00.533 --> 05:27:06.753
certain curious experiments. This was the man that Dorian Grey was waiting for, pacing

05:27:06.753 --> 05:27:12.293
up and down the room, glancing every moment of the clock, and becoming horribly agitated

05:27:12.293 --> 05:27:17.073
as the minutes went by. At last the door opened, and his servant entered.

05:27:19.253 --> 05:27:25.973
"'Mr. Alan Campbell, sir.' A sigh of relief broke from his parched lips, and the colour

05:27:25.973 --> 05:27:32.293
came back to his cheeks. Ask him to come in at once, Francis.' The man bowed and retired.

05:27:32.293 --> 05:27:39.573
In a few moments Alan Campbell walked in, looking very stern and rather pale, his pallor

05:27:39.573 --> 05:27:43.893
being intensified by his cold, black hair and dark eyebrows.

05:27:44.473 --> 05:27:48.813
"'Alan, this is good of you. I thank you for coming.'

05:27:48.813 --> 05:27:55.073
"'I had intended never to enter your house again, Grey. But you said it was a matter

05:27:55.073 --> 05:28:01.913
of life and death.' His voice was hard and cold. He spoke with slow deliberation.

05:28:02.593 --> 05:28:07.093
There was a look of contempt in the steady searching gaze that he turned upon Dorian.

05:28:08.333 --> 05:28:13.713
He kept his hands in the pockets of his Astrakhan coat, and appeared not to have noticed the

05:28:13.713 --> 05:28:16.053
gesture with which he had been greeted.

05:28:16.753 --> 05:28:22.413
"'It is a matter of life and death, Alan. And to more than one person, sit down.'

05:28:22.413 --> 05:28:28.613
Campbell took a chair by the table, and Dorian sat opposite to him. The two men's eyes met.

05:28:29.173 --> 05:28:35.213
In Dorian there was infinite pity. He knew that what he was going to do was dreadful.

05:28:36.633 --> 05:28:41.953
After a strained moment of silence he leaned across and said very quietly, but watching

05:28:41.953 --> 05:28:45.713
the effect of each word upon the face of the man he had sent for,

05:28:47.773 --> 05:28:53.453
"'Alan, in a locked room at the top of this house, a room to which nobody but myself has

05:28:53.453 --> 05:29:00.953
access. A dead man is seated at a table. He has been dead ten hours now. Don't stir,

05:29:01.493 --> 05:29:06.853
and don't look at me like that. Who the man is, why he died, how he died, are matters

05:29:06.853 --> 05:29:13.013
that do not concern you. What you have to do is this. Stop, Grey. I don't want to know

05:29:13.013 --> 05:29:20.273
anything further. Whether what you have told me is true or not true doesn't concern me.

05:29:20.973 --> 05:29:26.673
I entirely decline to be mixed up in your life. Keep your horrible secrets to yourself.

05:29:27.093 --> 05:29:35.093
They don't interest me any more. No, Alan, they will have to interest you. This one will

05:29:35.093 --> 05:29:42.453
have to interest you. I am awfully sorry for you, Alan, but I can't help myself. You are

05:29:42.453 --> 05:29:48.753
the one man who is able to save me. I am forced to bring you into the matter. I have no option.

05:29:49.273 --> 05:29:53.293
Alan, you are a scientist. You know about chemistry and things of that kind. You have

05:29:53.293 --> 05:29:58.353
made experiments. What you have got to do is destroy the thing that is upstairs, to

05:29:58.353 --> 05:30:03.653
destroy it so that not a vestige will be left of it. Nobody saw this person come into the

05:30:03.653 --> 05:30:08.293
house. Indeed, at the present moment he is supposed to be in Paris. He will not be missed

05:30:08.293 --> 05:30:13.793
for months. When he is missed there must be no trace of him found here. You, Alan, you

05:30:13.793 --> 05:30:18.573
must change him, and everything that belongs to him, into a handful of ashes, that I may

05:30:18.573 --> 05:30:28.953
scatter in the air. You are mad, Dorian. I was waiting for you to call me Dorian. You

05:30:28.953 --> 05:30:35.293
are mad, I tell you, mad to imagine that I would raise a finger to help you, mad to make

05:30:35.293 --> 05:30:43.113
this monstrous confession. I will have nothing to do with this matter, whatever it is. Do

05:30:43.113 --> 05:30:49.013
you think I am going to peril my reputation for you? What is it to me what devil's work

05:30:49.013 --> 05:30:57.313
you are up to? It was a suicide, Alan. I am glad of that. But who drove him to it? You,

05:30:57.333 --> 05:31:05.493
I should fancy. Do you still refuse to do this for me? Of course I refuse. I will have

05:31:05.493 --> 05:31:09.913
absolutely nothing to do with it. I don't care what shame comes upon you. You deserve

05:31:09.913 --> 05:31:16.933
it all. I should not be sorry to see you disgraced, publicly disgraced. How dare you

05:31:16.933 --> 05:31:23.973
ask me of all men in the world to mix myself up in this horror. I should have thought you

05:31:24.293 --> 05:31:29.113
knew more about people's characters. Your friend Lord Henry Wooten can't have taught

05:31:29.113 --> 05:31:35.053
you much about psychology, whatever else he has taught you. Nothing will induce me to

05:31:35.053 --> 05:31:42.113
a step to help you. You have come to the wrong man. Go to some of your friends. Don't come

05:31:42.113 --> 05:31:49.913
to me. Alan, it was murder. I killed him. You don't know what he made me suffer. Whatever

05:31:49.913 --> 05:31:55.133
my life is, he had more to do with the making or the marring of it than poor Harry has had.

05:31:55.713 --> 05:32:04.373
He may have not intended it, but the result is the same. Murder! Good God, Dorian! Is

05:32:04.373 --> 05:32:10.353
that what you have come to? I shall not inform upon you. It is not my business. Besides,

05:32:11.033 --> 05:32:16.333
you are certain to be arrested, without my stirring in the matter. Nobody ever commits

05:32:16.333 --> 05:32:24.733
a murder without doing something stupid. But I will have nothing to do with it. All I ask

05:32:24.733 --> 05:32:31.613
of you is to perform a certain scientific experiment. You go to hospitals and dead houses,

05:32:31.613 --> 05:32:37.813
and the horrors that you do there don't affect you. If in some hideous dissecting room or

05:32:37.813 --> 05:32:42.713
fetid laboratory you found this man lying on a leaden table with red gutters scooped

05:32:42.713 --> 05:32:48.233
out in it, you would simply look upon him as an admirable subject. You would not turn

05:32:48.233 --> 05:32:54.213
a hair. You would not believe that you were doing anything wrong. On the contrary, you

05:32:54.213 --> 05:32:59.093
would probably feel that you were benefiting the human race, or increasing the sum of knowledge

05:32:59.093 --> 05:33:05.973
in the world, or gratifying intellectual curiosity, or something of that kind. What I want you

05:33:05.973 --> 05:33:12.993
to do is simply what you have often done before. Indeed, to destroy a body must be less horrible

05:33:13.653 --> 05:33:19.533
than what you are accustomed to work at. And remember, it is the only piece of evidence

05:33:19.533 --> 05:33:27.433
against me. If it is discovered, I am lost, and it is sure to be discovered unless you

05:33:27.433 --> 05:33:37.313
help me. I have no desire to help you. You forget that. I am simply indifferent to the

05:33:37.313 --> 05:33:43.273
whole thing. It has nothing to do with me. Alan, I entreat you. Think of the position

05:33:43.273 --> 05:33:50.953
I am in. Just before you came I almost fainted with terror. No, don't think of that. Look

05:33:51.503 --> 05:33:57.553
at the matter purely from the scientific point of view. You don't inquire where the dead

05:33:57.553 --> 05:34:03.053
things on which you experiment come from. Don't inquire now. I have told you too much

05:34:03.053 --> 05:34:11.573
as it is, but I beg of you to do this. We were once friends, Alan. Don't speak of those

05:34:11.573 --> 05:34:18.153
days, Dorian. They are dead. The dead linger sometimes. The man upstairs will not go away.

05:34:18.453 --> 05:34:25.613
He is sitting at the table with a bowed head and outstretched arms. Alan, if you don't

05:34:25.613 --> 05:34:31.273
come to my assistance, I am ruined. Why, they will hang me, Alan. Don't you understand?

05:34:31.293 --> 05:34:37.193
They will hang me for what I have done. There is no good in prolonging this scene. I refuse

05:34:37.193 --> 05:34:45.513
absolutely to do anything in the matter. It is insane of you to ask me. You refuse? Absolutely?

05:34:46.993 --> 05:34:47.513
Yes.

05:34:48.773 --> 05:34:53.993
The same look of pity came into Dorian's eyes. Then he stretched out his hand, took a piece

05:34:53.993 --> 05:34:58.953
of paper and wrote something on it. He read it over twice, folded it carefully and pushed

05:34:58.953 --> 05:35:06.333
it across the table. Having done this he got up and went over to the window. Campbell looked

05:35:06.333 --> 05:35:13.353
at him in surprise and then took up the paper and opened it. As he read it his face became

05:35:13.353 --> 05:35:20.873
ghastly pale and he fell back in his chair. A horrible sense of sickness came over him.

05:35:21.753 --> 05:35:29.093
He felt as if his heart was beating itself to death in some empty hollow. After two or

05:35:29.093 --> 05:35:34.853
three minutes of terrible silence Dorian turned around and came and stood behind him, putting

05:35:34.853 --> 05:35:36.513
his hand upon his shoulder.

05:35:37.573 --> 05:35:46.433
"'I am so sorry, Alan,' he murmured, "'but you leave me no alternative. I have a letter

05:35:46.433 --> 05:35:53.673
written already. Here it is. You see the address? If you don't help me I must send it. You know

05:35:53.673 --> 05:36:00.333
what the result will be. But you are going to help me. It is impossible for you to refuse

05:36:00.333 --> 05:36:07.393
now. I tried to spare you. You will do me the justice to admit that. You were stern,

05:36:08.093 --> 05:36:17.213
harsh, offensive. You treated me as no man has ever dared to treat me, no living man

05:36:17.213 --> 05:36:24.193
at any rate. I bore it all. Now it is for me to dictate the terms.'

05:36:24.193 --> 05:36:27.993
Campbell buried his face in his hands and a shudder passed through him.

05:36:27.993 --> 05:36:34.053
"'Yes, it is my turn to dictate terms, Alan. You know what they are. The thing is quite

05:36:34.053 --> 05:36:41.873
simple. Um, don't work yourself into this fever. This thing has to be done. Face it

05:36:41.873 --> 05:36:44.573
and do it.'

05:36:44.573 --> 05:36:51.313
A groan broke from Campbell's lips and he shivered all over. The ticking of the clock

05:36:51.313 --> 05:36:57.773
on the mantelpiece seemed to him to be dividing time into separate atoms of agony, each of

05:36:57.773 --> 05:37:04.773
which was too terrible to be borne. He felt as if an iron ring was being slowly tightened

05:37:04.773 --> 05:37:11.633
round his forehead, and as if the disgrace with which he was threatened had already come

05:37:11.633 --> 05:37:19.613
upon him. The hand upon his shoulder weighed like a hand of lead. It was intolerable. It

05:37:19.613 --> 05:37:21.373
seemed to crush him.

05:37:23.353 --> 05:37:30.053
"'Come, Alan. You must decide at once.' He hesitated for a moment.

05:37:31.473 --> 05:37:36.413
"'Is there a fire in the room upstairs?' he murmured.

05:37:37.273 --> 05:37:40.733
"'Yes. There is a gas-fire with asbestos.'

05:37:42.773 --> 05:37:46.733
"'I will have to go home and get some things from the laboratory.'

05:37:47.633 --> 05:37:53.793
"'No, Alan. You need not leave the house. Write on a sheet of note-paper what you want

05:37:53.793 --> 05:37:59.933
and my servant will take a cab and bring the things back to you.'

05:37:59.933 --> 05:38:06.533
Campbell wrote a few lines, blotted them and addressed an envelope to his assistant. Dorian

05:38:06.533 --> 05:38:11.533
took the note up and read it carefully. Then he rang the bell and gave it to his valet

05:38:11.533 --> 05:38:16.653
with orders to return as soon as possible and to bring the things with him. When the

05:38:16.653 --> 05:38:22.993
all doors shut, Campbell started, and having got up from the chair, went over to the chimney-piece.

05:38:24.033 --> 05:38:30.533
He was shivering with a sort of ague. For nearly twenty minutes neither of the men spoke.

05:38:31.693 --> 05:38:38.193
A fly buzzed noisily about the room, and the ticking of the clock was like a beat of a

05:38:38.193 --> 05:38:38.553
hammer.

05:38:40.193 --> 05:38:46.173
As the chimes struck one, Campbell turned around and, looking at Dorian Gray, saw that

05:38:46.173 --> 05:38:52.133
his eyes were filled with tears. There was something in the purity and refinement of

05:38:52.133 --> 05:38:54.973
that sad face that seemed to enrage him.

05:38:56.033 --> 05:39:02.593
"'You are infamous, absolutely infamous,' he muttered.

05:39:03.373 --> 05:39:09.293
"'Hush, Alan. You have saved my life,' said Dorian.

05:39:10.093 --> 05:39:16.613
"'Your life? Heavens, what a life that is! You have gone from corruption to corruption,

05:39:16.633 --> 05:39:23.613
and now you have culminated in crime. In doing what I am going to do, what you force me to

05:39:23.613 --> 05:39:28.513
do, it is not your life that I am thinking.'

05:39:30.133 --> 05:39:33.033
"'Oh, Alan,' murmured Dorian with a sigh.

05:39:33.733 --> 05:39:40.113
"'I wish you had a thousandth part of the pity for me that I have for you.'

05:39:40.113 --> 05:39:46.353
He turned away as he spoke, and stood looking out at the garden. Campbell made no answer.

05:39:47.153 --> 05:39:51.953
After about ten minutes a knock came to the door, and the servant entered carrying a mahogany

05:39:51.953 --> 05:39:59.413
chest of chemicals with a small electric battery set on top of it. He placed it on the table

05:39:59.413 --> 05:40:04.813
and went out again, returning with a long coil of steel and platinum wire and two rather

05:40:04.813 --> 05:40:07.053
curiously shaped iron clamps.

05:40:10.893 --> 05:40:14.673
"'Shall I leave the things here, sir?' he asked Campbell.

05:40:16.293 --> 05:40:21.433
"'Yes,' said Dorian. "'And I am afraid, Francis, that I have another errand for you. What is

05:40:21.433 --> 05:40:25.573
the name of the man at Richmond who supplies Selby with orchids?'

05:40:26.093 --> 05:40:32.553
"'Harden, sir. Yes, Hardin. He must go down to Richmond at once, see Hardin personally,

05:40:32.913 --> 05:40:38.193
and tell him to send twice as many orchids as I ordered, and to have as few white ones

05:40:38.193 --> 05:40:44.413
as possible. In fact, I don't want any white ones. It is a lovely day, Francis, and Richmond

05:40:44.413 --> 05:40:48.193
is a very pretty place. Otherwise I wouldn't bother you about it.'

05:40:48.193 --> 05:40:52.673
"'No trouble, sir. And what time shall I be back?'

05:40:53.513 --> 05:40:54.593
Dorian looked at Campbell.

05:40:55.213 --> 05:41:00.533
"'How long will your experiment take, Alan?' he said in a calm and different voice. The

05:41:00.533 --> 05:41:06.093
presence of a third person in the room seemed to give him extraordinary courage. Campbell

05:41:06.093 --> 05:41:07.733
frowned and bit his lip.

05:41:08.753 --> 05:41:12.533
"'It will take about five hours,' he answered.

05:41:13.493 --> 05:41:18.633
"'It will be time enough, then, if you are back at half-past seven, Francis. Or stay.

05:41:18.633 --> 05:41:24.933
"'Just leave my things out for dressing. You can have the evening to yourself. I am

05:41:24.933 --> 05:41:27.653
not dining at home, so I shall not want you.'

05:41:27.653 --> 05:41:30.933
"'Thank you, sir,' said the man, leaving the room.

05:41:31.493 --> 05:41:37.973
"'Now, Alan, there is not a moment to be lost. How heavy this chest is! I'll take

05:41:37.973 --> 05:41:43.573
it for you. You bring the other things.' He spoke rapidly and in an authoritative manner.

05:41:44.253 --> 05:41:49.473
Campbell felt dominated by him. They left the room together. When they reached the top

05:41:49.473 --> 05:41:55.253
landing, Dorian took out the key and turned it in the lock. Then he stopped, and a troubled

05:41:55.253 --> 05:41:58.653
look came into his eyes. He shuddered.

05:42:00.033 --> 05:42:03.693
"'I don't think I can go in, Alan,' he murmured.

05:42:04.013 --> 05:42:11.113
"'It is nothing to me. I don't require you,' said Campbell, coldly. Dorian half opened

05:42:11.113 --> 05:42:17.133
the door. As he did so, he saw the face of the portrait, grinning in the sunlight. On

05:42:17.133 --> 05:42:22.333
the floor in front of it the torn curtain was lying. He remembered that the night before,

05:42:22.373 --> 05:42:28.093
for the first time in his life, he had forgotten to hide it when he crept out of the room.

05:42:30.273 --> 05:42:36.353
But what was that loathsome red dew that gleamed, wet, and glistening on one of the hands, as

05:42:36.353 --> 05:42:43.113
though the canvas had sweated blood? How horrible it was! More horrible, it seemed to him for

05:42:43.113 --> 05:42:47.913
the moment, than the silent thing that he knew was stretched across the table. The thing

05:42:47.913 --> 05:42:53.953
whose grotesque, misshapen shadow on the spotted carpet showed him that it had not stirred,

05:42:54.693 --> 05:42:57.813
but was still there as he left it.

05:42:59.353 --> 05:43:04.793
He opened the door a little wider and walked quickly in, with half-closed eyes and an averted

05:43:04.793 --> 05:43:11.493
head, determined that he would not look even once upon the dead man. Then, stooping down

05:43:11.493 --> 05:43:17.073
and taking up the gold and purple hanging, he flung it over the picture. He stopped,

05:43:17.393 --> 05:43:21.913
feeling afraid to turn round, and his eyes fixed themselves on the intricacies of the

05:43:21.913 --> 05:43:28.273
pattern before him. He heard Campbell bringing in the heavy chest and the irons and the other

05:43:28.273 --> 05:43:34.473
things that he had required for his dreadful work. He began to wonder if he and Basil Hallward

05:43:34.473 --> 05:43:39.053
had ever met, and if so, what they had thought of each other.

05:43:39.693 --> 05:43:41.913
"'Leave me now,' said Campbell.

05:43:43.673 --> 05:43:49.613
He turned and hurried out, just as conscious that the dead man had been thrust back into

05:43:49.613 --> 05:43:55.693
the chair and was sitting in it, with Campbell gazing into the glistening yellow face. As

05:43:55.693 --> 05:43:59.653
he was going downstairs he heard the key being turned in the lock.

05:44:01.173 --> 05:44:07.473
"'It was long after seven o'clock when Campbell came back into the library. He was pale, but

05:44:07.473 --> 05:44:09.733
absolutely calm.'

05:44:09.733 --> 05:44:17.453
"'I have done what you asked me to do,' he muttered, and now good-bye. Let us never see

05:44:17.453 --> 05:44:19.053
each other again.'

05:44:19.973 --> 05:44:22.553
"'You have saved me from ruin, Ellen.'

05:44:22.553 --> 05:44:29.313
"'I cannot forget that,' said Dorian simply. As soon as Campbell had left he went upstairs.

05:44:29.313 --> 05:44:36.693
There was a horrible smell of chemicals in the room, but the thing that had been sitting

05:44:36.693 --> 05:44:39.713
at the table was gone.'

05:45:01.307 --> 05:45:06.907
The Picture of Dorian Gray by Oscar Wilde

05:45:07.487 --> 05:45:10.347
As recorded by John Gonzales

05:45:10.347 --> 05:45:15.167
www.jongon.com

05:45:21.627 --> 05:45:36.727
There is no good way telling me you are going to be good, Dorian, cried Lord Henry, dipping his white fingers into the red copper bowl filled with rose water. You are quite perfect. Pray don't change.

05:45:37.687 --> 05:45:39.087
Dorian shook his head.

05:45:39.947 --> 05:45:51.467
No, Harry. I have done too many dreadful things in my life. I am not going to do any more. I began my good actions yesterday. Where were you yesterday?

05:45:52.067 --> 05:45:56.167
In the country, Harry. I was staying at a little inn by myself.

05:45:56.167 --> 05:46:24.687
My dear boy, said Lord Henry, smiling, anybody can do good in the country. There are no temptations there. That is the reason why people who live out of town are so uncivilized. There are only two ways, as you know, of becoming civilized. One is by being cultured. The other is by being corrupt. Country people have no opportunity of being either, so they stagnate.

05:46:25.867 --> 05:46:28.967
Culture and corruption, remembered Dorian.

05:46:29.847 --> 05:46:50.587
I have known something of both. It seems to me curious now that they should ever be found together. For I have a new ideal, Harry. I am going to alter. I think I have altered. You have not told me what your good action was, or did you say you had done more than one?

05:46:51.547 --> 05:47:15.267
I can tell you, Harry. It is not a story I could tell to anyone else. I spared somebody. It sounds vain, but you understand what I mean. She was quite beautiful, and wonderfully like Sybil Vane. I think it was that which first attracted me to her. You remember Sybil, don't you? How long ago that seems?

05:47:16.047 --> 05:47:43.387
Well, Hetty was not one of our own class, of course. She was simply a girl in a village, but I really loved her. I am quite sure that I loved her. All during this wonderful May that we have been having, I used to run down and see her two or three times a week. Yesterday she met me in a little orchard. The apple blossoms kept tumbling down on her hair, and she was laughing.

05:47:44.527 --> 05:47:52.967
We were to have gone away together this morning at dawn. Suddenly I determined to leave her as flowerlike as I had found her.

05:47:54.127 --> 05:48:10.427
I should think the novelty of the emotion must have given you a thrill of real pleasure, Dorian, interrupted Lord Henry. But I can finish your idol for you. You gave her good advice and broke her heart. That was the beginning of your reformation.

05:48:11.527 --> 05:48:25.227
Harry, you are horrible. You mustn't say these dreadful things. Hetty's heart is not broken. Of course she cried and all that, but there is no disgrace upon her. She can live like Perdita in her garden.

05:48:26.127 --> 05:48:43.307
And weep over a faithless Florizel, said Lord Henry, laughing. My dear Dorian, you have the most curious boyish moods. Do you think this girl will ever be really contented now with any one of her own rank?

05:48:43.307 --> 05:49:06.447
I suppose she will be married some day to a rough carter or a grinning ploughman. Well, having met you and loved you, we'll teach her to despise her husband, and she will be wretched. From a moral point of view, I don't really think much of your great renunciation. Even as a beginning it is poor.

05:49:07.187 --> 05:49:17.167
Besides, how do you know that Hetty isn't floating at the present moment in some mill-pond, with water lilies round her head, like Ophelia?

05:49:18.087 --> 05:49:32.087
I can't bear this, Harry. You mock at everything and then suggest the most serious tragedies. I'm sorry I told you now. I don't care what you say to me. I know I was right in acting as I did. Poor Hetty!

05:49:32.647 --> 05:49:51.587
As I rode past the farm this morning I saw her white face at the window, like a spray of jasmine. Don't let me talk about it any more, and don't try to persuade me that the first good action I have done for years, the first little bit of self-sacrifice I have ever known, is really a sort of sin.

05:49:52.287 --> 05:50:05.907
I want to be better. I am going to be better. Tell me something about yourself. What is going on in town? I have not been to the club for days.

05:50:07.427 --> 05:50:11.207
The people are still discussing poor Basil's disappearance.

05:50:12.267 --> 05:50:28.447
I should have thought they had got tired of that by this time, said Dorian, pouring himself out some wine and frowning slightly. My dear boy, they have only been talking about it for six weeks, and the public are not really equal to the mental strain of having more than one topic every three months.

05:50:29.147 --> 05:50:53.787
They have been very fortunate lately, however. They have had my own divorce case, and Alan Campbell's suicide. Now they have got the mysterious disappearance of an artist. Scotland Yard still insists that the man in the grey Ulster who left Victoria by the midnight train on the 7th of November was poor Basil, and French police declare that Basil never arrived in Paris at all.

05:50:54.547 --> 05:51:14.727
I suppose, in about a fortnight, we will be told that he has been seen in San Francisco. It is an odd thing, but every one who disappears is said to be seen at San Francisco. It must be a delightful city, and possess all the attractions of the next world.

05:51:16.287 --> 05:51:26.747
What do you think has happened to Basil?" asked Dorian, holding up his burgundy against the light, and wondering how it was that he could discuss the matter so calmly.

05:51:27.307 --> 05:51:55.007
I have not the slightest idea. If Basil chooses to hide himself, it is no business of mine. If he is dead—I don't want to think about him. Death is the only thing that ever terrifies me. I hate it. One can survive everything nowadays except that. Death and vulgarity are the only two facts in the nineteenth century that one cannot explain away. Let us have our coffee in the music-room, Dorian.

05:51:55.007 --> 05:52:09.307
You must play Chopin for me. The man with whom my wife ran away played Chopin exquisitely. Poor Victoria was very fond of her. The house is rather lonely without her.

05:52:10.407 --> 05:52:25.267
Dorian said nothing, but rose from the table and, passing into the next room, sat down to the piano and let his fingers stray across the keys. After the coffee had been brought in, he stopped, and, looking over at Lord Henry, said,

05:52:26.167 --> 05:52:54.307
"'Harry, did it ever occur to you that Basil was murdered?' Lord Henry yawned. Basil had no enemies, and always wore a water-berry watch. Why should he be murdered? He was not clever enough to have enemies. Of course, he had a wonderful genius for painting, but a man can paint like Velazquez, and yet be as dull as possible.

05:52:54.307 --> 05:53:03.307
Basil was really rather dull. He only interested me once, and that was when he told me years ago that he had a wild adoration for you."

05:53:04.167 --> 05:53:22.327
"'I was very fond of Basil,' said Dorian, with a sad look in his eyes. But don't people say that he was murdered? Oh, some of the papers do. It does not seem to be probable. I know there are dreadful places in Paris, but Basil was not the sort of man to have gone to them.

05:53:22.327 --> 05:53:47.007
He had no curiosity. It was his chief defect. Play me a nocturne, Dorian, and as you play, tell me, in a low voice, how you have kept your youth. You must have some secret. I am only ten years older than you are, and I am wrinkled and bald and yellow. You are really wonderful, Dorian. You have never looked more charming than you do to-night.

05:53:47.507 --> 05:54:12.107
You remind me of the day I saw you first. You are rather cheeky, very shy, and absolutely extraordinary. You have changed, of course, but not in appearance. I wish you would tell me your secret. To get back my youth, I would do anything in the world, except take exercise, get up early, or be respectable. Youth, there is nothing like it.

05:54:12.107 --> 05:54:34.447
It's absurd to talk of the ignorance of youth. The only people whose opinions I listen to now, with any respect, are people much younger than myself. They seem in front of me. Life has revealed to them her last wonder, as for the aged. I always contradict the aged. I do it on principle.

05:54:34.447 --> 05:55:03.487
If you ask them their opinion on something that happened yesterday, they suddenly give you their opinions current in 1820, when people wore high stocks and knew absolutely nothing. How wonderful that thing you are playing is! I wonder, did Chopin write it in Majorca, with the sea weeping around the villa, and the spray salt dashing against the panes? This is marvellously romantic.

05:55:04.567 --> 05:55:30.307
What a blessing it is that there is one art left to us that is not imitative. No, don't stop. I want music tonight. It seems to me that you are the young Apollo, and I am the young Marcius listening to you. I have sorrows, Dorian, of my own, that even you know nothing of. The tragedy of old age is not that one is old, but that one is young.

05:55:31.067 --> 05:55:55.787
I am amazed sometimes at my own sincerity. Ah, Dorian, how happy you are! What an exquisite life you have had! You have drunk deeply of everything. You have crushed the grapes against your palate. Nothing has been hidden from you. But it has all been to you no more than the sound of music. It has not marred you. You are still the same.

05:55:57.167 --> 05:56:13.947
I wonder what the rest of your life will be, not spoiled by renunciations. At present you are the perfect type. Don't make yourself incomplete. You are quite flawless now. You need not shake your head. You know you are.

05:56:13.947 --> 05:56:30.247
Besides, Dorian, don't deceive yourself. Life is not governed by will or intention. Life is a question of nerves and fibres and slowly built up cells in which thought hides itself and passion has its own dreams.

05:56:30.847 --> 05:56:53.247
You may fancy yourself safe and think yourself strong, but a chanced tone of colour in a room or a morning sky, a particular perfume that you had once loved and that brings strange memories with it, a line from a forgotten poem that you would come across again, a cadence from a piece of music that you would cease to play.

05:56:53.247 --> 05:57:16.507
I tell you, Dorian, that it is on things like these that our lives depend. Browning writes about that somewhere, but our own senses will imagine them for us. There are moments when the odour of heliotrope passes suddenly across me and I have to live the strangest year of my life over again.

05:57:17.507 --> 05:57:37.567
I wish I could change places with you, Dorian. The world has cried out against us both, but it has always worshipped you. It always will worship you. You are the type of what the age is searching for and what it is afraid it has found.

05:57:37.567 --> 05:57:57.647
I am so glad that you have never done anything, never carved a statue or painted a picture or produced anything outside of yourself. Life has been your art. You have set yourself to music. Your days have been your sonnets.

05:57:59.327 --> 05:58:02.867
Dorian rose from the piano and passed his hand through his hair.

05:58:02.867 --> 05:58:24.667
Yes, life has been exquisite, he murmured. But I'm not going to have the same life, Harry. And you must not say these extravagant things to me. You don't know everything about me. I think that if you did, even you would turn for me. You laugh. Don't laugh.

05:58:24.667 --> 05:58:41.867
Why have you stopped playing, Dorian? Go back and play the nocturne over again. Look at that great honey-coloured moon that hangs in the dusky air. She's waiting for you to charm her. And if you play, she will come closer to the earth.

05:58:42.867 --> 05:58:44.527
You won't?

05:58:45.287 --> 05:59:06.387
Let us go to the club, then. It has been a charming evening, and we must end it charmingly. There is someone who wants immensely to know you. Young Lord Poole, Bournemouth's eldest son. He has already copied your neck-ties, and has begged me to introduce him to you. He is quite delightful, and rather reminds me of you."

05:59:06.387 --> 05:59:11.667
I hope not," said Dorian, with a touch of pathos in his voice.

05:59:12.847 --> 05:59:22.127
But I am tired to-night, Harry. I won't go to the club. It is nearly eleven, and I want to go to bed early.

05:59:43.927 --> 06:00:01.847
Don't change, Dorian. At any rate, don't change to me. We must always be friends. Yet you poisoned me with a book once. I should not forgive you that. Harry, promise me that you will never lend that book to anyone. It does harm.

06:00:03.407 --> 06:00:26.707
My dear boy, you will really be getting to moralise. You will soon be going about warning people against all the sins of which you have grown tired. You are much too delightful to do that. Besides, it is no use. You and I are what we are, and we'll be what we will be.

06:00:26.707 --> 06:00:38.167
Come round to-morrow. I am going to ride at eleven, and we might go together. The park is quite lovely now. I don't think there have been such lilacs since the year I met you.

06:00:39.327 --> 06:00:43.927
Very well. I will be here at eleven, said Dorian. Good night, Harry.

06:01:08.167 --> 06:01:10.327
He heard one of them whisper to the other,

06:01:11.407 --> 06:01:13.207
That is Dorian Gray.

06:01:14.387 --> 06:01:29.027
He remembered how pleased he used to be when he was pointed out, or stared out, or talked about. He was tired of hearing his own name now. Half the charm of the little village where he had been so often lately was that no one knew who he was.

06:01:29.927 --> 06:01:57.987
He had told the girl whom he had made love him that he was poor, and she had believed him. He had told her once that he was wicked, and she had laughed at him, and told him that wicked people were always very old and very ugly. What a laugh she had. Just like a thrush singing. And how pretty she had been in her cotton dresses and her large hats. She knew nothing. And she had everything that he had lost.

06:01:58.587 --> 06:02:12.027
When he reached home he found his servant waiting up for him. He sent him to bed and threw himself down on the sofa in the library, and began to think over some of the things that Lord Henry had said to him.

06:02:12.027 --> 06:02:16.607
Was it really true that one could never change?

06:02:16.607 --> 06:02:26.007
He felt a wild longing for the unstained purity of his boyhood, his rose-white boyhood, as Lord Henry had once called it.

06:02:26.007 --> 06:02:51.327
He knew that he had tarnished himself, filled his mind with corruption and given horror to his fancy, that he had been an evil influence to others and had experienced a terrible joy in being so, and that of the lives that had crossed his own it had been the fairest and most full of promise that he had brought to shame. But was it all irretrievable?

06:02:54.107 --> 06:02:56.767
Was there no hope for him?

06:02:58.167 --> 06:03:06.707
It was better not to think of the past. Nothing could alter that. It was of himself and of his own future that he had to think.

06:03:08.227 --> 06:03:33.947
Alan Campbell had shot himself one night in his laboratory, and had not revealed the secret that he had been forced to know. The excitement, such as it was over Basil Hallward's disappearance, would soon pass away. He was already waning. He was perfectly safe there. Nor, indeed, was it the death of Basil Hallward that weighed most upon his mind. It was the living death of his own soul that troubled him.

06:03:35.247 --> 06:04:03.127
Basil had painted the portrait that had marred his life. He could not forgive him that. It was the portrait that had done everything. Basil had said things to him that were unbearable, and that he had yet born with patience. The murder had been simply the madness of a moment. As for Alan Campbell, his suicide had been his own act. He had chosen to do it. It was nothing to him.

06:04:04.987 --> 06:04:22.007
A new life. That was what he wanted. That was what he was waiting for. Surely he had begun it already. He had spared one innocent thing at any rate. He would never again tempt innocence. He would be good.

06:04:23.207 --> 06:04:46.267
As he thought of Hetty Merton, he began to wonder if the portrait in the locked room had changed. Surely it was not still so horrible as it had been. Perhaps if his life became pure, he would be able to expel every sign of evil from the face. Perhaps the signs of evil had already gone away. He would go and look.

06:04:47.027 --> 06:05:08.287
He took the lamp from the table and crept upstairs. As he unlocked the door, a smile of joy flitted across his young face and lingered for a moment about his lips. Yes, he would be good, and the hideous thing that he had hidden away would no longer be a terror to him. He felt as if the load had been lifted from him already.

06:05:09.067 --> 06:05:22.447
He went in quietly, locking the door behind him as was his custom, and dragging the purple hanging from the portrait. A cry of pain and indignation broke from him. He could see no change.

06:05:23.147 --> 06:05:41.767
Unless that in the eyes there was a look of cunning and the mouth, the curved wrinkle of the hypocrite, the thing was still loathsome, more loathsome, if possible, than before, and the scarlet dew that spotted the hand seemed brighter and more like blood newly spilt.

06:05:42.767 --> 06:06:05.407
Had it been merely vanity that made him do his one good deed, or the desire of a new sensation as Lord Henry had hinted with his mocking laugh, or that passion to act apart that sometimes makes us do things finer than we are ourselves, or perhaps all these?

06:06:05.407 --> 06:06:21.947
Why was the red stain larger than it had been? It seemed to have crept like a horrible disease over the wrinkled fingers. There was blood on the painted feet as though the thing had dripped, blood even on the hand that had not held the knife.

06:06:23.527 --> 06:06:42.587
Confess? Did it mean that he was to confess, to give himself up and be put to death? He laughed. He felt that the idea was monstrous. Besides, who would believe him, even if he did confess? There was no trace of the murdered man anywhere. Everything belonged to him had been destroyed.

06:06:42.587 --> 06:07:09.147
He himself had burned what had been below stairs. The world would simply say he was mad. They would shut him up if he persisted in his story. Yet it was his duty to confess, to suffer public shame and to make public atonement. There was a God who called upon men to tell their sins to earth as well as to heaven. Nothing that he could do would cleanse him till he had told his own sin.

06:07:10.507 --> 06:07:37.507
His sin? He shrugged his shoulders. The death of Basil Hallward seemed very little to him. He was thinking of Hetty Merton. It was an unjust mirror, this mirror of his soul that he was looking at, vanity, curiosity, hypocrisy. Had there been nothing more in his renunciation than that? There had been something more, or at least he thought so, but who could tell?

06:07:38.167 --> 06:07:57.627
And this murder? Was it to dog him all his life? Was he never to get rid of the past? Was he really to confess? No. There was only one bit of evidence left against him. The picture itself.

06:08:00.807 --> 06:08:26.667
That was evidence. He would destroy it. Why had he kept it so long? It had given him pleasure, once, to watch it changing and growing old. Of late, he had felt no pleasure. It had kept him awake at night. When he had been away, he had been filled with terror lest other eyes should look upon it. It had brought melancholy across his passions.

06:08:26.667 --> 06:08:49.687
Its mere memory had marred many moments of joy. It had been like conscience to him. Yes, it had been conscience. He would destroy it. He looked around and saw the knife that had stabbed Basil Hallward. He had cleaned it many times, till there was no stain left upon it. It was bright and it glistened.

06:08:50.527 --> 06:09:08.447
As it had killed the painter, so it would kill the painter's work and all that that meant. It would kill the past, and when that was dead he would be free. He seized it and stabbed the canvas with it, ripping the thing right up from top to bottom.

06:09:09.647 --> 06:09:35.527
There was a crash heard and a cry. The cry was so horrible in its agony that the fighting servants woke and crept out of their rooms. Two gentlemen, who were passing in the square below, stopped and looked up at the great house. They walked on till they met a policeman and brought him back. The man rang the bell several times, but there was no answer. The house was all dark, except for a light in one of the top windows.

06:09:36.107 --> 06:09:40.587
After a time he went away and stood in the portico of the next house and watched.

06:09:41.687 --> 06:09:45.827
Whose house is that, constable?" asked the elder of two gentlemen.

06:09:46.507 --> 06:10:10.867
"'Mr. Dorian Gray, sir!' They looked at each other as they walked away and sneered. One of them was Sir Henry Ashton's uncle. Inside, in the servant's pot of the house, the half-clad domestics were talking in low whispers to each other. Old Mrs. Leaf was crying and wringing her hands. Francis was as pale as death.

06:10:10.867 --> 06:10:32.087
After about a quarter hour he got the coachman and one of the footmen and crept upstairs. They knocked, but there was no reply. They called out. Everything was still. Finally, after vainly trying to force the door, they got on the roof and dropped down onto the balcony. The windows yielded easily. The bolts were old.

06:10:32.087 --> 06:10:55.687
When they entered, they found hanging upon the wall a splendid portrait of their master as they had last seen him, in all the wonder of his exquisite youth and beauty. Lying on the floor was a dead man in evening dress with a knife in his heart. He was withered and wrinkled and loathsome of visage.

06:10:55.687 --> 06:11:04.107
It was not till they had examined the rings that they had recognized who it was.
